<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Estate Sale for Centenarian Sisters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT VERNON, N.Y. (AP) -- Lots of old ladies leave teacups  
behind. Sarah and Bessie Delany left about 200. 
</P>
<P>
	The centenarian sisters, who became famous for their  
best-selling memoir ``Having Our Say: The Delany Sisters' First 100 
Years,'' also left behind dentist tools, homemade soap, and a corn 
liquor still. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday it all went on sale, four months after Sarah's death  
at 109, and four years after Bessie's at 106. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a wonderful way to leave, sharing your legacy with people  
who admired you,'' said Pamela McIver of Yonkers, who had read the 
sisters' 1993 memoir. 
</P>
<P>
	The book is a colorful account of the sisters' upbringing in the  
South as the daughters of a freed slave, and their later lives as 
trailblazers for black professional women. The publication won them 
many fans, some of whom showed up at the auction for a bit of 
memorabilia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Miss Sadie,'' as Sarah was known, was New York's first black  
home economics teacher. ``Dr. Bessie'' was the state's second black 
female dentist. They lived their entire lives together, the last 38 
years in Mount Vernon. 
</P>
<P>
	McIver was among 100 or so people who had arrived at the estate  
Friday morning hoping to find a memento. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost a feeling of sacredness to share the experience,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many antique dealers arrived early and rushed from room to room  
seemingly unaware of the Delany history. 
</P>
<P>
	One dealer quickly claimed a $1,500 Harvard Dental Chest Bessie  
had used for her picks and mirrors. He left behind the $125 sign 
that said, ``Dr. Bessie Delany, Dentist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The still, which was used to make corn liquor, went for $35.  
Sarah's bed, an antique, went for $1,500; Bessie's for $75. 
</P>
<P>
	Some treasures had been winnowed out, including the sisters'  
diplomas, the investiture papers of their father, who was America's 
first elected black Episcopal bishop, a book inscribed to the 
Delanys by author James Weldon Johnson, whose books include 
``Autobiography of an Ex-coloured Man,'' family photos, letters, 
awards and travel diaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Those items will go to the Schomburg Center for Research in  
Black Culture in Harlem or to St. Augustine's College in Raleigh, 
N.C., where their father was a vice principal and where they grew 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	The house itself was left to two nephews and sold for just under  
$300,000; they also will get the $10,000 or so expected from this 
weekend's tag sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernadette Carey Smith, whose family was close to the Delanys  
and who was working at the tag sale, called the sale extremely 
emotional. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad but in a way good because there was no way anybody  
could keep all this stuff and it forced us to go through it and 
find what really should be saved,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
