<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaskan Homes Evacuated in Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOMER, Alaska (AP) -- More than 50 people were evacuated from  
their homes Friday as an out-of-control wildfire threatened to 
consume the structures. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire was burning among beetle-killed spruce trees east of  
Homer and destroyed one mobile home by Friday evening, according to 
Homer fire officials. 
</P>
<P>
	No injuries were reported, said Elaine Grabowski, the fire  
department's service coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Homer High School was opened as a shelter for people evacuated  
from the homes, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Flames are shooting up -- we can see them way over here,'' said  
Colleen Leavitt, a clerk at a resort located about 10 miles from 
the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Helicopters were dispatched from Soldotna and Anchorage, along  
with a plane from Palmer to drop fire retardant, said Bob Painter, 
Homer's assistant fire chief, 
</P>
<P>
	The wildfire started when a resident burning a brush pile lost  
control of his fire in high winds, Painter said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Homer area has been ravaged in recent years by the  
spruce-bark beetle. Large swathes of land are covered with dead, 
dry spruce trees that are an ideal fuel source for a wildland fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
