<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Narhi Wins NCAA Javelin Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Washington State's Bernard Lagat showed he's  
ready for his showdown against Arkansas' Seneca Lassiter in the 
1,500 meters at the NCAA Outdoor Track and Field Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The irrepressible Lagat held off Stanford's Brad Hauser to win  
the 5,000 Friday night at 14 minutes, 1.09 seconds, smashing the 
Bronco Stadium record at Boise State by more than 12 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Lagat, the first Washington State 5,000 champion since 1984 and  
the NCAA indoor mile winner, will face Lassiter, the two-time 
defending champion in the 1,500 on Saturday's final program. 
</P>
<P>
	Hauser's second-place finish, along with a fifth by his brother  
Brent and and an eighth by Jason Balkman, accounted for 13 points 
and gave Stanford the men's team lead with 45 points after 10 
events. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford, seeking its fourth title but its first since 1934,  
leads seven-time defending champion Arkansas and SMU by 22 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's team title race became a three-way battle among  
defending champion Texas, UCLA and Southern California. After 11 
events, the Longhorns had 31 points, and UCLA and Southern Cal had 
28 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, South Carolina's Terrence Trammell electrified the  
crowd of 7,124 with his brilliant speed. 
</P>
<P>
	Trammell ran the second leg of the Gamecocks' 400-meter relay  
that won its first title in the event in the meet's 78-year 
history. South Carolina was timed at 38.92, .01 off the stadium 
record, in beating Southern Cal by three meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Trammell, a sophomore, also had the fastest time in the  
semifinals of the 110 hurdles, 13.54, and advanced to Saturday's 
final in the 100, clocking 10.08 in his semifinal heat, behind the 
10.05 of Florida freshman John Capel. 
</P>
<P>
	Capel also won his 200 semifinal heat at a wind-aided 20.37.  
</P>
<P>
	Auburn's Coby Miller, Capel's big rival from the Southeastern  
Conference, won the other 200 semifinal at 20.37 and was second in 
his 100 semifinal at 10.12, behind defending champion Leonard 
Myles-Mills of BYU (10.08). 
</P>
<P>
	In other men's finals, Baylor's Bayano Kamani won the 400  
hurdles with a stadium record and 1999 collegiate and career-best 
48.68; indoor champion Derrick Peterson of Missouri took the 800 at 
1:46.97; indoor champion Jacob Davis of Texas won the pole vault at 
18-2 3/4, and UTEP's Matti Narhi took the javelin at 261-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas earned the women's lead with the help of a second  
consecutive victory in the 400 relay and second-place finishes by 
Tonja Jarrett in the 400 hurdles and Liz Diaz in the 800. 
</P>
<P>
	In the relay, freshman LaKeesha White put the Longhorns ahead  
with a strong third leg and LaKeisha Backus brought them home at 
42.95, a stadium record. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory set the tone for the Longhorns.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're the type of team where one event does well, the rest of  
them catch on fire,'' leadoff runner Kim McGruder said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 400 hurdles, UCLA's Joanna Hayes set a stadium record and  
ran the fastest time by a collegian this season in beating Jarrett, 
55.16 to 55.80. 
</P>
<P>
	It was vindication for Hayes, who couldn't compete in the 400  
hurdles last year because of a strained right hamstring. She 
hyperextended her right knee in winning her heat in 1997 and 
finished seventh in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	Hayes also qualified for Saturday's final in the 110 hurdles.  
</P>
<P>
	LSU's Claudine Williams took the lead with about 250 meters  
remaining in the 800 and held off Diaz's late charge to win by .06 
at 2:03.38. 
</P>
<P>
	Other women's winners included Baylor's Stacy Bowers in the  
triple jump at 45-1, Villanova's Carrie Tollefson in 3,000 at 
9:26.51 and Georgia's Vigdia Gudjonadotti in the javelin at 182-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia's Debbie Ferguson, the defending champion in the women's  
100 and 200, advanced to Saturday's finals in both events. So did 
Texas' Nanceen Perry, LSU's Peta-Gaye Dowdie, Southern Cal's Terri 
Edwards and Ball State's Latasha Jenkins. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Backus, counted upon to score for Texas in both  
sprints, failed to reach the final in either event. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State's Donica Merriman registered the season's fastest  
time by a collegian in the 100 hurdles, winning her semifinal heat 
at 12.84. 
</P>
<P>
	After the first four events of the heptathlon, favored Tracye  
Lawyer of Stanford led with 3,721 points. The final three events -- 
long jump, javelin and 800 -- will be contested Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
