<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polygamist Convicted of Incest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A member of a polygamist clan has been  
convicted of incest and unlawful sex with his 16-year-old niece in 
a case activists say signals an end to Utah's generally tolerant 
attitude toward plural marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	David Ortell Kingston was convicted Thursday in a trial that  
brought renewed attention to polygamy in Utah, where an estimated 
20,000 to 30,000 polygamists reside. 
</P>
<P>
	The conviction ``gives girls trapped in polygamy the hope that  
they can escape,'' said Laura Chapman, a founder of Tapestry of 
Polygamy, which opposes the practice. ``This says there is hope in 
the state of Utah.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The secretive Kingston clan has as many as 1,000 members and  
business assets worth up to $150 million. While the clan shares 
many of the beliefs of other polygamous groups in Utah, it stands 
apart in practicing incest, former members said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kingston, an accountant, faces up to five years in prison for  
each felony. 
</P>
<P>
	At trial, the girl, now 17, said that Kingston, 33, called her  
in October 1997 and suggested they marry. 
</P>
<P>
	She said her father performed the ceremony attended by  
Kingston's other wives. Her uncle later gave her a ring with 15 
diamonds, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the ceremony, they had four sexual encounters, all in  
1998, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, now in foster care, testified she continued to live at  
home and repeatedly tried to avoid her husband-uncle when she knew 
he was planning to visit. Defense lawyers said the wedding and sex 
never occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Kingston was not charged with polygamy, and there was limited  
discussion of the topic during the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	About 70 percent of Utah's population are members of The Church  
of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, which renounced polygamy in 
1890 after Congress passed tough anti-bigamy laws. Large-scale 
prosecution of polygamists has not taken place in Utah for more 
than four decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Brass, a Salt Lake City criminal defense attorney not  
affiliated with the case, doubted it was a bellwether. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen polygamy wax and wane as an issue here,'' he said.  
``I don't think legally it will be significant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Tapestry attorney Douglas White said Kingston's conviction  
shows Utah ``is not a polygamy-free zone anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a single prosecutor in the state who is not  
watching what's been done here,'' White said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
