<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Members To Boost Office Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conservative lawmakers trying to force  
spending cuts may have found a new target: bipartisan legislation 
that would boost spending for House members' own offices by 7.3 
percent for the upcoming election year. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase is included in a $1.92 billion bill financing  
Congress' operations next year that may be considered by the full 
House as early as next week. The total excludes Senate expenses, 
which that chamber adds later. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the overall bill is 6 percent below this year's $2.05  
billion measure, it would increase House members' allowances for 
staff salaries, taxpayer-paid mail to voters and district office 
rents. It would also boost spending for leadership offices and most 
committees and pay for renovations of a fountain, a cafeteria and 
other Capitol Hill facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll work to try to change it,'' said Rep. Tom Coburn,  
R-Okla., who last month was among conservatives who blocked passage 
of an agriculture bill they said was too costly. 
</P>
<P>
	The extra dollars for members' offices come even as Republicans  
plan other bills slicing education, aid to veterans and other 
popular domestic programs in the coming year. That juxtaposition 
has drawn fire from conservative and liberal congressional 
watchdogs alike. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be good if the House leadership would ... show some  
leadership and eliminate waste from their own budgets,'' said Gary 
Ruskin, director of the Congressional Accountability Project, which 
is affiliated with consumer advocate Ralph Nader. 
</P>
<P>
	If conservatives do try to amend the bill, they could give House  
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., his newest headache in a year when 
Republicans' thin majority has made it tough to move legislation 
through the chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	But conservatives face a tough task cracking the broad  
bipartisan support the annual bill financing Congress' own 
operations traditionally draws. Most incumbents of both parties, 
eager for the electoral advantages the measure would provide, are 
likely to support the bill, said GOP and Democratic aides, speaking 
on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to cut members' office accounts ``is where it gets very  
personal,'' said Rep. Mark Sanford, R-S.C., another conservative. 
He said lawmakers think, ``'You're talking about my chances of 
getting re-elected.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The cut in the overall bill's price tag from last year is ``the  
important factor here,'' said Michele Davis, spokeswoman for House 
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	But conservatives say that comparison is phony. They say when  
one-time emergency spending for 1999 for Capitol security and other 
items is subtracted, next year's bill would be nearly $100 million, 
or 5 percent, higher than this year's. 
</P>
<P>
	Staff director James Dyer of the House Appropriations Committee,  
which produced the bill, said he has detected little support for 
cutting it. 
</P>
<P>
	``If members want to go out on the floor and say, 'Cut me, cut  
me,' OK, we have provisions to allow that to happen,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dyer said the extra money would help legislators' ``desperate  
scramble here to keep people with a corporate memory'' by allowing 
for pay raises. And he said construction projects were included 
because lawmakers have ``a custodial responsibility for this 
place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the account most directly affecting lawmakers, the bill would  
increase House members' office accounts from $385.3 million this 
year to $413.6 million next year. The accounts, based largely on 
the number of each district's postal customers, cover staff 
salaries, official office travel and other expenses, but not 
members' salaries, which seem likely to remain at $136,673 each. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to providing a 7.3 percent increase in office  
accounts, the measure would complete an important change that the 
House Administration Committee made last year in House rules 
governing taxpayer-funded mail to voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Effective this year, House members can use as much of their  
accounts as they please for mail to constituents. Until now, only a 
small, specified portion could be used for mail, based mainly on 
the number of postal customers per district. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the bill assumes a $17 million increase -- to $29  
million -- for members to respond to letters and send mass mailings 
to constituents. Mail costs traditionally grow in election years. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also provides:  
</P>
<P>
	--$14.2 million for House leaders' offices, up from $13.1 million  
this year. Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, would get $380,000 
more, a 36 percent increase in his budget, and Minority Leader Dick 
Gephardt, D-Mo., $396,000 more, a 24 percent boost. 
</P>
<P>
	--3 percent more for House committees, to $91.6 million. The  
House Appropriations Committee budget would grow 10 percent, which 
spokeswoman Elizabeth Morra attributed to pay raises and new 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	--$153,000 to improve the Bartholdi park and fountain at the foot  
of Capitol Hill, $3.4 million to renovate the Rayburn House office 
building cafeteria and $115,000 to renovate House Judiciary 
Committee rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 7 percent raise, to $135,200, for new Congressional Budget  
Office Director Dan Crippen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
