<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers Unhappy With Leaf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- New San Diego Chargers coach Mike Riley is  
already unhappy with Ryan Leaf. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley tried to be diplomatic about Leaf missing a second day of  
the Chargers' voluntary workout yesterday. While not mandatory, the 
Chargers made it clear that Leaf should be here, what with his 
horrendous play as a rookie and because Riley continues to put in 
his new offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaf's absence ``is a story because of everything that's gone on  
in the past,'' Riley said. ``It's not a story when some other guys 
have done the same thing all around the country, but this is 
special because of the history, for sure. I can tell you that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaf's brief NFL career was marked by his 39.0 passer rating,  
lowest in the league, and 15 interceptions compared to just two 
touchdown passes. He screamed at a reporter in the locker room, and 
reportedly acted boorishly on a visit to his college campus during 
the Chargers' bye weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley said Leaf told him several weeks ago that he would have a  
conflict due to a charity event, but the coach was under the 
impression it would be for just one day. Riley doesn't expect Leaf 
here until Monday, meaning he will have missed three days of what 
the Chargers call ``summer school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After his round Thursday in the NFL Golf Classic in New Jersey,  
Leaf was asked if he had spoken with Riley about his absence, but 
he basically evaded the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we had practice yesterday and today and tomorrow and  
we had the schedule for about a month or so,'' Leaf said. ``But we 
have a summer school next week, too, and I'll be back for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of heading back to San Diego, Leaf said he's going to a  
children's telethon in Orlando, Fla., this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The coaching staff can fill in Leaf on what he missed on the  
field, Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm more concerned, however, with how this is going to affect  
what his teammates think of him,'' the coach said. ``That's 
appeared to be the biggest deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riley said he's heard more than one player say, ``Where's  
Ryan?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not really questions, but statements,'' Riley said.  
</P>
<P>
	Leaf's standing inside the locker room took a beating last year  
when some teammates felt he wasn't trying hard enough to win back 
the starting job after he was benched for poor play as well as bad 
behavior off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley noted that while some veterans such as Pro Bowlers Junior  
Seau and Rodney Harrison have been excused from these workouts, 
several others have traveled across the country to participate. 
</P>
<P>
	Guard Aaron Taylor didn't want to talk about Leaf's absence  
after Thursday's workout, saying: ``It's too early for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he offered a brief comment.  
</P>
<P>
	``All I will say is that as a football player, I welcome any  
opportunity to get better,'' said Taylor, who played in two 
straight Super Bowls with the Green Bay Packers before signing with 
the Chargers. ``You can always get better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although these workouts are not mandatory, Leaf needs to realize  
the expectations placed on him, said newcomer Jim Harbaugh, who's 
considered the starting quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only do you do the things that you are asked to do, but  
you've got to ask more of yourself,'' Harbaugh said. ``So he's got 
to continue to set that bar of expectation for himself very high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Bobby Beathard called Leaf's absence ``very  
disappointing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd love for him to be here. He needs it as much as anybody.  
We just hope he wants to play football as badly as we want him to 
play football.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
