<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Stand by Jaret Wright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Jaret Wright isn't going to the bullpen or  
Buffalo any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Indians manager Mike Hargrove said Friday the embattled Wright,  
who is 0-3 with a 12.79 ERA over his last four starts, will be 
allowed to work through his pitching problems in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not right now, no,'' Hargrove said when asked if he would  
consider sending Wright down to Triple-A. ``After a lot of 
discussion, we feel that Jaret's best chance to get back to where 
he's an effective major league pitcher is here right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel like there is good work being done with Jaret. That  
Jaret is working very hard about the things he needs to do to 
become more consistent. And we feel like his best chance to be that 
and do that is here and not somewhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who despite his recent struggles is still 4-3, allowed  
seven runs and six hits in 3 1-3 innings in his last outing on 
Wednesday in New York. The start came one day after the 23-year-old 
was summoned to AL president Gene Budig's office to discuss his 
role in two bench-clearing brawls this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright's 7.61 ERA is the second highest of any starter in the  
AL, and if not for the Indians averaging 8.06 runs in each of his 
starts, he wouldn't have a winning record. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Hargrove is standing by the right-hander and insists  
Wright isn't in jeopardy of losing his spot in the starting 
rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no reason for Jaret to feel like he's on thin ice or  
his future is hanging in the balance,'' Hargrove said. ``Jaret is a 
starter on this ballclub and will continue to be a starter. 
Obviously, we're not going to sit here and let start after start be 
like the last two or three he has had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A lack of confidence could be one of Wright's biggest problems  
said Hargrove, who thinks the recent headhunting accusations may 
have affected the pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a 23-year-old kid whose got great stuff and is struggling  
to find his command,'' Hargrove said. ``I haven't asked him that 
but I have to believe (his confidence) has probably been dented a 
little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove does have an option if Wright, 8-10 since the All-Star  
break last season, continues to have trouble. He could move long 
reliever Steve Karsay into the rotation and use Wright out of the 
bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've talked about that a lot,'' Hargrove said. ``But it came  
down to the point that we believe in Jaret Wright, and we believe 
that Jaret is going to pitch better. And we believe that Jaret is 
going to make us win here as a starter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove doesn't want to mess with Karsay (5-1, 2.15 ERA) or his  
bullpen right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we start doing that, we're robbing Peter to pay Paul,''  
Hargrove said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
