<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TruServ To Cut 1,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- TruServ Corp. will cut 1,000 corporate jobs, or  
15 percent of its work force, by year's end as the parent of 
several hardware chains reorganizes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago-based company said Friday the restructuring plan  
completes a 20-month effort to merge operations from hardware 
retailers Tru Value, ServiStar and Coast to Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will eliminate corporate staffers through a  
combination of job cuts, early retirement and the closing of two 
support offices in Chicago and suburban Schiller Park, executives 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``TruServ's members -- the store owners -- will now realize the  
full benefits of the merger in terms of organizational efficiency 
and responsiveness, accuracy and reliability of deliveries, 
high-quality merchandise and marketing support,'' said Daniel 
Cotter, TruServ chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the plan, TruServ has already closed six of 25  
distribution centers and a paint manufacturing facility. The 
company also reconfigured two distribution centers, expanded three 
others and opened a new distribution center in Hagerstown, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	TruServ has 10,400 stores and sales of about $4.3 billion. Other  
stores names are Grand Rental Station, Taylor Rental, Home &AMP; Garden 
Showplace and Induserve Supply. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
