<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO-Serb Military Talks Set  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Military leaders from NATO and  
Yugoslavia plan to meet Saturday on the Macedonia-Kosovo border to 
discuss a Serb withdrawal -- the key step before NATO will stop its 
bombing. The Pentagon said that if the Yugoslav authorities 
cooperate, NATO airstrikes could end as soon as Sunday. Allied 
planes hit Serb ground forces, flying 610 sorties in the 24 hours 
ending at midday Friday. NATO said 234 were attack sorties and 74 
were aimed at suppressing Yugoslav air defenses. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Wants Access to Serbia  
</P>
<P>
	ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- The prosecutor who indicted Yugoslav  
President Slobodan Milosevic for war crimes said Friday that any 
peace deal for Kosovo should guarantee investigators probing 
alleged atrocities access to the Serb province. ``We have to try to 
get guaranteed access,'' Louise Arbour, the chief prosecutor for 
the U.N. War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, said in an 
interview with The Associated Press. 

</P>
<P>
	Co-Pilot Says Approach Was Fine  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The co-pilot of the American Airlines  
jet that crashed in rough weather said today the approach appeared 
fine until they touched down and could not stop on a rain-slickened 
runway. First Officer Michael Origel, who is recovering from a 
broken leg at a hospital, spoke to investigators. Rather than slow 
to a stop Tuesday night, the jet skidded off the runway about 90 
mph, hit a bank of runway lights and crashing into a steel walkway 
just short of the Arkansas River. The plane broke into three 
pieces, killing eight passengers and the pilot. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Nears Senate Run  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON -- Hillary Rodham Clinton said today she will begin  
raising money to form the nucleus of her possible Democratic 
campaign for the Senate in 2000. ``I'm going to open an exploratory 
committee in July. And then I'll spend some time -- a lot of time -- 
in New York listening to people and I'm looking forward to that,'' 
Mrs. Clinton announced. She spoke at the end of an ABC ``Good 
Morning America'' broadcast on youth violence. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Seized in Tiananmen Square  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- On the 10th anniversary of its crackdown on  
pro-democracy demonstrations, China kept a close watch on Tiananmen 
Square. Dozens of police were on hand to prevent incidents. Two 
protesters were arrested. Near the capital, more than 20 relatives 
of five victims of the 1989 assault held a commemorative gathering 
under police guard. In Hong Kong, the only place in China where 
commemoration of the Tiananmen protests were allowed, thousands 
gathered for a candlelight vigil. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Names Gay Ambassador  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bypassing Senate confirmation, President  
Clinton moved today to directly install gay businessman James C. 
Hormel as ambassador to Luxembourg. The president invoked a 
provision of the Constitution allowing him to make such 
appointments during a congressional recess. Hormel, 66, who will 
become the first openly gay U.S. ambassador, can serve in the 
diplomatic post through the end of 2000. He is an heir to the 
Hormel food fortune. 

</P>
<P>
	Joblessness Falls to 4.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate dipped back  
down to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent in May even though the growth 
of payroll jobs was the smallest in more than three years. The 
Labor Department said the total number of payroll jobs rose by just 
11,000 in May, a sharp slowdown from the 343,000 jobs created in 
April. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes 136.15 Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices rose smartly on Wall Street today as the  
government reported that inflation and the economy weren't running 
rampant after all. The Dow Jones industrial average ended up 136.15 
points at 10,799.84, For the week, the Dow was up 240.10. On the 
NYSE, gainers led losers 1,827-1,097. The battered Nasdaq composite 
index rose 75.02 to 2,478.34, its fifth-largest point gain ever. 

</P>
<P>
	Kane Ties U.S. Women's Open Mark  
</P>
<P>
	WEST POINT, Miss. (AP) -- Lorie Kane record-tying 8-under-par 64  
at the U.S. Women's Open golf tournament today gave her a share of 
the lead with Juli Inkster. Becky Iverson's 64 in the second round 
put her just two strokes off the lead. Their rounds matched Kelli 
Kuehne's score yesterday. Kane and Inkster (69) were at 10-under 
134. Kuehne (71) was one shot back. 

</P>
<P>
	Woods Leads Memorial Golf  
</P>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ohio (AP) -- Tiger Woods nearly holed a 274-yard 2-iron  
on the 11th hole and then grabbed a one-shot lead after two rounds 
of the Memorial Tournament today when Lee Janzen double-bogeyed the 
final hole. Woods finished with a 66 for a 36-hole total of 
10-under 134. Joining Janzen a shot back was reigning PGA champion 
Vijay Singh. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
