<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hoechst Calls Shareholders Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Hoechst AG shareholders will meet July  
15 to vote on the company's proposed merger with France's 
Rhone-Poulenc SA that would create a huge drug and agricultural 
chemical conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting date was announced Friday. The new company will be  
called Avantis. 
</P>
<P>
	With the merger, both companies will divest most of their  
non-core industrial chemicals businesses. In Hoechst's case, these 
will be spun off into a new company called Celanese AG, listed 
separately on the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger is set for November, and the Aventis life sciences  
group is to be headquartered in Strasbourg, France. 
</P>
<P>
	At the July 15 meeting, shareholders also will be asked to  
approve a shortened fiscal year ending July 31, a necessary step in 
order to distribute a special dividend. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
