<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 03:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Teens in Smoking Ads Lose Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Some teen-agers responsible for gritty  
anti-smoking advertisements credited with contributing to a decline 
in Florida youth smoking have lost their jobs in the state 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Students Working Against Tobacco, or SWAT, produced the state's  
``Truth'' campaign, financed by money received from tobacco 
companies in Florida's settlement with the industry. One TV ad 
depicted tobacco executives getting awards for being the biggest 
killer, beating out murder and Adolf Hitler. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, some of the teens who worked on the project for $6 an hour  
are losing their jobs, victims of a political fight that slashed 
the campaign's budget in half. Critics of the cuts say lawmakers 
were uncomfortable with the in-your-face tenor of the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Jared Perez, the creative force behind many of the ads, was one  
of those fired by the state Department of Health. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, 18, said Thursday he understood the need to cut jobs  
given the budget. But he said those let go were the people most 
adamant about the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``They cut the teens, and the teens are what made this program  
special,'' Perez said. 
</P>
<P>
	National anti-smoking groups agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``The kids are the guts of the program,'' said Bill Novelli,  
president of Campaign for Tobacco Free Kids in Washington. ``This 
has the potential to be devastating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A recent survey by the Centers for Disease Control and  
Prevention showed that over the last year, smoking among Florida 
middle school students has dropped 18 percent, 9 percent among high 
school students. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven of the 31 people at Florida's Tobacco Pilot Program were  
told in the last couple weeks they would be offered jobs elsewhere 
in the health department. 
</P>
<P>
	Adult professionals were also fired, including the press  
secretary and the director. 
</P>
<P>
	The health department and Gov. Jeb Bush requested $61 million  
for the project. Lawmakers earmarked roughly $32 million -- less 
than half what it got last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's spokesman Cory Tilley said Thursday the governor remains  
``totally supportive of the program,'' but that a staff of 20 was 
more than enough. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
