<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds Release Carlos Baerga </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Former major leaguer Carlos Baerga, who has  
been trying to earn a promotion from the Cincinnati Reds' farm 
system, was released by the Reds on Friday so he could sign a 
minor-league contract with the San Diego Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga, 30, had been playing with the Reds' Triple-A  
Indianapolis team. The Reds said he asked for his release so that 
he could join San Diego's Triple-A club. 
</P>
<P>
	The infielder batted .290 in 52 games at Indianapolis, with  
three home runs and 27 runs batted in. He agreed to a minor league 
deal during spring training that allowed him to become a free agent 
if another team wants him for its major league roster. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds had considered bringing him up, but bypassed him to  
promote other players and acknowledged that they could lose Baerga 
as a result. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're sorry that we were not able to provide Carlos an  
opportunity at the major league level, but we believe we kept the 
best 25-man roster to win now and long-term,'' Reds general manager 
Jim Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga made the American League All-Star team in 1992, 1993 and  
1995 while with the Cleveland Indians. Cleveland traded him in July 
1996 to the New York Mets. He played for the Mets through last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Louis Cardinals signed Baerga as a free agent in  
January, then released him during spring training. The Reds signed 
him on March 23 to his Triple-A contract with Indianapolis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
