<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Bombing May End Sunday  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon said today NATO might stop  
bombing Yugoslavia as early as Sunday if Serb begin to retreat from 
Kosovo. President Clinton said he was ready to end allied air 
strikes following a tentative peace deal. He explained: ``There is 
an enormous opportunity to be seized here, a chance to shift our 
focus from defeating something evil to building something good.'' 
Clinton said 11 weeks of NATO bombing have been worth the effort to 
end Serbian repression in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO-Serb Military Talks Set  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ready to halt the air campaign  
against Yugoslavia, NATO generals were expected to meet 
face-to-face tomorrow with Yugoslav and Russian counterparts. They 
will discuss plans for a Serb withdrawal from the disputed province 
of Kosovo -- the key step before NATO will stop the bombing 
campaign. Plans for the Serb retreat, including logistical 
questions about which roads and bridges to use, were to be 
considered in the NATO-Yugoslav military meeting. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Seized in Tiananmen Square  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- On the 10th anniversary of its crackdown on  
pro-democracy demonstrations, China kept a close watch on Tiananmen 
Square. Dozens of police, some in plainclothes, were on hand. Two 
protesters were arrested. Near the capital, more than 20 relatives 
of five victims of the 1989 assault held a commemorative gathering 
under police guard. In Hong Kong, the only place in China where 
commemoration of the Tiananmen protests were allowed, thousands 
gathered for a candlelight vigil. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Nears Senate Run  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON -- Hillary Rodham Clinton said today she will begin  
raising money to travel to New York, conduct polls and hire staff -- 
forming the nucleus of her possible Democratic campaign for the 
Senate in 2000. ``I'm going to open an exploratory committee in 
July. And then I'll spend some time -- a lot of time -- in New York 
listening to people and I'm looking forward to that,'' Mrs. Clinton 
announced. She spoke at the end of an ABC ``Good Morning America'' 
broadcast on youth violence. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Chooses Gay Ambassador  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bypassing Senate confirmation, President  
Clinton moved today to directly install gay businessman James C. 
Hormel as ambassador to Luxembourg. The president invoked a 
provision of the Constitution allowing him to make such 
appointments during a congressional recess. Hormel, 66, who will 
become the first openly gay U.S. ambassador, can serve in the 
diplomatic post through the end of 2000. He is an heir to the 
Hormel food fortune. 

</P>
<P>
	Relatives View Jet Crash Site  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Federal investigators in the crash of  
American Airlines Flight 1420 visited a hospital today to interview 
injured passengers, while survivors and victims' relatives went to 
the end of a runway to see the plane's burned-out shell. The 
National Transportation Safety Board wants to know what passengers 
saw, heard and smelled before the crash, which killed nine people, 
including the pilot. Twenty passengers remained hospitalized, four 
in critical condition. 

</P>
<P>
	Unemployment Falls to 4.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate dipped back  
down to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent in May even though the growth 
of payroll jobs was the smallest in more than three years. 
Unemployment among blacks fell to the lowest level on record while 
the jobless rates of teen-agers and adult women hit 30-year lows, 
the Labor Department said. Even with the drop in unemployment, the 
total number of payroll jobs rose by just 11,000 in May, a sharp 
slowdown from the 343,000 jobs created in April. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 136.15  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices rose smartly on Wall Street today as the  
government reported that inflation and the economy weren't running 
rampant after all. The Dow Jones industrial average ended up 136.15 
points at 10,799.84, For the week, the Dow was up 240.10. On the 
NYSE, gainers led losers 1,827-1,097. The battered Nasdaq composite 
index rose 75.02 to 2,478.34, its fifth-largest point gain ever. 

</P>
<P>
	Agassi's Match Postponed in Paris  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Andre Agassi's semifinal against Dominik Hrbaty was  
postponed until tomorrow because of rain with Agassi leading 6-4, 
7-6 (8-6), 3-6, 1-2. If he gets by the Slovakian, Andrei Medvedev 
will be waiting for him in the title match. Medvedev beat Fernando 
Meligeni today 7-5, 3-6, 6-4, 7-6 (8-6) to reach his first Grand 
Slam final. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
  	   	
</P>
