<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Problems for Team Kool Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST ALLIS, Wis. (AP) -- A friendly chat and a quiet lecture by  
team owner Barry Green apparently has healed any possible breach 
between teammates Paul Tracy and Dario Franchitti after their 
untimely collision last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	All three members of Team Kool Green, at the Milwaukee Mile on  
Friday as practice began for the Miller Lite 225, downplayed the 
incident last Saturday during the Motorola 300 in Madison, Ill. 
Tracy and Franchitti collided while racing each other for second 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	Tracy, whose bad-boy reputation had people immediately pointing  
fingers, wound up in the concrete wall and out of the race. 
Franchitti somehow managed to keep his car spinning in the middle 
of the track, recovered and went on to finish third. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paul and I talked a little yesterday and everything is just  
fine between us,'' Franchitti said. ``There's no problem at all. 
It's just a little awkward right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second time the teammates have been involved in an  
altercation. Last October in Houston, Tracy wrecked both team cars 
when he hit Franchitti while trying to pass on the tight city 
street circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Tracy then got into a brief shoving match with Green in the pit  
lane. 
</P>
<P>
	In this latest incident, it was Franchitti who was trying to  
make the pass. Tracy, who was barred from driving in the season 
opener by CART for a rough driving incident last fall in Australia, 
simply rode off on his motorbike after returning to the pits. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no tension between Dario and I,'' Tracy said Friday.  
``I'd be lying, though, if I said I wasn't disappointed. We could 
have had a podium finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``From my standpoint, we've got to pull the positives out of  
last week. We were competitive all three days, qualified on the 
front row and led the race. Now we've got to carry that momentum 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti, second by four points in the driver standings behind  
rookie sensation Juan Montoya, said he still trusts his teammate 
``as much as you trust anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, I think most of our problems on the racetrack are  
because we are teammates,'' Franchitti said. ``We would attack a 
lot harder with somebody else. It's when you hesitate that you get 
in trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tracy agreed, saying, ``I give him more room than anybody else  
out there. I went wheel to wheel with Montoya and with Greg (Moore) 
and I gave them less room than I gave Dario. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just drove in very hard to try to make the pass. I left  
room, but there just wasn't enough room after he skipped across 
some bumps and moved up a bit. I sure didn't want that to happen. 
We had a good car and we need that finish badly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green said the team had its usual Friday morning meeting, but  
admitted the topic this week was the incident in Madison. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a racing incident,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, it  
involved both of our cars. And there was equal blame to go 
around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green said he remains happy with his driver combination.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great problem to have when you get two drivers who are  
so competitive and so aggressive. That's what I want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The aftermath of the crash certainly didn't slow Tracy on Friday  
as he led the opening practice for Sunday's race with a lap of 
168.681 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore was second at 168.475, followed by Patrick Carpentier at  
168.048, Madison runner-up Helio Castro-Neves at 167.979, Montoya 
at 167.650, Christian Fittipaldi at 167.487 and defending race 
winner Jimmy Vasser at 167.261. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Andretti, who won the Motorola 300, was 10th at 166.765.  
Franchitti struggled to find the right setup and tied for 16th with 
Michel Jourdain Jr. at 165.032. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
