<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whirlpool Names New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Home appliance maker Whirlpool Corp.  
named a new president on Friday, promoting Jeff M. Fettig, who had 
been head of Whirlpool Europe operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Fettig, 42, was also named as chief operating officer. He will  
report to chairman and CEO David Whitwam. 
</P>
<P>
	Whirlpool also named Mark E. Brown, the company's comptroller,  
as chief financial officer, while Bengt G. Engstrom was selected to 
take Fettig's job as head of Whirlpool Europe. The moves are 
effective immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitwam said in a statement that Whirlpool had gone without a  
president for a number of years, but decided to fill the position 
to help manage the company. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Fettig led ``our significantly improved performance in  
Europe, which has led to Whirlpool's position as the number one 
brand of appliances in Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fettig joined Whirlpool in 1981 in financial operations. In 1990  
he was named vice president of marketing for the Whirlpool 
Appliance Group in Whirlpool Europe. Two years later he returned to 
the United States and was appointed vice president of group 
marketing and sales, North American Appliance Group. He moved back 
to Europe as an executive vice president and president of Whirlpool 
Europe in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Whirlpool is a leading maker of major appliances, marketing 11  
major brand names in 170 countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 00:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks' Ewing: Bring Me My Ring  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- How do the Knicks replace Patrick Ewing?  
For starters, Jeff Van Gundy isn't sure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what my starting lineup is yet,'' the coach of  
the Knicks said Thursday after Ewing stood before his teammates at 
practice, his injured left leg strapped into a thick, black walking 
cast, and made a request. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have to go out and get me my ring,'' Ewing said.  
``They're ready to go get it for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first step in that process comes Saturday when the Eastern  
Conference finals against the Indiana Pacers resumes. The series, 
tied 1-1, will look a whole lot different since a partial tear of 
the Achilles' tendon will keep Ewing sidelined for the rest of the 
postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy was giving no decent clues as to his thinking on the  
new lineup, although Latrell Sprewell said he expected to continue 
coming off the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can start big with Chris Dudley, you can start big with  
Marcus Camby, you can start small,'' Van Gundy said. ``I just have 
to decide what's best for our team in Game 3, and I haven't decided 
yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of Ewing will be especially troublesome if the  
remaining Knicks big men get into foul trouble. Van Gundy will be 
reluctant to press 40-year-old backup Herb Williams into service 
behind Dudley and Kurt Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas has been getting the early defensive matchup on Rik  
Smits, while Ewing was guarding the less-dangerous Dale Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy said he expects Smits to see more playing time since  
he can avoid foul trouble by not having to guard Ewing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The formula for winning is the same no matter who plays: Play  
defense, rebound and get quality shots,'' Van Gundy said. ``We 
can't turn into a jump shooting team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What they can turn into is a run-and-gun team that pushes the  
ball upcourt and tries to get into the paint before Indiana sets up 
its defense. The Knicks had 22 fast-break points in their Game 1 
victory but only seven in the Game 2 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	When Ewing sat out 12 games earlier this season, that was the  
strategy the Knicks used successfully. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still feel we have an opportunity to win it,'' Ewing said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ewing's teammates echoed that confidence, bouyed by the fact  
they already know what it's like to win without him. Tendinitis in 
the same tendon kept Ewing out of 12 games during the regular 
season, and he missed most of the previous season because of a 
broken wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling a little confident because we have played without  
him and we've been successful without him during the regular 
season. He's going to be missed a lot, but we'll play a more 
uptempo style,'' Camby said. ``Everyone's in an uptempo spirit, 
everyone's ready to raise their level of play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing's role with the Knicks, especially on offense, has  
diminished during the playoffs because of a multitude of injuries. 
He scored 16 points during 40 minutes in Game 1, then had 10 points 
in 25 minutes in Game 2 after feeling a ``ripping sensation'' in 
his Achilles' tendon during pregame warmups. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was told it was unlikely that when you have tendinitis it  
leads to a tear. Unfortunately, it happened,'' Ewing said. ``I 
don't regret playing. It was rough enough for me last year to sit 
and watch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Indianapolis, the Pacers said they know what to expect of the  
Ewing-less Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can look at it one of two ways,'' Davis said. ``Either  
they're going to respond to him or it is going to hurt them badly. 
Knowing the character of that team, I think they'll respond 
positively. I look for them to push the ball more. They're going to 
be home, so I look for them to be more of an uptempo team.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hall of Fame Spices Pepper's Game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST POINT, Miss. (AP) -- Dottie Pepper doesn't want an LPGA  
career measured by majors. Her goal is loftier. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepper, who won the season's first major with a record 19-under  
par at the Nabisco Dinah Shore, is 7 under and only three strokes 
off the lead halfway through the U.S. Women's Open. 
</P>
<P>
	As one of the fiercest competitors on the tour, there is no  
question Pepper would like to win the Open. But she insists her 
focus is on the LPGA Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in this for the big picture. I'm not in it to just win  
majors of X number of tournaments,'' Pepper said Friday after her 
second sub-70 round at Old Waverly Golf Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Under requirements revamped this year, there is a point system  
for induction into the LPGA Hall of Fame. Instead of needing to win 
at least 30 tournaments with two major titles, players now need to 
earn 27 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Players get one point for each career victory, scoring title and  
player of the year award, and a bonus point for winning in one of 
the four majors. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepper, who is 33 years old and a 12th-year pro, has 19 points  
toward the Hall of Fame. She has 15 victories, including two Dinah 
Shore titles, and in 1992 was the LPGA player of the year and 
scoring champ. The win at this year's Dinah Shore ended a nearly 
three-year victory drought. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal is the Hall of Fame. I'll take whatever it takes to  
get in there,'' Pepper said. ``It can be eight more regular 
tournaments. It could be four more majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``If an Open is among them that would be great. But I'm not  
going to freeze frame myself to think that's the only way I'm going 
to get in it is by winning an Open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pepper is in position to make a run at an Open title -- and add  
two points toward her Hall of Fame total. 
</P>
<P>
	A 68-69 start follows top 10 finishes at the Sara Lee and  
Corning tournaments, where she shot in the 60s for all four weekend 
rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	And in 15 previous Opens as a pro, Pepper has 10 times finished  
in the top 15. That includes five straight top 10 finishes between 
1988-92. 
</P>
<P>
	``All you do after two days is try to get yourself in the thick  
of it. And that's exactly what's happened,'' Pepper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure your excitement level tends to rise a little bit,  
especially on the weekend, but I think it's important not to 
overemphasize that the world doesn't end with U.S. Opens or majors 
specifically.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charismatic Tries for Triple Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Here we go again.  
</P>
<P>
	For the third year in a row, and for the seventh time in 21  
years, thoroughbred racing stands on the threshold of its first 
Triple Crown champion since Affirmed swept the Kentucky Derby, 
Preakness and Belmont in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	This time around, the 3-year-old on the verge of racing  
immortality is Charismatic, a great-grandson of the mighty 
Secretariat. Charismatic won the Derby and Preakness less than four 
months after he was tossed into a $62,5000 claiming race. 
</P>
<P>
	A win today in the 1 1/2-mile Belmont, considered the ``Test of  
Champions,'' would boost the 3-year-old chestnut's earnings to more 
than $2.5 million and clinch a Visa-sponsored $5 million bonus for 
owners Bob and Beverly Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, trained by Hall of Famer D. Wayne Lukas, is  
attempting to become the 12th Triple Crown winner and avoid joining 
14 others who flopped in the Belmont after winning the Derby and 
Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the timing is right, I think the public would like to  
see it,'' Lukas said of a Triple Crown. ``We're just hoping that 
the energy level is there to have one more great race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two years, the energy level fizzled in the final  
strides for Silver Charm and Real Quiet, a pair of colts trained by 
Bob Baffert, who tries to play spoiler today when he sends out star 
filly Silverbulletday to challenge Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Silver Charm battled Free House down the stretch,  
but Touch Gold swept by on the outside in the final 50 yards and 
won by three-quarters-of-a-length, denying the Lewises a Triple 
Crown on their first attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Victory Gallop nosed out Real Quiet at the wire after  
a sensational stretch run, giving trainer Elliott Walden a win 
after his colt finished second in the Derby and Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Walden is in the same situation today: Menifee, runner-up in the  
Derby and Preakness, could give the 36-year-old Kentucky-based 
trainer his second straight Belmont victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Baffert and Walden leave no doubt that, sure, a Triple  
Crown would be terrific for racing, but not at their expense. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no part of me that wants to see Charismatic win the  
Belmont,'' Walden said. ``That said, if we can't win, I'd like to 
see Charismatic win the Triple Crown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert's view of the race is slightly different.  
</P>
<P>
	``Winning the Triple Crown is either meant to be or not meant to  
be,'' he said. ``I lost the last two, and if Charismatic wins, 
it'll be a great story. But if Silverbulletday wins, it'll be a 
great story, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises, meanwhile, can't believe their good fortune.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you asked me what the odds of having another chance at the  
Triple Crown were, I'd say astronomical, unbelievable,'' Bob Lewis 
said. ``I think my elation at Pimlico was prompted not by the 
victory Chris and Wayne brought, but the fact that we were going to 
run for the Triple Crown again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chris would be Chris Antley, who has perhaps the best comeback  
story of all. 
</P>
<P>
	After years of being one of the nation's top jockeys, the  
33-year-old rider dropped out of the sport in 1997, bedeviled with 
drug problems that played a part in his weight ballooning to 147 
pounds. After nearly 1 1/2 years out of the sport, Antley returned, 
and Lukas gave him a shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope I can get this done,'' Antley said. ``If it doesn't  
happen, I'm going to still be the same. Believe me, nobody wants it 
more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic will face 11 challengers, making his task all the  
more difficult. In the 25 previous Belmonts where a Triple Crown 
was on the line, the only field larger was in 1971, when Pass 
Catcher denied Canonero II the series sweep in a 13-horse field. 
Also, none of the 11 Triple Crown winners faced more than seven 
opponents in the Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, who won just one of his first nine races before  
Lukas began working him harder and running him more frequently, won 
the Derby at odds of 31-1, the Preakness at 8-1, and was expected 
to be the favorite at post time (5:27 p.m. EDT). 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, with Pat Day aboard, and Silverbulletday, with Jerry  
Bailey in the irons for the filly's first race against males after 
winning 11 of 12 against her own sex, were expected to be the next 
to choices of an expected crowd between 80,000 and 85,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The other challengers are Best of Luck, Stephen Got Even,  
Adonis, Lemon Drop Kid, Vision and Verse, Patience Game, Pineaff, 
Prime Directive and Teletable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
