<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Examines Olympic Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Olympic officials have turned over 18  
boxes of financial records to congressional investigators examining 
the city's winning bid for the 1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Three staff members for a subcommittee of the House Commerce  
Committee were escorted to Olympic offices Thursday and given 
immediate access to the records, which are only a fraction of the 
1,400 boxes of documents chronicling the Atlanta Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., chairman of the subcommittee, said  
investigators most likely will want to see all Olympic records, 
including any files purged from the boxes by lawyers for the 
Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation, which contends it owns the 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	While the GAAF will not prevent the investigators from looking  
at all records, it wants to ``direct'' their review, spokesman Lee 
Echols said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be directing them, pointing out where they can find  
the information they are looking for,'' Echols said. 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee received a report this week from Billy Payne  
and Andrew Young, the foundation's cochairmen, detailing some of 
the enticements they used in winning the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation hoped the report would satisfy the investigators,  
but the details of expensive gifts, excessive travel and lavish 
receptions only piqued their interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just scratching the surface,'' Upton said after reading  
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation is keeping the records closed to public scrutiny  
and is battling Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker and The 
Atlanta Journal-Constitution in court to keep them private. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
