<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Government Eases Anti-Baiting Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service eased its  
anti-baiting rules Thursday, saying migratory game birds can be 
shot over natural wetlands where grains have been deposited through 
normal upkeep such as mowing or the clearing of brush. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule change ``recognizes the need to allow the necessary  
management of these (wetland) areas ... while still providing 
hunting opportunities,'' the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised regulations ``give landowners the flexibility to  
maintain, develop, manage and hunt (in) wetland habitat essential 
for migratory birds,'' the agency said in announcing the new 
baiting regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law prohibits hunters from distributing grain or other  
food to attract migratory game birds for the purpose of shooting 
them. Hunters and property owners have complained that the 
prohibition has also been applied when seed is inadvertently left 
by routine upkeep of land including mowing, the clearing of brush, 
or tillage. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, landowners have been reluctant to perform these  
needed maintenance practices to wetland areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie Rappaport Clark, the agency's director, said the revised  
regulations will provide incentives for landowners to maintain 
wetlands and, as a result, ``will provide additional habitat for 
birds and increase opportunities for hunting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Wetland conservation on private lands is essential to the  
long-term survival and growth of waterfowl and other migratory bird 
populations,'' said Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also said the new rules will no longer consider as  
illegal baiting the ``inadvertent scattering of seed'' from 
standing crops when a hunter places decoys or retrieves downed 
birds. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised regulations also implemented a less restrictive  
definition enacted by Congress last year of when someone should be 
considered subject to the anti-baiting law. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously a person could be held liable even if he claimed he  
did not know an area had been baited. Under the new rules, a person 
can be prosecuted ``if the person knows or reasonably should know'' 
that an area was baited. 
</P>
<P>
	The penalty for hunting over bait is a fine of up to $15,000 and  
six months in jail. Actual placing of bait can subject an 
individual to a fine of up to $100,000 and one year in jail. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
