<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Close Higher; Dow Up 136.15 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices rose smartly on Wall Street Friday as  
traders were pleasantly surprised by the government's report that 
inflation and the economy aren't running rampant after all. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's monthly employment report helped temper  
investors' concerns that the Federal Reserve might soon raise 
interest rates to slow the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bargain-hunting that followed the recent selloff on Wall Street  
also contributed to Friday's gains, as the Dow Jones industrial 
average rose 136.15 to close at 10,799.84, adding to an 85-point 
gain on Thursday. For the week, the Dow was up 240.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher. The battered Nasdaq  
composite index rose 75.02 to 2,478.34, its fifth-largest point 
gain ever. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 28.21 to 1,327.75. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported that the nation's unemployment  
rate dipped to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent in May. But investors 
were particularly impressed by the fact that only 11,000 jobs were 
created last month, far below the 225,000 expected by economists 
and a sign that the economy is growing moderately. 
</P>
<P>
	Another indicator closely watched for signs of inflation,  
average hourly earnings, was up 3.6 percent in May compared to a 
year ago, only a slight acceleration from a 3.2 percent increase 
the month before. 
</P>
<P>
	Both factors eased concerns among investors that the Fed will  
soon raise rates to slow an economy that is threatening to 
overheat. The central bank warned May 18 that it would raise rates 
if it determined that inflation was gaining momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors may feel like the worst news on that front has  
already occurred,'' said Bob Dickey, managing director of technical 
analysis at Dain Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed's warning has created volatility on Wall Street in  
recent weeks, with investors fearing a rate hike would cut into the 
profits of major U.S. companies. But analysts suggested that the 
weeks between the Fed's initial hint and the June 29 meeting of its 
Open Market Committee are giving investors time to get used to the 
idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts also attributed Friday's gains to the relatively cheap  
prices that have resulted from the downturn on Wall Street in 
recent weeks. The Dow is down about 2.8 percent since hitting a 
record high on May 13, while the Nasdaq is down 6.6 percent since 
reaching its all-time high April 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday brought the Nasdaq its strongest gain since April 21 as  
investors swooped in looking for bargains. Cisco Systems, up 6 1/16 
to 114 7/8 and Yahoo!, up 12 1/16 at 147 7/16, led a wide rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of these stocks have been hit really hard and there's  
some renewed interest in buying,'' Dickey said 
</P>
<P>
	On the New York Stock Exchange, America Online rose 12 to 117 3/4.  
AOL got a boost from a court ruling that AT&AMP;T must provide open 
access to its cable lines, a decision that should make it easier 
for Internet companies to compete for the business of offering 
high-speed access over cable lines. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, AT&AMP;T slipped 7/8 to 53 3/8. At Home, which has access to  
AT&AMP;T's cable properties, dropped 10 3/4 to 94 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial and bank stocks made some modest gains, as did  
consumer products issues like Procter &AMP; Gamble, which rose 3 1/8 to 
96 5/8 amid speculation it will soon announce a restructuring plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, analysts suggested Friday's gains may be difficult to  
sustain as long as questions about interest rates hang over the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is still tepid and cautious about what the Fed will  
do,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume came to 
836.66 million shares, compared with 868.80 million in the previous 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 10.32 to 634.52, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 5.04 to 780.98 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.35 to 442.33.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.45 percent.  
Germany's DAX index was up 1.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 
0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed closed down 0.2 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
