<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 10:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MCI WorldCom Sued Over Skytel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom is being sued by investors and may  
be facing a federal probe over whether it improperly concealed its 
plans to buy paging company Skytel Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	A class-action suit was announced late Thursday by a group of  
investors charging they made money-losing trades after MCI WorldCom 
made misleading statements. The suit alleges MCI WorldCom drove 
down the price of SkyTel's shares -- and the price tag for last 
week's deal -- by downplaying news it had reserved the Internet 
address ``www.skytelworldcom.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators, meanwhile, are reportedly investigating whether MCI  
WorldCom intentionally mislead investors with its statements 
regarding the Web address on May 25, three days before announcing 
the $1.3 billion purchase of Skytel. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission plans to ask MCI WorldCom  
to supply all documents related to the SkyTel negotiations to 
determine who knew what and when they knew it, The Wall Street 
Journal reported today, citing a person familiar with the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom declined comment today on both the investor suit  
and the Journal report. An SEC official did not return a phone call 
seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of SkyTel rose as much as 16 percent to $21.87 1/2 on May 25  
after an Internet service named Company Sleuth reported that MCI 
WorldCom had reserved an Internet address combining the two 
companies' names, suggesting a merger could be in the works. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom quickly played down the significance of that move,  
saying it routinely reserves domain names that might have value, 
and that the SkyTel-related registration was the work of an 
overzealous employee. 
</P>
<P>
	``From time to time, MCI WorldCom employees, sometimes acting on  
their own initiative, register domain names they believe may be 
potential targets of domain-name squatters. The action is not an 
indication of any official company intention,'' said the statement 
read that day by spokeswoman Barbara Gibson. 
</P>
<P>
	By the close of trading, SkyTel had closed with a 6 percent gain  
at $20.12 1/2, with MCI WorldCom compounding the confusion by first 
saying the registration had been withdrawn and later that night 
saying it had not. The merger agreement announced on May 28 valued 
SkyTel at about $21.25 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	The investor group, represented by the New York law firm  
Bernstein Liebhard &AMP; Lifshitz, alleged that ``MCI was aware that 
many public shareholders of SkyTel would sell their SkyTel stock if 
they believed that market rumors of takeover talks between MCI and 
SkyTel were unfounded. Defendant's motive was to reduce the price 
MCI would have to pay to acquire SkyTel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal said the SEC will try to determine if an executive  
decision had been made at MCI WorldCom to secure the Internet 
address and whether the employee had been directed to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also noted that MCI WolrdCom could easily have  
declined to comment on the SkyTel situation, a common strategy used 
by companies in merger discussions and one that is endorsed by the 
SEC and the courts. But in choosing to respond publicly, the 
company was required to make a full, truthful statement, the 
Journal said, quoting a securities lawyer. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:31:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Recalls Last Free Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- When Indonesians last held a free  
election, President Eisenhower was in the White House and the Cold 
War was in full bloom. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, as now, there was ample enthusiasm for democracy. In 1955,  
Indonesia was a fledgling nation, the memory of an independence war 
against Dutch colonizers still fresh. 
</P>
<P>
	But the political experiment went awry: Governing coalition  
parties bickered and founding President Sukarno steered the nation 
on an authoritarian course. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia, facing parliamentary elections on Monday, is again a  
fragile country as it emerges from three decades of rigid rule 
under former President Suharto, Sukarno's successor. Elections took 
place then, but they were carefully manipulated in Suharto's favor. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the uncertainty and political trends that shaped the old  
election remain alive today, but many of the destabilizing factors 
that undercut democracy do not. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-four years ago, 83 parties and individuals registered for  
the parliamentary race. The debate was acrimonious and no group won 
a majority. Next week, a handful of the 48 parties in the race are 
expected to dominate. 
</P>
<P>
	Again, no single party is likely to win an outright majority,  
making negotiations over a coalition government all but certain. 
</P>
<P>
	``There'll be lots of squabbling, but I don't think it will be  
squabbling of a kind that destroys the economy or breaks up the 
country,'' said Herb Feith of Gadjah Mada University in Yogyakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Feith, an Australian who witnessed the 1955 election, said  
bitter political rivalries bred anxiety and wild rumors: false 
sightings of submarines offshore and allegations of mass 
food-poisoning by political agitators. 
</P>
<P>
	There were also fears of unrest ahead of this year's poll, which  
came after outbreaks of deadly violence in many parts of the 
Southeast Asian nation of 210 million. Economic turmoil led to 
riots and protests that forced Suharto to quit last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign has been largely peaceful despite scattered  
attacks, including rock-throwing Friday at members of the ruling 
Golkar party in Jakarta, the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	In this year's election, all parties agree on the need for  
reform and an end to corruption. Even the forces that propped up 
Suharto -- Golkar and the politically powerful military -- have 
disavowed their authoritarian legacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesians feel like ``people who have been in a room without  
air for a long time and the door has been let open,'' said Arief 
Budiman, an expert on Indonesia at Melbourne University in 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, Sukarno and his allies in the military were never  
comfortable with a parliamentary democracy. The Communist Party, 
later crushed by Suharto, was considered a growing threat and party 
debates were seen as divisive. Regional rebellions broke out. 
</P>
<P>
	Sukarno ended up strengthening his executive powers under a  
system labeled ``guided democracy'' and a compliant Parliament 
declared him president-for-life in 1963. Suharto, then an army 
general, edged him from power a few years later. 
</P>
<P>
	The dominant political figures in Indonesia today have their  
roots in the blocs of 1955. Sukarno's daughter and pro-reform 
leader, Megawati Sukarnoputri, draws much of her support from the 
reverence that many people feel for her father. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslim factions that competed then form the base of support for  
two leaders today, Amien Rais and Abdurrahman Wahid. 
</P>
<P>
	After the vote, legislators will help choose a new president  
later in the year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
