<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Battle Against Fla. Fire Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSCEOLA NATIONAL FOREST, Fla. (AP) -- Casper Platero is in one of  
the most scenic forests in the country, but he can't see it for the 
smoke and can't breathe in the pine-scented air without getting a 
chest full of soot. 
</P>
<P>
	Platero, 20, is part of a cadre of American Indians fighting a  
64,000-acre fire covering parts of the Okefenokee Swamp, the 
Osceola National Forest and private land on the Florida-Georgia 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	Out among the towering pines and spearlike palmettos, the Navajo  
from Canoncito, N.M., is getting his first taste of the sweaty, 
gritty, work. White smoke hangs thick in the air and the ground is 
hot. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun because I am out in the wilderness,'' he says as he  
rolls up a water hose. ``And it's exciting, because you might not 
make it to see tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the same containment line are Indians from Oklahoma --  
Cherokees from Tahlequah, Kiowas from Anadarko, Chickasaws from Ada 
-- and Arapahos from Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	Arch Wells, chief forester for the Bureau of Indian Affairs in  
Washington, D.C., said half of the wildfire emergency firefighters 
in the country are American Indians -- a long-standing tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chances are that their brothers did it, their fathers did it,  
their grandfathers did it,'' Wells said. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike full-time Forest Service employees, who receive overtime  
and hazardous duty pay, 20-person Indian crews are hired for a 
specific fire and paid about $10 per hour with no overtime. Their 
clothing, housing and meals are provided, as is health insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 600 firefighters and a small air force of planes and  
helicopters have been working the Florida blaze around the clock 
since lightning set it off on May 21. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, no one has been hurt and no structures have been  
threatened. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Brown, 37, has spent 19 springs and summers fighting  
fires, taking winter breaks doing concrete and carpentry work on 
the Wind River Reservation in Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	``I spent spring here in the Southeast and in the summer I go  
out West,'' said Brown, a Northern Arapaho. ``We just go where we 
are called. I like to see all these places.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown spent part of last summer battling wildfires that swept  
through Florida for six weeks and now he is back. 
</P>
<P>
	Mac McCarthy, 23, runs a pump to supply water to firefighters. A  
Kiowa shield is painted on the side of his red truck. 
</P>
<P>
	``It got pretty scary last night,'' he said. ``We had to go  
through the swamp and put out some fires. There were several 
alligators, about 3 or 4 feet. I kept an eye on them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
