<HEADLINE> Yankees Put Nelson on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Yankees put relief pitcher Jeff  
Nelson back on the disabled list Friday because of an elbow problem 
and made three other roster moves before starting a three-game 
series against the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees optioned reliever Greg McCarthy to Triple-A  
Columbus, and recalled pitcher Todd Erdos and infielder Clay 
Bellinger from their top minor league affiliate. 
</P>
<P>
	Bellinger, sent down to Columbus on Tuesday, might serve as  
extra insurance for Chuck Knoblauch. The All-Star second baseman 
was forced to leave Wednesday night's game against Cleveland 
because of bruised ribs after being hit by a pitch from Jaret 
Wright. 
</P>
<P>
	Knoblauch was listed in the starting lineup for the opener of  
the interleague series against their crosstown rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson was pulled from Wednesday's game against Cleveland after  
he felt stiffness in his right elbow, and was put on the disabled 
list because of inflammation. He went on the DL on May 3 because of 
elbow inflammation and was activated May 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson is 1-1 with a 5.74 ERA in 17 games. He was a valuable  
member of the World Series champions last year as a middelman, 
going 5-3 with three saves and a 3.79 ERA in 45 games. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarthy was claimed on waivers from Seattle on May 28. He  
reported to the Yankees three days later, but did not pitch. The 
left-hander was 0-1 with a 2.05 ERA at Triple-A Tacoma. 
</P>
<P>
	Bellinger started the season with the Yankees and hit .120 in 10  
games. Sent down to the minors this week, he went 5-for-12 for 
Columbus before being recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	Erdos also spent time with New York this season, albeit a brief  
stint. He was promoted from Columbus on May 20 and did not pitch 
before he was sent down the next day. The right-hander was 2-1 with 
a 5.97 ERA in 11 appearances, including six starts, in the minors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
