<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Army Sergeant Sues CNN and Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Another U.S. Special Forces veteran has sued  
CNN and Time Inc., saying he was deceived into giving interviews 
for a story that accused U.S. commandos of using nerve gas to hunt 
down and kill defectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Hagen, a former Army Special Forces sergeant, sued CNN,  
Time Inc. and three producers as well as reporter Peter Arnett. He 
said he was told CNN producers could help him get medical treatment 
for his war-related illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``They took this brave war hero and made him look like a  
buffoon,'' said Hagen's lawyer, Kevin McLean. ``He was a hero, not 
a murderer and he has to restore his reputation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, which does not specify a damage amount, was filed  
Thursday, a day after former Army Special Forces Lt. Robert Van 
Buskirk filed a defamation lawsuit in North Carolina seeking $100 
million in damages for the story, which was later retracted. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagen said he was never told the true nature of the story being  
investigated. 
</P>
<P>
	``They asked to interview me about my medical problems and the  
problems I was having with the Veterans Administration,'' Hagen 
said. ``The whole family was ecstatic that finally we were going to 
get some help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said producers discussed his illnesses and shot footage of  
some 20 bottles of narcotic medications prescribed for him. But 
they also asked him questions about the nerve gas sarin and about 
orders for dealing with defectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagen said he told producers he knew nothing about sarin gas or  
its use. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for CNN and Time declined to comment on the lawsuit.  
</P>
<P>
	The joint CNN-Time story telecast on June 7, 1998, claimed the  
military used sarin in Laos during Operation Tailwind, a mission to 
find defectors. Two U.S. defectors were supposedly killed in the 
attack, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The story was retracted after an internal investigation could  
not substantiate the allegations. Time and CNN, both owned by Time 
Warner, apologized for the story. 
</P>
<P>
	Two producers were fired and a third resigned over the story.  
Arnett, the lead reporter, was reprimanded and ultimately left the 
network. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
