<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Terrell Owens Signs With 49ers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Wide receiver Terrell Owens became a San  
Francisco 49er again Friday, reportedly signing a one-year contract 
worth $3.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement capped lengthy negotiations among general manager  
Bill Walsh, director of football operations John McVay and Owens' 
agent, David Joseph, the San Francisco Chronicle reported in 
Saturday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	That means Owens is available for preseason minicamps, which  
continue next week in Santa Clara. He missed a three-day minicamp 
last month, saying he didn't want to risk injury without a 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``My agent's been in here for two weeks and has had some  
productive meetings with Walsh and McVay. They assured me that my 
(long-term) deal was almost finalized, so I told them I needed to 
get some work in,'' said Owens, 25. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll offer my services next week and hopefully we'll get  
something done real soon,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several 49ers officials did not immediately return calls by The  
Associated Press seeking comment Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	While the one-year deal was a formality, the salary was the  
required tender offer made to Owens, who was designated as the 
49ers' franchise player in February. Under the rules of the NFL's 
collective bargaining agreement, Owens was offered the average of 
the top five salaries for wide receivers for the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Had the 49ers not signed him to that minimum one-year tender  
offer by July 15, Owens would have been free to negotiate with 
other clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's some assurance that I'll be a 49er,'' Owens said. ``This  
team is on the verge of some great things and like always we're 
trying to reach the Super Bowl. I've been close for, like, three 
years since I've been here. It would have been hard to part ways -- 
not only for me, but for the fans as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now it's a lot of weight off my back, and a lot of guys can  
quit asking me if I'm going to be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Steve Mariucci said that since Owens hit several career  
highs in 1998 -- 67 receptions for 1,097 yards and 14 touchdowns, 
including a 79-yard scoring catch -- he would have been a successful 
free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't help but think other teams (might have) made a run  
at him,'' Mariucci said. ``Physically, he's as good a receiver as 
you're going to see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 49ers' regular training camp runs July 26-August 17 in  
Stockton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
