<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rivlin Resigns As No. 2 Fed Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The unexpected resignation of Federal Reserve  
Vice Chairman Alice Rivlin gives President Clinton two vacancies to 
fill at the nation's central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	And some private economists believe Rivlin's departure increases  
the likelihood that Alan Greenspan will be asked by Clinton next 
year to stay on as Fed chairman for a fourth four-year term. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin, 68, announced Thursday that she would leave the Fed on  
July 16 in order to devote more time to her second job as chairman 
of the District of Columbia's financial control board, a post that 
Clinton appointed her to a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am definitely not resigning as chair of the D.C. Financial  
Assistance Authority,'' Rivlin said in her resignation letter to 
Clinton. ``Indeed, I hope to spend more time and to be more 
effectively involved in the city than I have been able to be at the 
Fed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The control board was created by Congress in 1995 at a time when  
the District was on the brink of financial insolvency during the 
administration of former Mayor Marion Barry. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years the city has regained its financial footing, and  
both Congress and the control board have relaxed their day-to-day 
supervision of local affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	In a written statement, Clinton praised Rivlin for ``helping  
usher in a new era of budget surpluses'' during her time as head of 
the administration's budget office. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Anthony Williams said he looked forward to working with  
Rivlin ``to solidify our financial recovery and bring democracy to 
our nation's capital.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin's departure means there will be two vacancies on the  
seven-member Fed board of governors. The administration has 
indicated that Carol J. Parry, an executive vice president of Chase 
Manhattan Bank, the country's third largest bank, is the 
front-runner for a vacancy that has existed since last June when 
Susan Phillips left the board. 
</P>
<P>
	Some private economists viewed the departure of the No. 2 Fed  
official as making it even more likely that Clinton will decide to 
re-nominate Greenspan when his current term expires in June 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``This increases the likelihood that Greenspan will stay on,''  
said David Jones, chief economist at Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co. in New 
York. Jones said that in his last year in office, Clinton will have 
trouble persuading the Republican-controlled Senate to accept 
anyone other than Greenspan for the top job. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan was first nominated for the Fed chairmanship by  
President Reagan in 1987 and has been re-appointed by Presidents 
Bush and Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the departure of Rivlin should have little effect  
on the Fed's interest rate decisions, given Greenspan's mastery at 
gaining consensus on the board for his policy moves. The Fed 
announced last month that it had changed its policy stance and is 
now leaning toward raising interest rates because of growing 
concerns about inflationary pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin said she would not participate in the Fed's next interest  
rate-setting meeting on June 29-30. Some analysts believe a rate 
hike could come at that time but others are not sure. 
</P>
<P>
	``The loss of her vote will have only a marginal impact on the  
next meeting and we still expect no increase in the interest rate 
target coming out of the June meeting,'' said Gary Thayer, chief 
economist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin, who served as first the deputy and then the head of  
Clinton's Office of Management and Budget, was nominated by the 
president for the Fed post in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	She was seen as a deficit hawk inside the administration,  
helping push Clinton toward a more aggressive approach to reducing 
the budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an enormous privilege to be part of the Clinton  
economic team and help put together the policies that turned that 
huge budget deficit into a surplus,'' Rivlin said in her letter to 
Clinton. ``We did the right thing and it worked!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin announced that in addition to devoting more time to her  
duties as chair of the control board, she will also return to the 
Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
