<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Consultant Predicts Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Forget the polls and focus groups.  
</P>
<P>
	Republican consultant Ed Gillespie, working for GOP presidential  
hopeful John Kasich, says he can predict how Americans will vote in 
the 2000 presidential election. It's all in the name, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	His tongue-in-cheek assessment:  
</P>
<P>
	If your name begins with ``mayor,'' ``congressman'' or  
``governor'' you're with front-runner George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	If it begins with Ms., you're with Elizabeth Dole.  
</P>
<P>
	If it begins with ``reverend'' you're with religious activist  
Gary Bauer. 
</P>
<P>
	If your names ends with a Roman numeral, you're with millionaire  
Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	If it ends with a vowel, you're with Kasich -- a product of an  
ethnic Pennsylvania town. 
</P>
<P>
	If it ends with USN retired, you're with former Navy pilot John  
McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	If your name is spelled just like it sounds, you're with  
weak-spelling Dan Quayle. 
</P>
<P>
	If you've changed it, you're with Lamar (Lamar!) Alexander.  
</P>
<P>
	If you can trace it back to the American revolution, you're with  
Pat Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	If your name is Smith, you're with Sen. Bob Smith of New  
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the Democrats, if your name ends with .com, you're with  
Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	And if it begins with ``Dr.'' and ends with ``J.,'' you're with  
Hall of Fame basketball player Bill Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Gillespie: ``The essence to campaigning is to increase your  
name identification. This is a guidebook for the entire field.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
