<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army-Navy Game May Move to Baltimore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Army-Navy football game, will be played in  
Baltimore next year, The (Baltimore) Sun reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Naval Academy is expected to announce today that the game  
will be played on Dec. 2, 2000, at PSINet Stadium, home of the 
Baltimore Ravens, the newspaper said, quoting anonymous sources. 
</P>
<P>
	That will mark the third time the game has been held in  
Baltimore, the first since 1944, the newspaper said. The 2000 game 
will be the 100th time the two teams square off. 
</P>
<P>
	For 50 of the past 54 years, the game has been play in  
Philadelphia, about midway between Annapolis, home of the U.S. 
Naval Academy, and West Point, N.Y., home of the Army counterpart. 
Philadelphia first hosted the game in 1899 and has done so 74 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	It also has been played at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena and Giants  
Stadium in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the railing gave way at Veterans Stadium under  
pressure from cadets, injuring nine and raising questions about 
safety in the aging facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Army and Navy have a contract to play at Veterans Stadium  
until 2002, an option in the contract will allow the game to be 
played elsewhere once more, the newspaper said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
