<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST ALLIS, Wis. (AP) -- CART will require tethers on the rear  
wheels of its Champ cars before the July 25 U.S. 500 at Michigan 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was made Friday at the Milwaukee Mile, where  
practice began for Sunday's Miller Lite 225. 
</P>
<P>
	The tethers, called wheel energy absorbing restraints by CART,  
are attached to the chassis, keeping the wheel and broken 
suspensions from flying off during a heavy crash. 
</P>
<P>
	CART has required the devices on the front wheels since the  
Motorola 300 last Saturday in Madison, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	They were added in response to an accident May 1 at an Indy  
Racing League event in Concord, N.C. A wheel and suspension pieces 
flew into the stands, killing three fans and injuring eight others. 
</P>
<P>
	It was also at the U.S. 500 last July when a wheel and  
suspension pieces also killed three spectators and injured six 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL added the tethers -- made of a high-tech material -- to  
all four tires before last Sunday's Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	At Indy, the tethers worked in all but one case, with one rear  
tire rolling harmlessly away after Mark Dismore hit the wall. 
Several crashes produced no loose tires at the CART race. 
</P>
<P>
	Formula One adopted a tether system before the 1999 season and  
there have been no injuries outside the cars in any crash so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Anderson, team manager for the Target-Chip Ganassi Racing  
team, which has won the last three CART championships and is 
leading the current points, said the CART teams began by tethering 
the front tires because there was not enough material immediately 
available to do all four. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. 500 is the next oval race on the CART schedule.  
</P>
<P>
	In other CART safety moves, the pit speed limit has been reduced  
from 60 mph -- with a 5 mph leeway -- to a maximum of 50 for all CART 
events, and all crew members who go over the wall to service cars 
will be required to wear helmets, beginning with the June 27 road 
race in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TRACK DOWN:* Chip Ganassi, who will promote the inaugural  
Target Grand Prix on Aug. 22 at the new Chicago Motor Speedway, 
said Friday the first layer of asphalt has been laid for the 
1.1-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Juan Montoya, who drives for Ganassi's CART team and is the  
series points leader, drove a Champ car on the unfinished track 
Thursday, ``just to check it out for bumps and make sure the 
transitions work and there are no dips or valleys out there. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lap record right now is 26.1 seconds,'' he added with a  
grin. That translates to 151.72 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Ganassi said the final layer of asphalt will be poured next  
week, with the official opening of the new track some time in July. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *INTERNATIONAL CAST:* Heading into Sunday's race, each of the  
top six drivers in the CART series is from a different country. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya is from Colombia, with runner-up Dario Franchitti from  
Scotland. Third place belongs to Michael Andretti of the United 
States, followed by Greg Moore of Canada and Christian Fittipaldi 
of Brazil, tied for fourth, and Adrian Fernandez of Mexico. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
