<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet Extradition Hearing Set </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Spain's request to have former Chilean dictator  
Gen. Augusto Pinochet extradited for human rights abuses allegedly 
committed during his 17-year rule will be heard on Sept. 27, a 
magistrate ruled Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a blow to Spanish investigators, judge Graham Parkinson said  
the charges against the 83-year-old Pinochet must be finalized by 
Aug. 31, in the interests of fairness. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as the extradition proceedings are concerned, I take  
the view that we need to know the exact boundaries of this 
application,'' Parkinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Brian Gibbins had argued that more time was needed to  
define the charges, saying it would be ``quite wrong of this 
court'' to impose limits on the Spanish investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an investigation that is continuing and the examining  
judge is continuing to question witnesses on a regular basis,'' 
Gibbins said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Julian Knowles, one of Pinochet's lawyers, asked the court  
to ``bring down the guillotine'' on the matter so that the defense 
would know exactly what case it needed to answer. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said Pinochet's lawyers would have until Sept. 14 to  
submit questions about the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The full extradition hearing at the Bow Street Magistrate's  
Court is expected to last up to five days. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet was arrested Oct. 16 in London at the request of  
Spanish magistrate Baltasar Garzon, who wants to try the former 
Chilean leader for human rights abuses allegedly committed at the 
hands of his security forces during his 1973-90 regime. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, aspects of the case have been considered and  
reconsidered in the High Court and the House of Lords, Britain's 
highest court of appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The law lords issued a ruling in March that dramatically limited  
the scope of the Spanish case against Pinochet, who remains under 
24-hour guard at a rented mansion southwest of London. 
</P>
<P>
	The judges ruled Pinochet could face charges of torture and  
torture conspiracy dating only after December 1988, when Britain 
ratified the International Convention Against Torture. 
</P>
<P>
	Home Secretary Jack Straw, the Cabinet minister who decides  
whether to pass extradition requests onto the British courts, ruled 
the next month that the remaining charges were sufficiently serious 
to allow the extradition process to carry on. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the High Court denied Pinochet permission to  
challenge Spain's extradition request. 
</P>
<P>
	An official Chilean report says 3,197 people disappeared or were  
killed at the hands of Pinochet's secret police after he ousted 
Chile's elected Marxist president, Salvador Allende, in a bloody 
coup. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
