<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 11:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Plans 'Reinvigorating' Retreat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Concerned that the Security Council has  
been deadlocked for months on pressing world issues, 
Secretary-General Kofi Annan is taking action: He's bringing the 15 
council ambassadors to New Jersey for the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-day retreat at a lakeside conference center in Princeton  
will attempt to ``reinvigorate'' the work of the council and find 
new opportunities for action and agreement, U.N. spokesman Fred 
Eckhard said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's rather nice sometimes to talk with ties off,''  
said British Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock. 
</P>
<P>
	The retreat was to begin late Friday with addresses by David A.  
Hamberg, president of the Carnegie Corporation, a New York-based 
grant and research organization, and Samuel Huntington, professor 
of government at Harvard University. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamberg co-authored ``Preventing Deadly Conflicts,'' a 1997  
report by a special commission funded by Carnegie on the causes of 
conflicts and ways to prevent them that has become almost required 
reading at the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Huntington is best known for his 1996 book ``The Clash of  
Civilizations and the Remaking of World Order,'' which makes a case 
for nonintervention by the West in world conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Annan and the diplomats will enter into discussions  
on the role of the United Nations and the Security Council, and 
possible changes in both what the council does and how it does it. 
</P>
<P>
	Greater transparency in the council's work and more effective  
ways of enforcing its decisions, such as ``smart sanctions'' that 
spare innocent populations, will be among the ideas discussed, 
diplomats said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will give all the members of the council a chance  
to reflect, to reflect among themselves and away from the daily 
chores, the phone calls, and discuss how the council can be made 
more effective,'' Annan said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The council soon will have to reassert itself as it takes on a  
Kosovo peace plan, which was accepted Thursday by Yugoslavia. The 
council was marginalized during the conflict because of clashes 
among the permanent council members. 
</P>
<P>
	The council has also been unable to come up with a new policy  
toward Iraq. France, Russia and China are advocating a suspension 
of sanctions but the United States and Britain say they must remain 
until inspectors report Iraq is free of banned weapons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
