<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 10:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Tells Insurer To Halt Biz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese financial authorities ordered a life  
insurance firm to cease key business operations today after company 
auditors found it had effectively become insolvent. 
</P>
<P>
	The apparent failure of Toho Mutual Life Insurance Co. comes as  
only the second collapse of a Japanese life insurer since World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's Financial Supervisory Agency said an administrator will  
be appointed to oversee Toho Mutual. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, it instructed the insurer to stop lending and paying  
dividends and to accept more policy cancellations. Toho can 
continue to receive premiums and make non-dividend payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes about a year after GE Capital Services, a unit of  
General Electric Co., formed a joint venture which took over all 
new business from Toho along with its headquarters building in 
Tokyo and most of its sales staff. 
</P>
<P>
	But Toho continued as an independent entity responsible for  
overseeing existing policyholders' contracts and investment assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Toho said in a statement Friday that company auditors had  
determined that its liabilities effectively exceeded assets by 
$1.64 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The company was unable to cope with bad loans and losses related  
to securities and foreign exchange holdings, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, more and more clients have been canceling their  
policies since Toho posted its first-ever loss since World War II 
in the fiscal year that ended in March 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Toho's policyholders will be protected by a life insurance  
industry fund and will receive full payment on their policies 
through March 2001, the Financial Supervisory Agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	In April 1997 the Japanese Finance Ministry ordered ailing  
Nissan Mutual Life Insurance Co. to shut down, the first time in 50 
years that financial regulators forced an insurer to close. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
