<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Plans Exploratory Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taking a big step toward a political race,  
Hillary Rodham Clinton said today she will form an exploratory 
committee in July to prepare for a possible campaign for a Senate 
seat from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to open an exploratory committee in July,'' she  
said. ``And then I'll spend some time -- a lot of time -- in New York 
listening to people and I'm looking forward to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady made her comments in an interview on ABC's ``Good  
Morning America.'' Her statement confirmed what her top political 
adviser had said Thursday, that she would form an exploratory 
committee next month for the seat being vacated next year by 
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. No first lady has ever run for 
public office. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's running for office. She's running,'' said James  
Carville, the political mastermind of Bill Clinton's 1992 
presidential victory. Carville, who met with Mrs. Clinton at the 
White House on Thursday, offered to help with her campaign but said 
he would not have an official staff role. 
</P>
<P>
	With the exploratory committee decision made, Mrs. Clinton must  
next ``start thinking about a timetable, thinking about people, 
putting a staff together. There's a gazillion things you have to 
do,'' Carville said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a race that could pit her against the Republican mayor of  
New York City, Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think exploring New York is a good thing,'' Giuliani said  
following a speech in Michigan, stressing that the first lady has 
never lived in New York. ``Maybe she should explore New York a 
little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I should say though, I have supreme confidence that the next  
senator from New York will be someone from the state of New York,'' 
the mayor added. 
</P>
<P>
	Formation of an exploratory committee will allow Mrs. Clinton to  
begin raising money for the race. That means she could begin paying 
for some of her travel to New York, for polling and other 
campaign-type expenses. She already has come under fire for making 
campaign-style trips to New York as first lady, and thus at 
taxpayer expense. 
</P>
<P>
	Formation of such a committee will be seen in political circles  
as tantamount to a declaration of candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Harold Ickes, who is heading up Mrs. Clinton's political  
operation, disclosed the exploratory committee plans after Rep. 
Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., called the first lady to tell her she would 
seek re-election to the House, leaving the Senate Democratic field 
open for Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told her it seemed clear she was running. ... I wished her  
well,'' Lowey said. ``I told her I would support her 
enthusiastically.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton issued a statement that said: ``Today Nita Lowey  
called me to say that she would be running for re-election to the 
House. I thank Nita for her support and I look forward to working 
with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also met Thursday with political consultant James  
Carville. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether they discussed the New York Senate race, the first  
lady's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said, ``They both have a love of 
politics, so it wouldn't surprise me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ickes, a former White House chief of staff to President Clinton,  
said Mrs. Clinton did not go into detail about her own political 
plans during the conversation with Lowey. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ickes added: ``I think you can discern that Hillary is going  
to press forward and she will be forming an exploratory committee 
in early July and just keep moving forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He cautioned that formation of the committee did not necessarily  
mean Mrs. Clinton would seek the seat. ``This is one step at a 
time,'' Ickes said. ``The initial step forward is to form the 
exploratory committee and continue to talk to the people of New 
York.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
