<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 09:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Funds? Don't Get 'Em While Hot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Don't get 'em while they're hot.  
</P>
<P>
	That's a thought to bear in mind when you go shopping for a  
mutual fund. News reports are filled these days with talk of ``hot 
funds'' -- the names that have been burning up the performance 
charts or just got a top rating from the research services. 
</P>
<P>
	But if you are seeking a long-term investment to pursue  
long-term goals, which is the mission that funds are best suited 
for, hot may be the last thing you want. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, you need to make sure you don't flame out before you  
reach your goal. Aesop's fable of the hare and the tortoise comes 
to mind, with its simple moral ``slow but steady wins the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experience shows that in the up-and-down world of the investment  
markets, the funds that look the hottest at any given time may be 
the ones in greatest danger of going stone cold. 
</P>
<P>
	In a few weeks from mid-April to late May, Internet and other  
high-technology stock funds demonstrated this principle in vivid 
style. Almost as fast as you could say ``log off!'', Dow Jones's 
index of Internet stocks plunged 32 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The tech tumble is by no means the only recent story of that  
kind. If you look back to 1997, you may recall that financial 
services funds and real estate funds were racking up some of the 
best performance numbers in the business. 
</P>
<P>
	Then both turned in dismal showings in 1998. An average of  
financial services funds tracked by Lipper Inc. rose just 6.86 
percent, trailing the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 by more than 21 
percentage points. Real estate funds LOST more than 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the health and biotechnology group, a consistent  
winner in recent years until 1999. From Jan. 1 through mid-May this 
year, the Lipper health and biotech fund average lost 1.59 percent 
while many funds were posting double-digit gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``Too often, investors forget history,'' says the research firm  
of Wiesenberger in its monthly Mutual Funds Update. ``Many 
concentrate on the hot fund being touted for that month. However, 
last year's winner may be this year's loser and vice versa. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trying to time the market and pick this year's or this month's  
investment-category darling does not pay off, but instead leads to 
high transaction costs and lost opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If that's the case, how do you decide where to put your money?  
It's as much an art as a science, but most advisers agree that the 
best approach starts from a careful calculation of what you want to 
accomplish, rather than whatever message the markets seem to be 
transmitting at the moment. 
</P>
<P>
	Need long-term growth to cover tuition costs for your children  
and build a nest egg for your old age? Then consider a mixture of 
funds that stands a chance of staying on track as market moods keep 
changing. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with big bills coming due in the next year or two for  
something like college or a new home? Then minimize stock-market 
risk in your portfolio, regardless of whatever the market seems to 
be doing right now. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the time, risks can't be eliminated. But they can be  
managed by staying diversified, using bond or money-market funds to 
protect against the chance of a bear market in stocks, and 
different types of stock funds as a cushion against the modern 
phenomenon known as ``market rotation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In April this year, large growth stocks suddenly lost favor, and  
value stocks just as abruptly became popular, in what Robert Pozen, 
chief executive at Fidelity Management in Boston, called ``one of 
the sharpest rotations that we've ever seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The idea is to ride tides, rather than chasing waves -- to avoid  
the kind of day-trading mentality that has received so much 
attention of late. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very concerned about the impression some people have about  
day-trading,'' says Michelle Smith, managing director of the Mutual 
Fund Education Alliance, a Kansas City-based trade group of no-load 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that troubles me the most is the feeling that this  
is a game, that there is no risk. People get stars in their eyes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
