<DOCNO> APW19990604.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 16:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston's Portugal Won't Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Boston pitcher Mark Portugal, who strongly  
considered retirement so he could spend more time with his three 
children, decided Friday to remain with the Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been my life for the last 18 1/2 years. It's given me  
everything I have,'' he said. ``You don't know how long you'll play 
this game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal, 36, made his decision as he was driving to Fenway Park  
for Friday night's game against the Atlanta Braves. But when he 
arrived at the Red Sox clubhouse ``I was flip-flopping again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he talked to manager Jimy Williams.  
</P>
<P>
	``One of the questions I asked Jimy is if he wants me on his  
team. He said, `most definitely.' That was reassuring,'' Portugal 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal is 3-3 with a 5.33 ERA in 10 starts and will be used as  
a reliever for now. He said that was fine with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Darn right we want him back on this team. He can help us,''  
Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Rapp will take Portugal's place in the starting rotation on  
Sunday against Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last outing, Portugal allowed six runs and lasted three  
innings in Monday's 8-7 win over the Detroit Tigers. He left the 
ballpark in a hurry without talking to reporters. He said he 
apologized to teammates and Williams about his behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	He was ``angry, upset and confused'' at the time and, after  
talking with his agent, team officials and others since then, 
decided to remain active, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal was married 11 years before going through a divorce  
last season, when he went 10-5 with Philadelphia. His three 
children are Derek, 10, Jacob, 6, and Alexandra, 3. 
</P>
<P>
	His children live in nearby Barrington, R.I., one of the main  
reasons he signed with Boston as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came back here to spend more time with my children, but with  
the night games and the road schedule, at times it feels like I've 
been a Saturday afternoon father on homestands,'' Portugal said. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason he decided to stay active was the pleasure his  
children get from seeing him play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came back because I love to play baseball and my kids love  
to see me play baseball,'' Portugal said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his ex-wife ``never acted in a malicious way'' and told  
him and their children that ``any time I can get away to see them, 
they're mine. When the kids get out of school in a couple of weeks 
I'm sure it'll be a lot easier to deal with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox have made some recommendations for him to deal with  
his problems and he's ``talking to people now,'' Portugal said. 
``I'll continue to talk to people through the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal first came to the majors in 1985 with Minnesota and  
played with Houston, San Francisco and Cincinnati before joining 
Philadelphia in 1997. His career record entering this season was 
102-83 with a 3.89 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	He signed a $2.7 million, one-year contract with the Red Sox, a  
deal that gives Boston a $3.3 million option with a $300,000 buyout 
for 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal said there have been times this season when ``I was  
literally not in the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Monday was one of those games,'' he said. ``I can't go out  
there and pitch like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had indicated to teammates this week that he was leaning  
toward retirement and still hadn't made a decision after meeting 
with general manager Dan Duquette and Williams on Thursday at 
Pawtucket, R.I., where the Red Sox played an exhibition game 
against their International League affiliate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to go home and think about this from a father's  
perspective and from a baseball player's perspective,'' he said. 
``We all have problems and bad days at our job where we just want 
to toss it out the window. And sometimes we don't get a second 
chance to do what we love to do. It's been rough seas, but we've 
weathered the storm now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
