<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NTSB: Jet's Wing Flaps Didn't Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Wind-resisting wing panels used to slow  
down landing jetliners were not opened as American Airlines Flight 
1420 hurtled down a runway and crashed, killing nine people, 
federal investigators say. 
</P>
<P>
	During a typical landing, the spoilers -- movable panels on the  
top of the wing -- are opened and thrust reversers are engaged to 
cut a plane's speed. 
</P>
<P>
	But information from the aircraft's flight data recorder shows  
that the spoilers did not deploy Tuesday night and that the thrust 
reversers turned off and on, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	The question now is whether the irregularities were due to  
mechanical problems or were the result of choices by the pilot, who 
was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be that the only person who knows the answer to that  
question is no longer with us,'' George Black of the National 
Transportation Safety Board said Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said it is possible to land a plane without spoilers,  
adding he himself was once in a plane that safely landed with the 
spoilers closed. 
</P>
<P>
	The MD-82 jetliner landed as a thunderstorm raked Little Rock  
National Airport with hail, lightning and wind gusts of 75 mph. The 
plane skidded off the end of the runway, plunged over a stone 
embankment and was ripped open as it hit a metal walkway. The jet 
broke into three parts and caught fire. 
</P>
<P>
	NTSB staff members planned to escort victims' relatives to the  
site later today so they can see it for themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said the pilot was warned twice about dangerous  
wind shears and received more notice than usual of bad conditions 
as he brought the plane in for the landing. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators were to interview the injured co-pilot today, and  
salvage crews were to begin removing parts of the plane for more 
examination. 
</P>
<P>
	The airplane was traveling at 165 mph when it landed, according  
to the data recorder, which included 27 to 28 seconds of 
information after the touchdown and 62 previous hours of data, 
Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	The most interesting finding from the recorder was the repeated  
cycling of the thrust reversers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a routine landing, jet engines are reversed until the plane  
is slowed to a reasonable speed. In this case, the data recorder 
showed that the thrust reversers cycled on and off twice. Then, 
eight seconds before the end of the recording while the engine was 
near idling, the left thrust reverser engaged but the right did 
not, Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are facts. There has been no analysis done on this,''  
Black said. ``This is not a time to speculate on this data.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spoiler system is customarily armed before landing so that  
the panels automatically pop up when the wheels touch the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta Air Lines recently instituted a policy under which both  
the pilot and the co-pilot have to confirm that the spoiler lever 
has been put in the armed position. 
</P>
<P>
	The jet had been directed to land from the north because the  
airport was reporting southerly winds as the plane neared. But as 
the fierce storm moved in from the northwest, the pilot was instead 
ordered to approach from the southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the cockpit voice recorder, a pilot commented twice  
that he had lost visual contact with the runway and noted that 
winds were at 35 mph with gusts up to 52 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	During the approach, air traffic controllers relayed regular  
updates, including word of winds up to 46 mph and two alarms for 
wind shears -- sudden down bursts that can rob a plane of its lift, 
Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The level of care, we think, by the controller was pretty  
good,'' Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	Black declined to say how a pilot should react given such  
information, stressing it is the pilot's call about whether to land 
the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Richard Buschmann was an experienced pilot whom colleagues  
described as unlikely to take risks. He had been on the job for 13 1/2 
hours before the crash -- within the airline's maximum of 14 hours -- 
flying from Chicago to Salt Lake City and Dallas before Little 
Rock. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators want to know whether the pilot's decision to land  
was influenced by a desire to end the long day and get the plane to 
its intended airport for the night to prevent delays the next 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane had about 2,400 gallons of fuel, enough to make it to  
Dallas or Nashville, Tenn., Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tests Thursday also showed that the rain-slickened runway had  
proper grooves to prevent hydroplaning, and the tires and a brake 
were in good condition. According to skid marks, the plane touched 
down 2,000 feet from the start of the 7,200-foot runway, which 
Black said was about the proper place to begin a landing. 
</P>
<P>
	One passenger, Dave Ozmun, said the plane never seemed to get  
traction. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could tell he was trying to work the brakes,'' he said.  
``Once we even left the runway, he was continuing to try to reverse 
the plane and try to protect the passengers as best he could. It 
was just impossible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press Writer Glen Johnson in  
Washington contributed to this report. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
