<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Defends Best-Sellers Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Internet bookseller Amazon.com has asked a  
federal court to declare that it can continue to cite The New York 
Times' best-seller list in advertising discount prices, the company 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com announced May 17 that it would offer 50 percent  
discounts on books on the Times' best-seller list. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement today, Amazon.com said the Times demanded May 28  
in a letter that Amazon.com stop using the list for promotions, 
saying Amazon was infringing on the newspaper's copyright and 
trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com said it filed a request late Thursday in U.S.  
District Court here asking for declaratory relief that would allow 
it to continue to refer to the Times best-seller lists in promoting 
its discounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The New York Times best-seller list is widely used in the  
book-selling industry as an indicator of the most popular books 
being bought nationwide,'' Amazon.com's release said. ``Book 
buyers, therefore, can easily use the list to make price 
comparisons on the best-selling books.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com spokesman Bill Curry said the company's argument is  
that citing the Times' best-seller lists is ``fair use -- that it's 
data that is out there and it is fair use to say that something is 
a New York Times best seller in the same way you would say a movie 
won an academy award.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com filed its court action as a last resort after  
discussions with the Times failed to reach an agreement, Curry 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	After Amazon.com announced the discounts last month, it was  
quickly matched by the Internet booksellers Barnesandnoble.com of 
New York, and Borders.com of Ann Arbor, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Fahle, a spokesman for Borders.com, said a letter asking  
his company to stop referring to the Times' best-seller list ``was 
faxed to us late last night. It's dated June 4. I'm assuming it's a 
letter similar to the one Amazon.com received.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fahle said the letter was from the Times legal department. ``We  
haven't decided what to do at this point,'' Fahle said. He said the 
company continues to refer to the Times' best-seller list online 
``just as we've done for years in our stores.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Boyd, a spokesman for barnesandnoble.com, said his company  
had not gotten a similar letter. He said nytimes.com is an 
affiliate of barnesandnoble.com and sells books through 
barnesandnoble.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``They sell through barnsandnoble.com. They earn a commission on  
all books sold through barnesandnoble.com as part of the affiliate 
relationship,'' Boyd said. He said the agreement with the New York 
Times allows barnesandnoble.com ``to use New York Times content 
according to their stipulations,'' including the New York Times 
best-seller list. 
</P>
<P>
	Borders has no business arrangement with the Times, Fahle said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Times did not immediately return a telephone call for  
comment this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com claims to be the Internet's largest retailer of  
videos, music and books. It also has bought or is developing 
interests in a variety of online companies offering products and 
services such as pharmaceuticals, beauty aids, greeting cards, 
pets, groceries and auctions. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
