<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Snake Slips Into Couple's Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HURON, Ohio (AP) -- Ginny Slivka thought she'd spotted some rust  
on her car. Then, the rust moved. 
</P>
<P>
	It turned out to be a 6-foot snake that had made a home inside  
the car, next to the driver's door. 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of day earlier, her husband had seen the snake at a  
golf course. Using a golf club, he nudged it back into the woods -- 
or so he thought. 
</P>
<P>
	The snake apparently slipped into the car through the trunk and  
stayed there until Mrs. Slivka discovered it while running errands 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two firefighters helped bag the reptile, which wasn't believed  
to be poisonous. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Slivka was thankful she wasn't driving at the time.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think I would have had a heart attack or an accident,'' she  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 06:10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Confusion Over State of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- European Union leaders added to  
confusion over the state of the euro today by first drawing up a 
statement saying they were ``not at all concerned'' about the 
currency's weakness, then deleting the passage from the final 
summit communique. 
</P>
<P>
	The turnaround came amid mounting criticism that EU authorities  
were contributing to the euro's slump against the dollar by sending 
mixed signals about the currency, which has slipped by more than 10 
percent since its adoption by 11 nations on Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	EU officials said the phrase was dropped at Italy's request. No  
further details of why the draft statement was altered were 
immediately given. 
</P>
<P>
	Other changes were made to the draft statement's passages  
dealing with the EU economy, including one confirming the EU's 
resolve ``to secure market confidence in the stability of the euro 
by a consistent economic and financial policy geared to stability 
and reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	EU officials said that passage was dropped at the request of  
France. 
</P>
<P>
	An EU official said the leaders agreed to delete the bulk of the  
language about the euro out of concern for its possible impact on 
the financial markets. He said they were concerned any written 
statement on the euro might be taken as a sign of undue concern by 
currency markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro lurched to new lows today of $1.0270 in Asian markets  
and $1.0313 in European trading. When the currency was launched on 
Jan. 1 it was trading at around $1.17. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopes of a peace deal in Kosovo did little to raise the euro's  
fortunes, although German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder expressed 
confidence Thursday that the possible end to the conflict ``will 
also have positive effects on the currency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	European traders said they were expecting more volatility in  
euro-dollar markets and don't exclude the possibility of another 
euro low before the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the euro's woes had not  
altered his aim of taking Britain into the single currency if the 
economic conditions are right. ``Our position remains exactly the 
same and I don't think you can judge it on the basis of 
fluctuations of the euro from this month to that,'' Blair told 
Britain's GMTV. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro's slump has left Blair open to criticism from political  
opponents for not ruling out a switch from the pound to the euro. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Adopt Departure Countdowns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airlines are starting to use strict boarding  
procedures to improve departure performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers are being told to be in their seats 10 minutes before  
takeoff. Five minutes beforehand, the cabin door is closed. At the 
scheduled departure time, the plane leaves the gates. 
</P>
<P>
	The two major U.S. carriers who have adopted or are adopting the  
policy say it will help them stick to their schedule. It also 
reflects the preferences of most passengers, who hate late 
departures, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being prepared to depart as soon as possible improves our  
position for takeoff clearance, which in turn improves the 
likelihood of an on-time arrival at our customer's destination,'' 
said Al Crellin, vice president of customer service for US Airways. 
</P>
<P>
	US Airways, the nation's sixth-largest airline and an East Coast  
mainstay, announced this week that it will adopt the ``10-5-take 
off'' policy on June 15. United Airlines, the largest U.S. carrier, 
initiated the move in April with a ``Time to Go'' campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Hopkins, a United spokesman, said the airline acted after  
market research showed passengers wanted punctual flights. Since 
the policy took effect, passenger praise has far outweighed 
complaints, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines have an interest in the policy change, Hopkins  
conceded, since it helps ensure that passengers won't miss their 
connections -- necessitating re-booking -- and that planes will be 
ready for their next trip. Getting everyone seated early also 
clarifies how many first-class seats are available for upgrades and 
how many standby passengers can be accommodated. 
</P>
<P>
	There's one more payoff: Punctuality helps the airlines score  
well in on-time and quality ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is information the government collects and publishes, and  
it's a competitive factor in the airline industry, so everyone is 
paying attention to it,'' said David Fuscus, spokesman for the Air 
Transport Association, a trade group for major airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines typically retain the right to cancel a seat assignment  
for anyone who hasn't checked in 20 minutes before the scheduled 
departure time. They also say that if passengers don't check in 10 
minutes beforehand, they lose their reservation and must take their 
chances as standbys. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers are being warned of the new policies with airport  
signs, notices in their frequent-flier mailers and mentions on 
airline Web sites. To ensure that the policy does not penalize 
passengers making connections, United last year expanded the time 
between its flights by five minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this policy, you can get people out on time and without  
the anxiety of wondering if they'll have time to make their 
connection,'' said Hopkins, the United spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers seem pleased.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been on a lot of flights where they've loaded up and then  
waited for late connections or folks dallying in the airport,'' 
said Dan Bartz of Milwaukee, who was waiting Friday at Washington's 
Reagan National Airport for a United flight to Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathy Weber of Chicago, sitting beside Bartz, said she agreed,  
although she did not want to see connecting passengers punished. 
She used to live in Milwaukee and frequently had to make 
connections. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it were a matter of accommodating them by waiting a few  
minutes, I would be in favor of that, having been on both sides,'' 
Weber said. 
</P>
<P>
	So what happens to passengers who get to the gate just before  
their scheduled departure time? If the ramp is still there, they 
may get on, despite the new policy. But if it's been pulled back, 
they're probably out of luck, said Hopkins. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want 179 people on a plane delayed because one  
person gets there at the last minute,'' he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0080 </DOCNO>
