<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Official Charged With Pound Burning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOLLAND, Mass. (AP) -- An animal control commissioner who had  
been trying to get the town to build a better shelter for strays 
has been charged with burning down the town's dog pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Patricia Mumper, 57, was charged Thursday with burning a public  
building. 
</P>
<P>
	No animals were in the four-stall lean-to shelter when it burned  
Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	State Trooper Michael Mazza, an investigator for the state fire  
marshal's office, said Mumper had argued with Paul Gillis, the 
chairman of the town's board of selectmen, over the condition of 
the pound shortly before the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillis said Mumper had threatened to take action that would  
embarrass the town He said he thought she might file a lawsuit or 
complain to the Humane Society. 
</P>
<P>
	Mumper did not return a telephone message seeking comment  
Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
