<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 05:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ron Polk Named Ga. Baseball Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Ron Polk, a four-time national baseball coach  
of the year, is returning to the dugout as coach at the University 
of Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Polk, 55, accepted the job Thursday, ending a two-year  
sabbatical that followed his 22-year career at Mississippi State. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the Georgia job came open, I asked myself, `Do you have  
one more challenge in you?''' he said. ``I said `yes.' This is 
where I want to be at this time in my life. I missed big-time 
working with the kids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Polk resigned in 1997 from Mississippi State after his sixth  
trip to the College World Series, citing ``coaching burnout'' as a 
factor. He stayed at Mississippi State as an associate athletic 
director and worked with the U.S. national team. 
</P>
<P>
	Working with the national team rekindled his desire to coach,  
Polk said. He said he told a former Georgia player he would be 
interested in the Bulldogs' job, and that player contacted Georgia 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one question I had was, did Ron really want to go back  
into coaching?'' Georgia athletic director Vince Dooley said. ``I 
could see the fire in his eyes. Baseball has been his life. You 
could tell that he missed coaching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia gave him a four-year contract that will pay him $80,000  
a year in base salary, Dooley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Polk succeeds Robert Sapp, who coached for three years at  
Georgia. The Bulldogs have been in a decline since 1990, when Steve 
Webber coached them to their only national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Sapp and Webber both coached under Polk at Georgia Southern.  
Polk started as a head coach there in 1972 and took the Eagles to 
the College World Series the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Polk's career record is 1,043-486, including 888-422 at  
Mississippi State, which went to the College World Series five 
times. He coached 12 future major leaguers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
