<DOCNO> APW19990604.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 16:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Familiar Foes Fight To Unify Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- Roy Jones Jr. and Reggie Johnson spent a  
lot of time this week saying nice things about each other. 
</P>
<P>
	The pleasantries are over and both say it could really get nasty  
when they meet Saturday night to unify the light heavyweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who holds the WBC and WBA light heavyweight  
championships, and Johnson, the IBF titleholder, believe they have 
been pointed towards this match for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always known Reggie can fight and we've always wanted the  
same things,'' Jones said. ``It was only a matter of time before we 
had to see which one of us got what we wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both fighters trained in Pensacola, Fla., early in their  
professional careers under the tutelage of Roy Jones Sr. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones Jr. said he grew uncomfortable with Johnson in his camp  
because he knew they would have to fight some day. His father's 
refusal to dump Johnson led to a split between the Joneses. But 
while they were together, their intense sparing sessions taught 
Johnson and Jones to respect each other's abilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of all the mountains I've had to climb, and the hurdles I've  
had to get over, this is the biggest,'' Johnson said. ``Roy is a 
great boxer and I like him, but I'm coming to win this thing and 
win big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Jones weighed in at 174 pounds, Johnson at 171,  
</P>
<P>
	There hasn't been an undisputed light heavyweight champion since  
Michael Spinks relinquished the title in 1985 to successfully 
campaign for the IBF heavyweight championship against Larry Holmes. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old Jones, a former IBF middleweight and super  
middleweight champion, won the WBC light heavyweight title in 1996, 
lost on a disqualification to Montell Griffin in 1997 and regained 
the title with a first-round knockout of Griffin later that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones added the WBA title by outpointing Lou Del Valle last July  
18. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 32, a left-hander, won the WBA light heavyweight title  
in 1992 and lost it in 1993. After failing twice to regain it, he 
became IBF champion by knocking out William Guthrie in the fifth 
round on Feb. 6, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who will defend his titles for the fifth time in the last  
year-and-a-half, is a heavy favorite to grab his third 
championship. Even Johnson acknowledges his underdog role. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the biggest fight of my life, and Roy's life too,''  
Johnson said. ``And I know what people expect. They call him the 
world's best boxer pound-for-pound, but I also know what I expect 
and I'm going to shock everyone. I can't predict a round. I can't 
say exactly how. But I know I'm going to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones also sees Johnson as his biggest challenge, but believes  
Saturday's fight will be his biggest victory as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it I'll knock him down or not, but from round  
one to round 12, I'll be doing a job on him,'' Jones said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 16:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Adjusted BCS Formula To Be Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DESTIN, Fla. (AP) -- The new formula for the Bowl Championship  
Series will be released later this month and its chairman said 
Friday there will be a few new wrinkles to the system that debuted 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Most notably, it will likely include additional computer  
rankings to go with those compiled by Jeff Sagarin, The New York 
Times and Seattle Times. 
</P>
<P>
	``That will give it a broader diversity of information,'' BCS  
chairman Roy Kramer said. ``The more information you put in, the 
better information you get, in most cases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer said he was pleased with the formula that landed  
Tennessee and Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Some football fans, however, felt alienated by a system that  
used complex math formulas -- nothing that could be done on a pad of 
paper at home -- to factor The Associated Press media poll, the 
coaches' poll, computer rankings, strength of schedule and overall 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer has steadfastly defended the system and says there are no  
plans to alter it dramatically. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Kansas State, UCLA, Florida and Ohio State all  
remained in contention for the top spot until late-season losses 
eliminated them. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee earned one spot in the Fiesta Bowl thanks to its  
undefeated record. The second spot came down to Florida State and 
Ohio State. The Seminoles got it because of a higher BCS ranking. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the last four or five weeks of college football last  
year, we had as much excitement and interest as we had in many, 
many years,'' Kramer said. ``We heard one guy on the radio applying 
the BCS standings to the NFL. That was the ultimate compliment. It 
certainly enlivened every call-in show in the country. From that 
standpoint, it worked.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:32:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  EU Summit Backfires Over Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- Plans for a show of support from all 15  
European Union leaders to bolster confidence in the battered euro 
backfired Friday when an EU summit produced a flip-flop that only 
added to market uncertainties over the new currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In a baffling turnaround, the leaders first produced a draft of  
a joint statement which said they were ``not at all concerned'' by 
the euro's weakness against the dollar. They deleted the passage 
from the summit's final communique. 
</P>
<P>
	The switch came amid mounting criticism that EU officials were  
contributing to the euro's decline by sending mixed signals about 
the currency, which has slipped by more than 11 percent since its 
adoption by 11 nations on Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	EU officials said the phrases were dropped at the request of  
Italy, France and Spain, who believed any written statement on the 
euro's slump would create an impression the leaders were overly 
worried by developments. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the council decides it doesn't want to discuss the euro in  
the document, there's nothing on the euro,'' Italian Prime Minister 
Massimo D'Alema told reporters. ``Bad information generates 
confusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other passages talking up the euro were also removed from the  
summit declaration, including one blaming the euro's frailty on 
differences in the business cycles between Europe and the United 
States that are ``likely to lessen over the course of this year and 
next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They also dropped a commitment ``to secure market confidence in  
the stability of the euro by a consistent economic and financial 
policy geared to stability and reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The euro lurched to new lows of $1.0270 in Asian markets and  
$1.0318 in late London trading, where it hit a new intraday low of 
$1.0296. The euro was worth $1.1668 when it first started trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopes of a peace deal in Kosovo did little to raise the euro's  
fortunes, although German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder expressed 
confidence Thursday that a possible end to the conflict ``will also 
have positive effects on the currency.'' The euro responded 
Thursday by hitting a then-intraday record low of $1.0303 before 
rising to $1.0350 late in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The summit muddle comes after markets punished recent  
conflicting signals from European officials about whether to shore 
up the euro, and a decision to allow Italy to overrun its budget 
deficit target despite repeated assertions that euro-zone nations 
must apply tight fiscal disciple. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the disadvantages of the euro, is that there's too many  
people talking,'' German Finance Minister Hans Eichel told 
reporters at the summit. ``This has to stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the euro's woes had not  
altered his aim of taking Britain into the single currency if the 
economic conditions are right. ``Our position on the euro has not 
changed and will not change,'' Blair told a news conference at the 
summit. ``It is in Britain's interests that the euro succeeds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The euro's plunge has left Blair open to criticism from  
political opponents for not ruling out a switch from the pound to 
the euro. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:32:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
