<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 06:20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Police Close Two Firing Ranges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A dangerous incident the cops are calling a  
``training mishap'' has prompted the District of Columbia to shut 
down two of its police department firing ranges. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Chief Charles H. Ramsey ordered the ranges closed 10 days  
after bullets from one of the facilities slammed into a residential 
neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	A dozen homes and three vehicles in Lorton, Va., were hit by  
submachine gun fire that came from the range at the Lorton 
Correctional Facility on May 24. No one was hurt, but some of the 
bullets came dangerously close to striking residents. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me it boiled down to a simple question: Would I feel  
comfortable with my own 12-year-old son playing in the backyard of 
one of the houses that was struck by the live fire from our range? 
It took me a nanosecond to know I would not,'' Ramsey said during a 
radio interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramsey called it a ``training mishap.'' He said officers were on  
their backs shooting up at targets at the time of the incident, and 
the angle of the shots caused the bullets to whiz over a dirt 
embankment. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the police chief said the mistake indicated that  
safety procedures must be overhauled at the range, and he closed 
the facility temporarily. But on Thursday, Ramsey said the only 
solution was to close it permanently. 
</P>
<P>
	He also announced that as a precautionary measure, officers  
would no longer be allowed to use the outdoor range at the 
department's police academy in Southwest Washington, but would 
instead use the facility's indoor range. 
</P>
<P>
	``Open-air live-fire ranges and populated residential areas  
simply do not mix,'' Ramsey said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 01:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> National League Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- What a showdown it would have been: Matt Mantei,  
throwing 100 mph, against Mark McGwire. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would have been nice,'' Mantei said. ``That's the  
situation you like to be in. Either I beat him with my best stuff, 
or he beats me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The matchup never materialized because McGwire left Thursday  
night's game in the sixth inning with tightness in his lower back. 
Willie McGee, batting in his spot, grounded out against Mantei with 
two runners on to end the game, and the Florida Marlins beat the 
St. Louis Cardinals 4-2. 
</P>
<P>
	In other NL games, San Francisco beat Philadelphia 7-4,  
Milwaukee defeated Houston 4-1 and Chicago tripped San Diego 7-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Mantei threw three consecutive 99 mph fastballs in the ninth.  
His first pitch to Edgar Renteria hit 100, and the crowd roared 
when the speed registered on the scoreboard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard everybody cheering,'' Mantei said. ``I looked up and  
said, `100 mph? Damn!''' 
</P>
<P>
	But after Mantei retired the first two batters, Joe McEwing  
singled and took third on a single by Renteria. That brought up the 
No. 3 hitter in the order, normally McGwire. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would have been a good matchup,'' Marlins interim manager  
Fredi Gonzalez said. ``I would have left the dugout. I didn't want 
to see that one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, McGee stepped to the plate. He hit a sharp grounder  
down the third-base line, but Mike Lowell made a backhanded stop 
and threw to first for the game-ending out. 
</P>
<P>
	``That guy made a great play,'' Cardinals manager Tony La Russa  
said. ``If he's not on the line, it's a tie game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mantei earned his sixth save in seven chances and lowered his  
ERA to 1.73. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was throwing hard, but who cares?'' Mantei said. ``Mike  
saved me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell, who missed the start of the season following surgery for  
testicular cancer, also hit his first major league homer, a two-run 
blow in the seventh, to give Florida a 3-2 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire hit a solo homer, his 17th, before leaving the game as a  
precaution. Mighty Mac said he expects to play tonight in Detroit, 
which is good news for the Cardinals because he's warming up with 
the weather. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire has nine homers in his past 14 games and needs one more  
to tie Stan Musial and Willie Stargell, who are 17th on the career 
list with 475. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Louis slugger's first-inning homer off Alex Fernandez  
landed in the upper deck and was estimated at 475 feet. He now has 
six career hits off Fernandez, and five of them are homers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He threw me a curve,'' McGwire said. ``I don't think I'm going  
to see many more of those.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire has eight homers in 10 career games at Miami.  
</P>
<P>
	Lowell's first homer came with Florida trailing 2-1. Preston  
Wilson was hit by an 0-2 pitch leading off the seventh, and Lowell 
followed with a home run off Darren Oliver (4-3). 
</P>
<P>
	``Hitting a home run is always special,'' Lowell said, ``and  
that was a pretty big moment in the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rookie was acquired last winter from the New York Yankees  
for three pitching prospects after they re-signed World Series MVP 
Scott Brosius. Lowell underwent surgery Feb. 21, started the season 
on the disabled list and joined the Marlins on May 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because I've been through cancer surgery and treatment,  
it makes a better story, but I try to separate it from baseball,'' 
said Lowell, 25. ``At this point, I'm just a young guy trying to 
prove myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Braden Looper (1-1), a former Cardinal, pitched two  
scoreless innings for his first major league victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver took a three-hitter into the seventh but couldn't get  
another out. He was charged with four runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made one mistake,'' he said, ``and that cost us the  
ballgame.'' 
</P>
<P>
                          *Cubs 7, Padres 2    	
</P>
<P>
	Sammy Sosa homered for the second straight day and took over the  
NL lead with 19 as Chicago won for the sixth time in seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa, who hit a major league record 20 home runs last June, has  
two this month and 15 home runs and 31 RBIs in his last 27 games. 
He hit a solo shot in the first off rookie Matt Clement (1-6), who 
then allowed Henry Rodriguez's three-run homer in a six-run second. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Tapani (5-2) allowed two runs and six hits in six innings  
at Wrigley Field. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Giants 7, Phillies 4    	
</P>
<P>
	Curt Schilling (8-3) failed to become the first pitcher with six  
straight complete games since Orel Hershiser in 1988, getting 
knocked out after seven innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Staked to a 4-1 lead after Philadelphia scored three in the  
sixth at Veterans Stadium, Schilling was rocked for four runs, four 
hits and a walk in the seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Kent was 2-for-5 with three RBIs, including a two-run  
single that tied it at 4 in the seventh. Ellis Burks drove in the 
go-ahead run with a sacrifice fly. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Spradlin (1-1) was the winner, and Robb Nen got three outs  
for his NL-leading 16th save. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Brewers 4, Astros 1    	
</P>
<P>
	Dave Nilsson homered twice and doubled as Milwaukee avoided a  
three-game sweep at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Woodard (5-5) gave up one run and six hits in six innings.  
Shane Reynolds (7-5) allowed four runs and nine hits in 5 2-3 
innings to lose for the third time in four starts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
