<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 12:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Springer Appears at Chicago Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Talk show host Jerry Springer appeared today  
before a Chicago City Council hearing, telling aldermen he knew 
little about the business arrangements behind his show and 
declining to disclose his salary. He said the ``roughhousing'' 
wasn't staged but should not be equated with a common street fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Alderman Edward Burke, a former policeman, called the hearing of  
the Police and Fire Committee. He said that if the fist fights, 
chair throwing and hair pulling on the controversial show are 
genuine, Chicago police should enforce the law, cuff the guests and 
haul them off to jail. 
</P>
<P>
	If it's staged, Burke suggested, ``The Jerry Springer Show''  
should be required to obtain a city entertainment license. The 
nationally syndicated show is taped in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	As the hearing got under way, some in the audience applauded  
Springer, a former mayor of Cincinnati, at times when he objected 
to some questioning, such as that about his salary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why would you get into that? That's none of your business,''  
Springer told Burke. ``If you want some money, I'll loan you 
some.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't work for you, sir,'' he said. ``I really don't. ...  
I'm trying to be very respectful but you're not the boss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burke had threatened to issue a subpoena but Springer appeared  
voluntarily. He said he was polite enough to show up when he heard 
about the hearing even though the alderman hadn't called him to 
invite him. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the violence on his show is staged or real, he  
responded, ``It looks real to me.'' He said there may have been 
some staged incidents over the years but that ``overwhelmingly, the 
show is real.'' He said the show attempted to portray any violent 
antics in a negative light. 
</P>
<P>
	Security on the show is provided by off-duty Chicago police  
officers. Burke says those officers are required by state statute 
to make arrests if they see violations of the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer said it would be up to the discretion of an officer on  
what antics might merit arrest, adding, ``When people are 
roughhousing, most of the time we don't take them to jail.'' He 
noted that a fight in a studio, with security present, the 
participants known and the cameras rolling, was different from a 
fight an officer might confront ``on the street late at night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The public gallery filled with dozens of Springer supporters  
applauded frequently. Alderman Dorothy Tillman told the gallery 
that they would be ejected from the meeting if the applause 
continued. However, it did little to quiet observers. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he didn't know a lot about such questions as the  
terms to the lease on the studio where the show is taped. He 
suggested Burke could have asked his producers directly. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are things I know a lot about, and there are things that  
are not my business,'' he said. ``I can't imagine Andy Griffith 
knew a lot about all the contracts and business arrangements of 
`The Andy Griffith Show.''' 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're interested in making a show here, and just beat up  
our show, that's fine. But you know you can get those answers, 
don't you? ... You don't have to be asking me. You know that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer agreed to eliminate the fighting on his show after  
numerous protests last year, but they returned when the show's 
ratings suffered. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
