<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cabletron Gets New CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Cabletron Systems, a computer networking  
company, named a new chairman and chief executive on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Piyush Patel, 43, former chief executive of a technology company  
acquired by Cabletron last year, will succeed co-founder Craig 
Benson as chairman, chief executive and president, the company said 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Patel said he wants to make Cabletron a leader in growing  
markets such as that for delivering voice, video and data. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cabletron has all the ingredients for future success,  
including an extremely loyal customer base, talented employees and 
award-winning technologies,'' Patel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Patel formerly was chief executive of Yago Systems, a closely  
held technology company. 
</P>
<P>
	Benson, who is also 43, had left Cableton several years ago only  
to rejoin it as chairman and CEO last year. 
</P>
<P>
	He praised Patel for ``demonstrated technology leadership ... a  
customer focus and a West Coast entpreneurial spirit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For most of the 1990s, Cabletron was a major player in the  
network hubs market, selling the powerful processors that link 
computers and related equipment into one local network. 
</P>
<P>
	But by last year, hubs were becoming obsolete, replaced by  
faster routers and switches that transmitted data across networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts said Cabletron has lost too much ground to  
competitors such as Cisco Systems and will have to be sold if it is 
to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares closed up 12 1/2 cents a share at $13.93 3/4 in trading Friday  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Esmeralda Silva, an analyst with IDC in Framingham, Mass., said  
the move could pave the way for major changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Craig is a great guy but he's still really viewed as the old  
Cabletron,'' she said. ``The best thing that could happen would be 
to get some fresh blood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But John Armstrong, an analyst with Dataquest in San Jose,  
Calif., said the leadership change isn't necessarily significant. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Benson was expected eventually to pass the reins.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
