<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disabled Hiring Standards To Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is eliminating the federal  
government's stricter hiring and promotion standards for the 
mentally disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	At an East Room awards ceremony today for private companies with  
exceptional track records in hiring people with disabilities, 
Clinton was announcing an executive order changing the civil 
service rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The move, White House officials said, was intended as a prelude  
to Tipper Gore's White House Conference on Mental Illness next 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The wife of the vice president, who has taken a higher policy  
profile in the White House since Al Gore began his presidential 
campaign in earnest, announced in January that the Office of 
Personnel Management would examine the government's 22-year-old 
hiring rules to eliminate barriers for the mentally disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's executive order, officials said, would change civil  
service rules to ensure that people with psychiatric disabilities -- 
schizophrenia, paranoia and others -- are covered by the same hiring 
and promotion standards that apply to people with physical 
disabilities and the developmental disabilities that accompany 
mental retardation. 
</P>
<P>
	A White House fact sheet, which estimated that more than 75  
percent of the psychiatrically disabled are unemployed, said the 
new action ``will level the playing field for individuals with 
psychiatric disabilities who are seeking employment and eliminate 
the institutional barriers that prevent them from bringing their 
enormous energy and talent to the work force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was also using the occasion today to press Congress,  
which returns to work next week after a Memorial Day recess, for 
action on the Work Incentives Improvement Act. The legislation, 
sponsored by Sens. Jim Jeffords, R-Vt., and Edward M. Kennedy, 
D-Mass., would allow people with disabilities to keep their 
Medicare or Medicaid health coverage when they return to work. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
