<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV Works on Remote Control Ordering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALAMEDA, Calif. (AP) -- You're watching the football game and a  
pizza commercial comes on. You pick up the remote, pop open an 
on-screen menu and order a medium pepperoni. Thirty minutes later, 
the doorbell rings and it's time to eat. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the dream of every couch potato -- and it may be getting  
closer to reality, thanks to a new interactive television 
technology called Wink that allows viewers to order products and 
get information through the cable boxes on top of their TV sets. 
</P>
<P>
	Wink programming is already available in Japan and is just  
making its way into the United States. Wink is now used in about 
120,000 homes in a handful of U.S. cities, and the California 
company that developed the technology hopes to expand its presence 
to 1.5 million households this summer in major cities including 
Chicago, New York and Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Wink got an important endorsement Friday when Microsoft Corp.  
said it would invest $30 million in the closely held company, 
joining other key investors like Paul Allen, a co-founder of 
Microsoft who has been amassing cable TV empire. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has its own interactive TV project, known as WebTV,  
which operates differently from Wink. As part of their arrangement, 
Microsoft and Wink will work together in developing common 
standards for interactive television, a collaboration that could 
help the fledgling technology spread. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not solving world hunger here, but we are offering  
American consumers an easy and free way to interact with their 
television using nothing more than their good old remote control,'' 
said Maggie Wilderotter, chief executive officer of Wink. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's how it works: If you're watching a show or commercial  
that has Wink features, you'll see a little icon with a cursive 
letter ``i'' in the corner of the screen. Then you can click a 
button on your remote, and up pops a little window offering you 
options for more information about the show or commercial you're 
watching. It's a little like ordering a pay-per-view movie. 
</P>
<P>
	The Weather Channel is offering extra information on local  
forecasts. On The Tonight Show, details about Jay Leno's guests 
pops up. On CNN, the top headlines scroll past while the main 
report continues. 
</P>
<P>
	So far the Wink system has industry analysts interested, though  
they remain a little skeptical. 
</P>
<P>
	Josh Bernoff, principal TV analyst at Forrester Research, said  
Wink has an advantage over potential competitors because its 
technology is already in place, and broadcasters and cable 
operators are cooperating. 
</P>
<P>
	The drawback, he says, is that the graphics viewers see are  
``extremely ugly'' -- simple text without the colorful and vivid 
pictures that viewers expect these days. ``Right now, what they're 
doing is a dress rehearsal,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he added, ``in the future, it wouldn't surprise me if there  
are millions of Wink users.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's what the networks hope. ABC, NBC and CBS are all creating  
Wink pop-up notes on a handful of shows, starting off with a few 
hours of programming to see how it catches on. 
</P>
<P>
	Several advertisers, including Procter &AMP; Gamble, Clorox and  
Charles Schwab, are also trying out Wink features in commercials 
that allow viewers buy products or request free samples and 
informational materials. 
</P>
<P>
	The system, backed by about $55 million in investments, began  
being developed in 1993, and now is supported by about 85 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Wink managers said their major challenges have been developing  
cheap software, convincing advertisers, cable companies and 
networks to try it, and finding a way to process orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Wink chairman Brian Dougherty, who developed the system, said  
manufacturers pay only a few dollars per set-top box, and consumers 
pay nothing. ``The cable operator pays a little bit extra to put 
this box in, then has all these new interactive revenue streams,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike other interactive television systems, Wink is free for  
consumers and isn't hooked up through telephone lines to the 
Internet. But analysts said Wink should expect competition from 
interactive systems also vying for viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Arlen Communications estimates that 15 to 20 percent of U.S.  
households will use some form of interactive TV services within the 
next eight to 10 years. By offering an inconspicuous and 
inexpensive technology, Wink hopes to get a big piece of that. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
