<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army-Navy Game Headed to Baltimore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- One of college football's top attractions, the  
Army-Navy game, will be played in Baltimore next year before 
returning to Philadelphia in 2001 and 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The 101st meeting between the service academies will be held  
Dec. 2, 2000 at PSINet Stadium. This year's game will be at 
Veterans Stadium in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Navy athletic director Jack Lengyel suggested that more games  
against Army will be played closer to Annapolis after the current 
arrangement expires in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``By then we'll have played four games at Jack Kent Cooke  
Stadium (home of the Washington Redskins). This will give us an 
opportunity to evaluate both stadiums for the future,'' Lengyel 
said. ``We want to serve our fans in this area, and we want to play 
on grass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Navy played Notre Dame last fall at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium and  
will use that facility for home games against Air Force in 1999, 
2001 and 2003. PSINet Stadium, home of the Baltimore Ravens, and 
Cooke Stadium have grass fields; Veterans Stadium in Philadelphia 
has artificial turf. 
</P>
<P>
	PSINet Stadium, which seats 69,400, was the site of two college  
football games last year -- a University of Maryland game and the 
Morgan State homecoming game. 
</P>
<P>
	The game will be the third Army-Navy game in Baltimore and the  
first since 1944. All but six of the games since 1932 have been 
played in Philadelphia -- three of those shifts were due to World 
War II travel restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, nine Army cadets were injured when a railing at  
Veterans Stadium collapsed. Lengyel said that id not precipitate 
the move to Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I came here in 1988, we renegotiated the contract with  
Philadelphia, giving us three opportunities to move games. We've 
been to Giants Stadium (East Rutherford, N.J.) twice, and I felt it 
was important to have one game closer for our fans,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia mayor Edward Rendell said city officials were not  
surprised at the move because the contract allows the service 
academies to shift venues every three years. The game was last 
played outside Philadelphia in 1997, and Rendell said the city 
would welcome the game back after its year in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Rendell also thinks that with a new stadium for the Philadelphia  
Eagles planned, the city won't have a problem in securing a new 
contract for future Army-Navy games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 00:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dave Matthews Has Two Broken Ribs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) -- Dave Matthews will be playing hurt --  
and probably with a new guitar -- when he performs a sold-out 
concert this weekend in this resort city. 
</P>
<P>
	The namesake of the Dave Matthews Band suffered two broken ribs  
in a bizarre grape-catching accident during some late-night 
horseplay in Boston last week, publicist Ambrosia Healy said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a silly accident,'' Ms. Healy said. ``They were  
throwing grapes and catching them in their mouths.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said Matthews fell back in his chair trying to catch a grape  
and landed on his guitar. 
</P>
<P>
	But the injury hasn't slowed him down, Ms. Healy said.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was in pain, but he totally rocked,'' she said. ``He would  
never let something like this get in his way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews will perform Saturday night at the Virginia Beach  
Amphitheater. 
  	   	
</P>
