<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Springer Appears at Chicago Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- To hear Jerry Springer tell it, he's been doing  
the country a favor by televising violence in all its unattractive 
glory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody watches our show and thinks, 'Wow, that's behavior that  
I think everyone's going to love,''' Springer said Friday at a City 
Council committee hearing. ``You do away with that and we'll go 
back to violence on television being totally sanitized.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer came to City Hall to answer aldermen's questions about  
``The Jerry Springer Show,'' and the rowdy guests the 
Chicago-produced program tends to attract. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer admitted there have been some staged incidents during  
the show's eight-year run. But ``overwhelmingly, the show is 
real,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alderman Ed Burke, a former policeman, has said that if the  
violence is real, off-duty Chicago police officers who work for 
Springer should cuff guests who get out of hand and haul them off 
to jail. If it's fake, he says Springer should get an entertainment 
license. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes vague, sometimes defiant, Springer held court amid  
cheering fans, hissing opponents and a block of as many as 20 TV 
cameras. 
</P>
<P>
	He drew applause when he objected to some of Burke's questions,  
including one about how much money he makes. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's none of your business,'' Springer replied.  
</P>
<P>
	When questioned about his producers allegedly bringing a banned  
felon into the country to appear on the show, Springer chose not to 
answer, saying, ``I've never been a member of the Communist 
party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's beautiful,'' yelled Jim Birmingham, a retired city  
worker and Springer fan who came to watch the hearing. ``Do it some 
more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though threatened with a subpoena, Springer came to the hearing  
voluntarily. But he said he thought the panel should be 
concentrating on more serious matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of difference in the violence that happens on  
the streets of Chicago and the roughhousing that takes place in our 
studio,'' Springer said, likening the fights on his show to brawls 
at a hockey game. 
</P>
<P>
	He said guests were free to file complaints against one another.  
The off-duty officers also have the discretion to make arrests -- 
and have done so on rare occasions. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the syndicated show's distributor issued an order  
forbidding fights and replaced some scheduled episodes with tamer 
shows -- an agreement that Springer has already reneged on once. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Michael Pfleger, a Catholic priest who prompted the  
committee to take up the matter, said he plans to hold distributor 
Studios USA Network to that promise. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, the aldermen tabled a resolution that would force  
officers to make arrests if real violence erupts. Alderman Dorothy 
Tillman called the hearing a waste of time. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really sat here and tried to turn it into `The Jerry  
Springer Show,''' Tillman told her colleagues. Then she turned her 
comments to Springer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jerry, through it all, you won.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 12:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 22-Year-Old Wants W.Va. Mayor Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRATT, W.Va. (AP) -- About all Wesley Nugent had in common with  
most of the people at the monthly town council meeting was senior 
status. 
</P>
<P>
	Nugent was a senior at West Virginia University. Most of his  
neighbors were senior citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Nugent was there recently to introduce himself as a candidate  
for mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	At 22, Nugent is Pratt's youngest ever candidate for chief  
executive, running in Tuesday's election against two of the 
community's oldest public servants: Mayor Paul Slack, 69, and 
former Mayor Gary Fields, 51. 
</P>
<P>
	His candidacy has created some much-needed excitement in this  
town of 640. 
</P>
<P>
	Win or lose, Nugent said he wants to show other young people  
that they can do something to help their hometowns in West 
Virginia's depressed coal regions instead of leaving the state to 
make a living. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can send a message against brain drain, it will be worth  
it,'' said Nugent, who has himself turned down job offers in 
Pittsburgh, Washington and North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Pratt and other coal country towns in West Virginia have been  
hit hard since the 1950s, first by the mechanization of coal 
mining, then by the closing of many of the mines once they were 
played out. A big round of closings took place in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Pratt's residents are retired or unemployed. Many of  
those who do work travel to places like Charleston, about 20 miles 
away, where they hold down low-paying jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, there were nearly 208,000 Kanawha County residents.  
Seven years later, the county had lost nearly 4,000 people. The 
population drain is blamed on a lack of good-paying jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, 62 percent of the WVU graduates who found work within  
six months had left the state. The trend is the same at other state 
colleges. 
</P>
<P>
	Nugent, who graduated last month with a degree in international  
studies, helped write successful grant proposals at WVU and wants 
to use those talents to land projects that can revitalize Pratt and 
create jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Nugent's campaign is a hot topic in Pratt, where neighbors share  
their opinions as they work in their yards or relax on their 
porches. 
</P>
<P>
	``The competition is healthy,'' Steven McGraw said. Still,  
McGraw said he plans to vote for Fields, his neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorothy Hastings, a lifelong Pratt resident, said: ``I have  
mixed feelings about that. You have to be experienced to be mayor 
or do anything else in life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fields said he is glad to see Nugent is getting into politics in  
his hometown but added that the young man needs more experience. 
</P>
<P>
	And Slack, the current, two-term mayor, said he is confident he  
will be re-elected. But he added: ``I hope after the election he 
still is interested in serving the town. We need more people 
involved in our town.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 16:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolls To Sport Baseball Uniforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Barbie is getting called up to the big  
leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	A new line of collector Barbie dolls will wear the home uniforms  
of the Los Angeles Dodgers, Chicago Cubs and New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Major League Baseball Barbie'' will hit store shelves by  
mid-June, said Nancy Zwiers, senior vice president of Barbie 
Collectibles at Mattel Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with authentic logos, pants, jerseys, caps, jackets and  
athletic shoes, the dolls will include a miniature glove, bat and 
ball. 
</P>
<P>
	The doll was designed to encourage girls to get involved in  
sports, said Tim Brosnan, of Major League Baseball's licensing and 
sponsorship division. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbie's 1999 collectible line also will include outfits  
featuring the Women's National Basketball Association, NASCAR auto 
racing and the Women's World Cup of Soccer. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Distance Runners Push Stanford </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- The men's field is chasing Stanford again on  
the final day of the NCAA track and field championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinal's distance runners had 37 points through Friday  
night as Stanford took the lead heading into today's final events 
with a total of 45 points. Last year, Stanford also led going into 
the last day, but Arkansas rallied in the sprints to capture its 
seventh straight title. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington State's Bernard Lagat won the 5,000-meter race in  
14:01.09, but right behind him was Brad Hauser of Stanford. His 
brother Brent finished fifth and Jason Balkman was eighth, giving 
Stanford 13 points in the event. Cardinal runners finished 1-2-3 in 
Wednesday's 10,000 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending women's champion Texas led with 31 points, but  
Southern Cal and UCLA were just three points behind. Southern 
Methodist had 25 points, followed by Georgia with 21, Pittsburgh 
20, Brigham Young 19 and Louisiana State 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The pace was relatively slow in the men's 5,000 meters, and when  
Lagat broke out with 800 meters to go, he knew the race was his. 
``In the last 800 meters, nobody can beat me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brad Hauser agreed. ``Bernard's got a great kick,'' he said.  
``He's very tough to catch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said his teammates were happy with 13 points in the event.  
``It's as good as we could have expected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford's Toby Stevenson added eight points with a second-place  
finish in the pole vault. He was the defending champion in the 
event, but Jacob Davis of Texas beat him on the final jump by 
clearing 18 feet, 2 3/4 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson was ranked fourth coming into the event. ``Eight  
points is great. The more the better,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford has won three national championships, but the last was  
65 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Stacey Bowers of Baylor won the women's triple jump at 45 feet,  
10 inches over Trecia Smith of Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	John Capel of Florida led semifinal qualifiers at 200 meters  
with his 20.37 second clocking, slightly ahead of Coby Miller of 
Auburn. Capel also had the best time among the 100-meter finalists 
with a wind-aided 10.05. BYU's Leonard Myles-Mills qualified at 
10.08, slightly ahead of Terrence Trammell of South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Latasha Jenkins of Ball State had the best 200 qualifying time  
among the women, 22.22 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Trammell ran a brilliant leg as the Gamecocks won the 400-meter  
relay over Southern Cal in 38.92 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor's Bayano Kamani won the 400-meter hurdles in 48.58, and  
Missouri's Derrick Peterson won the 800-meter run in 1:46.97. 
</P>
<P>
	Matti Narhi of UTEP captured the javelin title with a throw of  
261-7. Georgia's Vigdia Gudjonadotti won the women's title at 
182-3. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas women won the 400 relay in 42.95 seconds. UCLA's  
Joanna Hayes won the 400-meter hurdles in 55:16. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrie Tollefson of Villanova won at 3,000 meters with a time  
9:26.51 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	LSU's Claudine Williams won the 800-meter run in 2 minutes, 3.38  
seconds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Miller Says Knicks Are Whining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A war of words replaced the war on the  
basketball court Friday as the New York Knicks and Indiana Pacers 
waited to resume the Eastern Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after New York coach Jeff Van Gundy complained about the  
Pacers' play and the officiating, the Pacers responded by saying 
the Knicks should shut up and play basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no whining on our part. Everything is coming from  
their camp,'' said Reggie Miller, accused by Van Gundy of taking 
cheap shots at the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy also accused Rik Smits of taking a cheap shot and  
claimed referees are not allowing his point guards to play defense 
against Indiana's Mark Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York coach said he had called NBA vice president Rod  
Thorn about the play in the opening two games in the best-of-7 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller wasn't impressed.  
</P>
<P>
	``If they're going to call Rod Thorn and beg for calls, they  
need to look at themselves in the mirror. They're the ones that are 
doing all the hitting and the holding,'' Miller said. ``We're just 
trying to play basketball. ... It's too late in the season to be 
crying now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series is tied 1-1 with Game 3 in New York on Saturday. The  
Knicks will be without center Patrick Ewing, gone for the rest of 
the season with a partially torn Achilles tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have the advantage. They're the ones who won one here.  
We're trying to come into the Garden and win one,'' Miller said. 
``I don't understand where they're coming from. ... The good thing 
about is we play Saturday night and everything will resolve 
itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jalen Rose agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're a team that doesn't have to cry and whine. We're a team  
that is going to go out and play tough, give everything we have,'' 
Jalen Rose said. ``We have guys that are going to be aggressive, be 
physical. You have to be at this point of the season or you will be 
at home watching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana coach Larry Bird said Van Gundy's comments were directed  
at officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's trying to work the officials, which is good. It's all  
part of the game,'' he said. ``We say things how we feel. 
Obviously, he's not too happy right now. ... It's up to us to just 
go there and play basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rose didn't think Van Gundy's complaints would change the  
officiating for the rest of the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that officials get caught up in that too much.  
They're human, they do hear and see what is going on,'' he said. 
``At this point of the season you have veteran crews and guys who 
have been around the block, so they're going to call the game the 
way they see it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's game will only be the third one for Indiana in two  
weeks since it completed a sweep of Philadelphia in the semifinals 
May 23. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's been great for us,'' Bird said of the extensive  
time his team has had after the compacted 50-game schedule created 
after the NBA lockout ended. ``We got a lot of things accomplished. 
We put in some new stuff on the offensive end. We've had time to 
prepare and that should help us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
