<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clear skies were over most of the Northwest this morning and  
while some showers passed through the mid-Atlantic and Southeastern 
states. The Southwest may have to deal with unseasonably cool 
weather again today. 
</P>
<P>
	In Southern California on Thursday, light snow fell in the  
mountains, with cold rain and some hail elsewhere in gloomy weather 
better suited to midwinter than June. Meanwhile, tornadoes touched 
down in both North Dakota and Nebraska, with no serious damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Beautiful weather is expected in the Northeast today, with clear  
skies and dry conditions. Showers in the mid-Atlantic states and 
parts of the Southeast may be gone by this afternoon. However, in 
the deep Southeast, stormy, rainy weather remains a threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Pleasant weather in the central and northern Plains was expected  
to turn sour later in the afternoon as showers and thunderstorms 
move in the area. Hot, humid conditions were forecast for the 
southern Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacific Northwest is expected to have cloudy skies with a  
chance of precipitation. The desert Southwest was forecast to have 
unusually cool weather again today. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's forecast highs: in the 70s and 80s in the Northeast and  
the Midwest; in the 80s in the northern and central Plains, and the 
most of the Southeast; in the 50s, 60s and 70s in most of the 
Pacific Northwest and the Southwest; and in the 90s in the southern 
Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Extremes in the Lower 48 on Thursday were a high of 100 in Del  
Rio, Texas and a low of 28 in Redmond, Ore. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
