<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Know About Stanley Cup Flops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Six players on the Buffalo Sabres know what  
a Stanley Cup final is like. And all six know what it's like to 
flop. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts, man,'' defenseman Jason Woolley, Buffalo's leading  
scorer in the playoffs, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Woolley, Joe Juneau, Stu Barnes, Rhett Warrener, Alexei Zhitnik  
and Dominik Hasek have all been there. They understand the 
pressures, the distractions, the endless questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Five of those Sabres also know the embarrassment of being swept  
from hockey's showcase event. 
</P>
<P>
	Woolley played for the Florida Panthers when they were swept by  
Colorado three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts a lot, and I don't want to have that feeling again,''  
Woolley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Juneau was with the Washington Capitals when they were swept by  
Detroit last year. Barnes and Warrener played with Woolley when the 
Avalanche swept the Panthers in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek rode the bench behind Ed Belfour when Chicago was swept by  
Pittsburgh in 1992. Alexei Zhitnik played for the Los Angeles Kings 
when they were beaten in five games by the Montreal Canadiens in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in the final, I think it was eight years ago or seven, I  
don't even know,'' Hasek said. ``I don't remember too much. I was 
the backup. This year is a totally different experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes.  
</P>
<P>
	Zhitnik says all six players will build on their experience for  
the final, which begins Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody's angry,'' Zhitnik said.  
</P>
<P>
	Zhitnik vows not to be embarrassed.  
</P>
<P>
	``This could be my last chance,'' said Zhitnik, a native of  
Ukraine. ``I know this game is going to be shown all around the 
world. My friends are going to watch at home. I'm going to be 
hungry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Juneau scored Washington's winning goal to oust the Sabres in  
Game 6 of the Eastern Conference finals last season. He was happy 
when Washington traded him to Buffalo on March 23. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to have a chance at it again,'' Juneau said. ``With  
all the injuries with Washington we didn't have a chance to repeat. 
That's why I feel very lucky that Washington let me go with a team 
that had a chance to go far in the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff and assistant Mike Ramsey also were  
part of a Stanley Cup sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a little easier the second time around,''  
said Ruff, an assistant with Florida in 1996. ``You know you've got 
to keep your players focused and that there's a lot of media 
attention and a lot of things going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ramsey played for the Red Wings when they were swept by the New  
Jersey Devils in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Having failed to grab it once, Zhitnik knows what it takes to  
capture the Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kill to win,'' he said. ``Do anything possible -- score, block  
the shots, play physical, even if you're not a physical player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warrener says Buffalo is bound to last longer than the 1996  
Panthers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's scary because you know you're only going to get a couple  
shots at this thing,'' he said. ``I've been there once and I didn't 
make the most of it. I don't want to waste it this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woolley says there's a lot to handle both on and off the ice.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know exactly what I'm getting into, from the media exposure  
to focusing properly and handling the tickets and handling the 
family,'' he said. ``It's something that our young guys are going 
to have to pick up and learn real fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, maybe the biggest lesson to be learned from a crash  
in the Cup final is to forget it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to be thinking about the past,'' Woolley said.  
``I'm not going to be thinking about the last time I was there. I'm 
just going to be going forward and trying to win this thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``You really have to cherish this. It's a very special moment.  
And to win, man, how cool that would be?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 06:10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Costs To Keep Congress Running </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Overall spending for the annual bill that finances Congress' own  
operations dropped when Republicans took control in 1995, but is 
growing beyond where it was under Democrats: 
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1995 (last year under Democratic control): $2.4 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1996 (first year of GOP control): $2.2 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1997: $2.2 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1998: $2.3 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1999: $2.4 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 2000: (according to Senate Appropriations Committee  
allocation): $2.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Money provided for House members' office salaries, mail, rent  
and other expenses has also grown. This account is called 
``members' representational allowances,'' and is set by a formula 
that includes number of postal customers in each district. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1995: $351 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1996: $361 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1997: $363 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1998: $380 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 1999: $385 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 2000 (House bill): $414 million.  
</P>
<P>
	According to the National Taxpayers Union, in 1997 -- the most  
recent year it has analyzed -- Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, spent more 
from his office account than any other representative, $1,022,807. 
The now-retired Rep. Bill Redmond, R-N.M., spent the least, 
$572,749. 
</P>
<P>
	Most House members, however, did not spend their entire office  
accounts. The taxpayers union study found that 79 House members 
spent at least 99 percent of their account. Rep. Bob Schaffer, 
R-Colo., spent the smallest portion, 62 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Raids Don King's Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Federal agents raided the offices  
of boxing promoter Don King on Friday as part of an investigation 
into whether the IBF sold rankings and arranged fights for 
kickbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI agents entered the offices of Don King Productions with  
empty boxes. A boxing industry source, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, told The Associated Press they were looking for records 
involving the International Boxing Federation, Don King Productions 
and Monarch Productions, a company run by King's son, Carl. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal grand jury in Newark, N.J., has been investigating the  
International Boxing Federation for several months -- even before 
the disputed draw in March between Evander Holyfield and Lennox 
Lewis, which prompted New York law enforcement agencies to start 
their own investigations of the IBF. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI would not confirm the raid at King's office in Deerfield  
Beach, about 40 miles north of Miami, was linked to the IBF 
investigation or if the search would be completed Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I can tell you is we are serving search  
warrants on his offices as part of an ongoing investigation,'' FBI 
spokesman Mike Faregas said. 
</P>
<P>
	King spokesman Greg Fritz did not immediately return a call for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for IBF president Bob Lee Sr., said Friday he knew  
nothing about the FBI raid and refused to say what he knew about 
King's possible involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 18, the Los Angeles Times quoted boxing promoters and  
managers as saying the sport's sanctioning bodies sometimes sell 
the rankings that lead to more lucrative bouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times reported that witnesses have testified before the  
federal grand jury in New Jersey that some payments to the 
sanctioning bodies were made in cash, but that others were less 
obvious, such as those contained in overpayments of standard fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, HBO president Lou DiBella denied King's  
assertion that a rematch was set between Evander Holyfield and 
Lennox Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	And sources close to the negotiations, speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said one of the stumbling blocks was the possibility 
King could be indicted. 
</P>
<P>
	DiBella said there were ``some problematic issues that need to  
be worked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	HBO has insisted King step aside as the fight promoter if he  
were to be indicted on charges stemming from a number of 
investigations, sources close to the negotiations told the AP. So 
far, King has refused such a clause in the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile in Newark, federal grand jurors have subpoenaed all  
IBF records since 1982 on rankings and contracts for fights, as 
well as checks, invoices, expense forms and telephone records, its 
attorney has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors, citing grand jury secrecy, will not  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald Krovatin, the lawyer for Lee, said he does not want to  
give ``any sort of credibility'' to rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boxing itself seems to be a sport that is awash in rumors and  
innuendo and false allegations and rivalries and jealousies and 
paybacks and those sorts of things,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IBF and two other sanctioning groups -- the World Boxing  
Association and World Boxing Council -- set rules and rankings that 
play a large role in determining bouts. Boxers who defy the groups 
risk losing the chance to be declared a champion and earn large 
purses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
