<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Stadium Cited for Liquor Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Veterans Stadium concession operators have  
been cited for allegedly serving beer to a minor, an offense that 
could result in the venue used by the Phillies and Eagles being 
fined or even losing its liquor license for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Liquor Control Board cited Veterans Stadium Associates  
for serving beer to a 17-year-old during the Phillies' April 12 
season-opener, board spokeswoman Bettina Bunting said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The board launched a probe after nearly a dozen Philadelphia  
high school students started a brawl that was broadcast on national 
television. Investigators talked to six youths identified from 
television clips, and each explained that the students had been 
drinking before the game in the parking lot and during the game. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges stem from one juvenile who told police he bought  
beer from three different concession stands in Veterans Stadium, 
Bunting said. The youth will not be charged. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not saying it was only one minor. We only have concrete  
evidence that it was a juvenile,'' Bunting said. 
</P>
<P>
	Penalties for the offense range from a $1,000 fine to loss of  
the liquor license for one year. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium's parent company, Ogden Entertainment, said  
concession workers are trained to ask for proof of age from anyone 
under 30 who is buying beer. 
</P>
<P>
	``In more than 10 years of serving millions of fans, we have  
never had a report of this kind and therefore we take it very 
seriously,'' Ogden said in a statement. ``We pledge to maintain the 
strictest standards of responsible alcohol serving at the Vet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An administrative judge is expected to consider the charges in  
the next two months. If the license is revoked, Ogden must reapply 
for a liquor license after one year, Bunting said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Edward G. Rendell said he hoped a compromise could be  
reached, if the stadium is found guilty of serving beer to a minor. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's any other feasible controls we can put in ... you  
don't want to ban the sale of beer at a game,'' he said. ``A lot of 
people, of course, enjoy going to a game, having a hot dog and a 
beer, and they act very responsibly.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 08:40:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Emphasizes AOL-Netscape Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A government witness in the Microsoft trial  
today offered what he said was ``a plausible suggestion'' to answer 
questions raised about how Netscape's top executive described under 
oath the declining health of his company because of its battle with 
the software giant. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has used newly disclosed documents this week to argue  
that America Online Inc.'s recent purchase of Netscape 
Communications Corp. illustrates how competition in the high-tech 
industry is robust and federal intervention is not needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge urged the Justice Department's David Boies on Thursday  
to focus his questioning at least partly today on the AOL 
documents, saying there was ``some very interesting information in 
there that I hope for you to revisit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft used one such document to raise questions about the  
testimony last October from James Barksdale, Netscape's chief 
executive, who said under oath that Microsoft had crippled his 
ability to distribute Internet software. 
</P>
<P>
	But weeks later, in a far healthier assessment, Netscape told  
its investment bankers its software was included on more than 
one-fifth of the machines sold by the nation's computer makers and 
given away by almost one-fourth of the 20 largest Internet 
providers. 
</P>
<P>
	Netscape also told the bankers overseeing its $10 billion sale  
that computer makers were distributing its software for ``no 
compensation,'' and that consumers were downloading roughly 160 
million copies of the Web browser annually, according to the newly 
disclosed documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin Fisher, an economist testifying for the government,  
said today that Netscape might have been telling bankers that its 
software was distributed by computer makers whose total sales 
account for more than one-fifth the nation's computers, but that 
its software was not necessarily included on all those models of 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher called that a ``plausible suggestion'' but acknowledged  
he didn't know how Netscape arrived at the figures it cited to its 
bankers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher also scoffed at Netscape's claims to its bankers about  
160 million downloads annually, citing one estimate that in 1998 
there were only 67.5 million computers in the United States 
connected to the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``That number (160 million) is way too big,'' Fisher said,  
calling it ``totally, totally inconsistent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyers contend that Microsoft wielded its influence  
among computer makers to discourage them from distributing 
Netscape's browser and, in some cases, paid Internet providers to 
give its own software to their subscribers rather than Netscape's. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporting those claims, Barksdale told the judge last October  
that computer makers and Internet providers represented more than 
half the total distribution for Web software in the industry, ``and 
we're basically out of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Microsoft charged that Netscape told its investment bankers  
more than twice as many new computers included its software than 
Barksdale had represented to the judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I have seen numbers around -- this is a new PC shipped  
worldwide -- I believe it's around 10 percent,'' Barksdale testified 
in October. 
</P>
<P>
	But documents Microsoft cited in court Thursday, dated just  
weeks after Barksdale testified, showed Netscape telling its 
bankers, ``Estimate client on 22 percent of OEM (computer) 
shipments with minimal promotion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said Thursday that he believed the numbers Netscape gave  
to its bankers might have been exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the documents also appeared to contradict statements by  
AOL Chairman Steve Case and others, who maintained that AOL was 
more interested in buying Netscape's Web site than its Internet 
browser software. 
</P>
<P>
	Case told Microsoft lawyers last month under oath that AOL ``did  
not buy Netscape because of the browser business. We bought 
Netscape in some ways despite the browser business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a slide presentation from AOL's investment bankers last  
November repeatedly describes the company's upcoming plans for the 
Netscape browser, including a proposal to ``extend browser to be a 
more comprehensive desktop application ... with the goal of 
becoming user's de facto environment.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Portrayed as Clinton Clone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Electing Al Gore president in 2000 would be  
like giving President Clinton another four years in office, and 
that's something the nation ``can't afford,'' the head of the 
Republican National Committee says. 
</P>
<P>
	RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson spoke to a weekly public forum in  
Cleveland on Friday and focused his remarks on attacking Vice 
President Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson criticized Gore for strongly supporting Clinton during  
the president's impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the vice president was part of an administration under  
which China stole nuclear weapons' secrets while the Clinton-Gore 
campaign took contributions tied to the Chinese military. And he 
accused Gore of being in the grip of teachers' unions on education 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson took a poke at Gore for embellishing his non-political  
jobs and life experiences while on the campaign trail. ``There's 
only one man in America with more life experience -- Forrest Gump,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Describing the GOP as the party of ``lower taxes, less  
government, more freedom, stronger defense and better schools,'' 
Nicholson challenged Gore to set out his positions on tax cuts and 
military spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact of the matter is that electing Al Gore means giving  
Bill Clinton a third term,'' Nicholson said. ``The American 
presidency can't afford it. The integrity and character of that 
office -- and of American leadership -- can't afford it, nor we, as 
taxpayers and citizens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Roger Salazar declined to respond directly to  
Nicholson's remarks but said he wasn't surprised the vice president 
was drawing Republican criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since they see the vice president as a strong candidate, they  
focus their attacks on him,'' Salazar said. ``They have nothing of 
substance to offer on their own. All they can offer are attacks.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
