<HEADLINE> Levin Named AP National News Editor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ann Levin, a supervising editor for The  
Associated Press, has been promoted to national news editor. 
</P>
<P>
	Levin will work with AP editors in all 50 states and supervise  
AP's national news desk at the cooperative's headquarters in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment was announced Thursday by AP Managing Editor Jon  
Wolman. 
</P>
<P>
	Levin joined the AP in Newark, N.J., in 1989 after working as a  
reporter for the The Tribune in San Diego. Before that, she was a 
reporter for two Texas newspapers, the Tyler Morning Telegraph and 
the Port Lavaca Wave. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1994 Levin has been the key supervisor of AP's main news  
report for morning newspapers in the United States. Last fall she 
served briefly as acting correspondent in Sacramento, Calif., in 
charge of that state's political coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Levin, 45, graduated from Smith College and received a master's  
degree in English from the University of Texas at Austin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
