<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Fortunes Suddenly Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The landscape was looking bleak for President  
Clinton. His poll ratings had slipped, NATO's resolve was being 
strained and the conflict with Yugoslavia seemed mired in 
stalemate. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton's fortunes changed swiftly with Belgrade's agreement  
to a peace plan after 72 days of airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The man who beat impeachment, frustrated a Republican majority  
in Congress and helped send two Republican House leaders packing 
appears to have scored another political victory. Against long 
odds, he seems to have succeeded in defying both the critics and 
the conventional wisdom that you can't win a war merely with bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	For a president pursuing a legacy, it's a big boost.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's always been lucky,'' said Henry Graff, presidential  
historian at Columbia University. ``When I think of the things he's 
stepped into and the problems he's had -- he's a survivor. I think 
people will say he fought a war and didn't lose a single man. That 
has to be a plus in all the World Almanacs hereafter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the final verdict isn't in. Clinton himself questions  
whether Slobodan Milosevic really will keep his promise to withdraw 
all Serb forces from Kosovo and allow the return of hundreds of 
thousands of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics grumble about the cost of the airstrikes, the price tag  
for rebuilding Kosovo and the fact that Milosevic remains in power. 
</P>
<P>
	Budget surpluses that were eyed for tax cuts or social programs  
have been whittled down by billions of dollars. Clinton still is 
being second-guessed about his early decision not to use ground 
troops -- an announcement some say may have given Milosevic false 
hopes of surviving NATO's onslaught. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still don't know what the endgame is going to be,'' said  
Princeton political scholar Fred Greenstein. ``The endgame for 
George Bush on Iraq finally was that Saddam Hussein is still in 
power. What we now have at the very best will be a major occupying 
force that will make it possible for Albanians to get back into a 
ravaged area where the United States and Europe will subsidize 
them. And a Yugoslavia which had a horrendous economy to begin 
with, which now has its infrastructure destroyed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton managed to cement a remarkable consensus in NATO  
that Milosevic must be stopped from his campaign of terror, 
violence and ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidents and prime ministers who often quarrel about sensitive  
issues seemed amazed at times that their fraternity of 19 sovereign 
nations somehow held together. There was bickering about a ground 
invasion, differences over a naval blockade and suggestions for 
bombing pauses. But Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair 
kept their partners in line. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a guy who is said to be totally dictated by the polls, to  
be completely opportunistic, to lack spine, he did get involved in 
this one eventually,'' Greenstein said of Clinton. ``I think he 
comes out well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just an incredibly wily politician who is very good when  
he's on the defensive and not very good when he's got kind of a 
clear path ahead of him,'' Greenstein said. ``There is some luck 
here. He's sort of endlessly bouncing back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The apparent end of the conflict is also a political blessing  
for Vice President Al Gore, hoping to win the Democratic 
presidential nomination next year and succeed Clinton in the White 
House. Gore would not have been helped if the air war had dragged 
on or -- worse yet -- American troops had invaded Kosovo and suffered 
casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	If peace holds, Clinton's poll ratings likely will recover. His  
job approval rating had slipped 10 points or more to the lower 50s 
amid concerns about bombing accidents, a ground invasion and the 
uncertainty of the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether higher poll ratings give Clinton more clout is  
questionable, though, since his term is running out, the 2000 
campaign is approaching and many Republicans burned by impeachment 
revile him. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the apparent victory over Milosevic, they are not  
clinking champagne glasses at the White House. There is relief but 
also a deep sense of caution. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you gloat,'' said Graff. ``It's caused too much  
civilian loss. It's cost so much money. It isn't a clear-cut 
victory. We didn't get Milosevic. It's very hard to gloat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EDITOR'S NOTE -- Terence Hunt has covered the Reagan, Bush and  
Clinton presidencies for The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
