<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ADs Call Agents a Growing Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DESTIN, Fla. (AP) -- Nearly two years ago, it was Alabama, not  
Florida, handling a problem involving improper contact between 
sports agents and players. 
</P>
<P>
	It took the Crimson Tide about a month to investigate and  
dismiss star defensive lineman Michael Myers, just one game into 
his senior season. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of cementing his position as a sure first-round draft  
pick, Myers' stock plummeted. Because he didn't play the final four 
months of his senior season, Myers gained weight, lost his form and 
fell to the fourth round of the NFL draft. 
</P>
<P>
	A lesson learned?  
</P>
<P>
	Not even close.  
</P>
<P>
	``I worry every day that we're going to get another call about  
another problem,'' said Alabama Athletic Director Bob Bockrath. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question that we did the right thing. But I have no  
doubt that what we did won't change our situation in terms of the 
possibility of getting in trouble again. Anytime you have a top 
program with top athletes, you always run the risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That sense of foreboding permeated the annual meeting of SEC  
athletic directors and coaches. The theme seems to be unanimous: 
agents on campus continue to pose a major problem, one the schools 
have little means of policing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It continues to grow each year and unfortunately, it's almost  
a clandestine operation,'' said SEC Commissioner Roy Kramer. ``It's 
almost like parasites grab onto these young people at a very early 
age, at a very early stage in their career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Florida, university police are investigating whether sports  
agent Tank Black illegally gave money to former Gators, including 
linebacker Johnny Rutledge and defensive linemen Jevon Kearse and 
Reggie McGrew. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Rutledge admitted he received $500 per month over  
the span of a year in exchange for a promise to sign with Black. 
</P>
<P>
	Black denies any wrongdoing. His attorney says Rutledge and  
Kearse initially told investigators they had not accepted money, 
but they were coerced into changing their stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida Athletic Director Jeremy Foley said he has yet to hear  
of a solution to a decades-old problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue isn't just cropping up now and it's not just a  
problem at the University of Florida,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kids knew the rules, the agents knew the rules. You can't  
have everybody under 24-hour guard. This is a very easy 
conversation to have, but what are the answers? What would you 
suggest?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foley said Florida reacted as soon as it learned of possible  
improper contact, notifying the SEC and NCAA and turning the 
investigation over to school police. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA and SEC agree that was the right thing to do.  
</P>
<P>
	``The brave thing about Florida is that they reported it right  
away,'' said SEC compliance officer Jim McCullough. ``But 
institutionally, how is any school going to handle something like 
this? I don't know if they can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama reported its case immediately, with fresh memories of  
how bad things can go when an agent issue is mishandled. In 1993, 
the NCAA placed the Crimson Tide on probation mishandling a case 
involving defensive back Antonio Langham. 
</P>
<P>
	Langham signed with an agent after Alabama's 1993 Sugar Bowl  
victory and played the next season. The NCAA said that when Alabama 
found out, it tried to cover up the case instead of coming clean. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Bockrath replaced Hootie Ingram as athletic director.  
</P>
<P>
	But a change in administration doesn't necessarily change the  
atmosphere on campus -- at the dormitories and apartments where 
agents and their runners connect with players. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to get into the system, get to the athlete, the  
family, the roommate and find a way to corrupt them,'' Kramer said. 
``None of them do this with great sums of money. That's the sad 
part in many cases. It's just a few hundred dollars and they're 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Alabama toughened its agent law, making agents  
financially liable if their actions result in financial losses for 
schools and adding penalties of up to 20 years in prison and a 
$5,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, a law passed in 1994 carries a penalty of up to five  
years in prison and a $5,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Kramer knows enforcement is a different matter.  
</P>
<P>
	He says the issue comes down to trust -- asking for  
responsibility from players who sign statements saying they haven't 
taken and won't take money until they graduate. 
</P>
<P>
	That offers little comfort to the men in charge.  
</P>
<P>
	``Michael Myers signed all those papers, he went to all those  
workshops,'' Bockrath said. ``All that is, is an effort that covers 
you if something goes wrong. But the truth is, it doesn't give me 
any piece of mind.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 10:07:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Internet Connections Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Europeans are getting wired, with the number of  
household and business Internet connections nearly doubling last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Dataquest Inc. reports 10 percent of Western European households  
were connected last year, up from five percent in 1997, according 
to today's edition of The Wall Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	About 36 percent of U.S. households were online at the end of  
1998, Dataquest says. 
</P>
<P>
	Business connections in Europe increased to 9.5 percent, up from  
five percent the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany led the way online both at home and work with 24  
percent, and the United Kingdom was second with 17 percent, the 
Journal reported. The fastest growth was in Russia, France and 
Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Online connections in Europe were boosted in part by increased  
activity among Internet service providers, Dataquest said. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Jose, Calif.-based market research company predicts  
cheap broadband services will continue to fuel growth in Europe, 
likely increasing Internet penetration in Western European 
households to 17 percent and in businesses to 16 percent by the end 
of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The critical point to attract mainstream advertisers and  
businesses to the Internet is about 20 percent, Dataquest senior 
analyst Petra Gartzen told the Journal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
