<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utilities Give Early Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Electric utilities provided preliminary  
figures Friday on toxic chemical releases from coal-burning power 
plants, but did not include information on mercury, a 
cancer-causing chemical that has been the subject of growing health 
concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The Edison Electric Institute said reports from two-thirds of  
the coal-burning power plants showed 355,000 tons of toxic releases 
last year. About two-thirds of the total was hydrochloric or 
sulfuric acid, which pose little direct health concern when 
released into the air at low concentrations. 
</P>
<P>
	The institute, which represents investor-owned utilities, also  
said the coal plants released 64,000 tons of barium, 16,000 tons of 
manganese and 4,700 tons of nickel. Most of these heavy metals were 
found in ash usually disposed of in the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning this year, the utilities must report to the  
Environmental Protection Agency toxic releases from coal- or 
oil-burning power plants. The EPA will include the information in 
its annual toxic inventory report next year. In all, more than 600 
chemicals are covered, but industry officials predict their plants 
will be involved with only a few dozen. 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers provided Friday covered only seven chemicals because  
those were all that would be required of utilities at this time 
under the reporting thresholds currently in effect, said Paul 
Bailey, EEI's director for environment. Some of those thresholds, 
including the one for mercury, are likely to be reduced before the 
reporting is completed, however. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists criticized the industry group for not  
reporting mercury releases. It is believed that utilities account 
for about 50 tons of mercury emissions annually. Mercury is a 
persistent toxic chemical that is considered by many health experts 
to be dangerous at even low doses because it accumulates over long 
periods of time in fish and in humans. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA does not require reporting on mercury emissions unless a  
plant releases more than 25,000 pounds. However, the agency is 
considering lowering the threshold to 10 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, seven northeast utilities, breaking with the  
rest of the industry, said they would favor the government setting 
federal limits on mercury releases from power plants as part of a 
program cutting nitrogen oxide and sulfur emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey said release data on mercury was not included because no  
plant released more than 25,000 pounds of it, making it exempt 
under the current threshold from Toxic Inventory Reporting 
requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	While there may be large amounts of toxic chemicals released --  
386 million pounds of hydrochloric acid, for example -- the 
concentrations are ``below levels that present a public health 
concern,'' Bailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry group provided only aggregate numbers and no  
release data from specific plants. 
</P>
<P>
	The group also cited an EPA report to Congress last year that  
concluded the cancer risks from power plant releases is exceedingly 
low -- a chance of less than one in a million of an additional 
cancer during a lifetime. 
</P>
<P>
	But Frank O'Donnell of the Clean Air Trust, an environmental  
group, accused the utilities of trying to ``control the spin'' on 
the toxic emissions issue and ``deceive the American public about 
the real impact of power company pollution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	EPA Administrator Carol Browner, meanwhile, has made clear that  
the agency considers the potential health risk from persistent, 
bioaccumulative chemicals such as mercury as a significant area of 
concern. And the agency wants utilities to provide more information 
on releases of mercury and other toxic chemicals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
