<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 05:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> President of Chicago School Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The president of the University of Chicago, who  
came under fire for plans to reduce the number of required courses 
and improve campus facilities, has announced that he will resign 
and return to teaching next year. Officials said his plans would go 
forward anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Hugo Sonnenschein, 58, wrote in an open letter to students and  
faculty Thursday that he will teach economics at the university 
because ``it is time for another president, one who is less a 
symbol of change, to carry the momentum forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sonnenschein came to the university six years ago from  
Princeton, succeeding the retiring President Hanna Holborn Gray. He 
had put together a plan aimed at attracting the students who might 
normally favor schools seen as having a more diverse campus life, 
such as Harvard, Yale and Princeton. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics at the high-minded university saw the changes as a  
plot to dumb-down an institution where more Nobel laureates -- 70 -- 
have taught, researched or studied than anywhere else in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonnenschein said the criticism had nothing to do with his  
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have largely accomplished the things I set out to do,'' he  
said. ``I feel more than ever that because they stood up to 
scrutiny that they are the right things, and now time will tell how 
they work out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alum Robert Stone, who founded Concerned Friends of the  
University to oppose Sonnenschein's changes, said he hopes the 
university's ``current misguided strategy can be re-evaluated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Howard Krane, chairman of the university's 45-member board  
of trustees, defended Sonnenschein's leadership and said ``we're 
not changing course'' on his plans for the school's future. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
