<DOCNO> APW19990604.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 21:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, Serb Military To Confer  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO, Serb and Russian military  
leaders were to meet Saturday to plan for the withdrawal of 
Yugoslavian forces from Kosovo. The meeting was to take plac at the 
Kosovo-Macedonia border. The Pentagon said allied bombing of 
Yugoslavia could end by Sunday if President Slobodan Milosevic 
keeps his promise on withdrawals. ``We will not stop until we see 
the beginnings of a rapid, complete, and verifiable withdrawal of 
those Serb forces,'' a NATO spokesman said in Belgium. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Lauds Mexico Anti-Crime Bid  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno praised Mexico's  
crime-fighting efforts Friday after a Cabinet-level meeting between 
the two nations. At annual meetings of the Binational Commission, 
the two sides promised further cooperation. The sessions, involving 
13 Cabinet officials from both countries, reached agreements on 
topics ranging from airline fares to splitting money seized from 
drug traffickers. 

</P>
<P>
	Haiti Accident Kills 2 US Soldiers  
</P>
<P>
	PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- A U.S. military truck went off a  
Haitian road and overturned Friday, killing two American soldiers 
and injuring 14 others, U.S. officials and witnesses said. The 
2 1/2-ton truck overturned about 8 miles from the Port-au-Prince 
airport. The vehicle from the U.S. support group in Haiti was 
headed to a ceremony celebrating the completion of a humanitarian 
construction project, said a Pentagon spokesman. 

</P>
<P>
	Co-Pilot: Approach Was Fine  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The co-pilot of an American Airlines  
jetliner that crashed in Arkansas said Friday the approach appeared 
fine, but they could not stop on a rain-slickened runway. First 
Officer Michael Origel, recovering from a broken leg, spoke to 
investigators. The jet skidded off the runway, hit a bank of lights 
and crashed into a steel walkway. The plane broke into three 
pieces, killing eight passengers and the pilot. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Seized in Tiananmen Square  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- On the 10th anniversary of its crackdown on  
pro-democracy demonstrations, China kept a close watch Friday on 
Tiananmen Square. Police, on alert to prevent public mourning, 
arrested at least two people. Near the capital, more than 20 
relatives of five victims of the 1989 assault held a commemorative 
gathering under police guard. In Hong Kong, the only place in China 
where commemoration of the Tiananmen protests were allowed, 
thousands gathered for a candlelight vigil. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Appoints Gay Ambassador  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bypassing Senate confirmation, President  
Clinton moved Friday to directly install gay businessman James C. 
Hormel as ambassador to Luxembourg. The president invoked a 
provision of the Constitution allowing him to make such 
appointments during a congressional recess. Hormel, 66, who will 
become the first openly gay U.S. ambassador, can serve in the 
diplomatic post through the end of 2000. He is an heir to the 
Hormel food fortune. 

</P>
<P>
	Calif. Blocks Sale of Payroll Data  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Citing privacy concerns, Gov. Gray  
Davis Friday blocked a law from taking effect that would have 
allowed the state to sell confidential payroll data to private 
lenders. The law allows a state agency to sell personal financial 
information to banks, car dealers and other lenders to help them 
verify an applicant's income, with the applicant's written 
permission. It was intended to expedite loan applications. The 
measure, signed by the former Republican governor, was designed to 
take effect later this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes 136.15 Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices rose smartly on Wall Street Friday as the  
government reported that inflation and the economy weren't running 
rampant after all. The Dow Jones industrial average ended up 136.15 
points at 10,799.84, For the week, the Dow was up 240.10. On the 
NYSE, gainers led losers 1,827-1,097. The battered Nasdaq composite 
index rose 75.02 to 2,478.34, its fifth-largest point gain ever. 

</P>
<P>
	Stars Win, Go To NHL Finals  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Mike Keane scored twice in the second period as  
Dallas defeated Colorado 4-1 in a Game 7 showdown Friday night and 
brought the NHL Stanley Cup finals to Texas for the first time. The 
Stars, who moved south from Minnesota six years ago, will open the 
championship round at home Tuesday night against Eastern Conference 
champion Buffalo. 

</P>
<P>
	Bosox's Martinez Tops Braves  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Pedro Martinez struck out a career-high 16,  
pitching a three-hitter to become baseball's first 11-game winner 
and lead the Boston Red Sox over the Atlanta Braves and Tom Glavine 
5-1 Friday. Martinez (11-1) raised his major league-leading 
strikeout total to 133. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
