<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Stay Higher; Dow Up 45.91 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today after the government's  
employment report helped temper investors' concerns that the 
Federal Reserve might soon raise interest rates to slow the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bargain-hunting after the recent selloff on Wall Street also  
contributed to today's gains. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 45.91 at  
10,709.60, adding to an 85-point gain on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher, including the Nasdaq  
composite index, which has been battered in recent weeks amid a 
sharp decline in technology stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported today that the nation's  
unemployment rate dipped back down to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent 
in May. 
</P>
<P>
	While the overall unemployment rate fell, investors were  
impressed by the fact that only 11,000 jobs were created last 
month, far below the 225,000 expected by economists. Another 
indicator closely watched for inflation, average hourly earnings, 
was up 3.6 percent in May compared to a year ago, only a slight 
acceleration from the 3.2 percent increase the month before. 
</P>
<P>
	Both factors eased concerns among investors that the Fed will  
soon raise rates to slow an economy that is threatening to 
overheat. The central bank warned May 18 that it would raise rates 
if it determined that inflation was gaining momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	That warning created volatility on Wall Street in recent weeks,  
with investors fearing that a rate hike would cut into the profits 
of major U.S. companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report wasn't a doomsday scenario,'' said Bryan  
Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential Securities. ``But the 
market is still tepid and cautious about what the Fed will do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts also attributed today's gains to the cheap prices that  
have resulted from the downturn on Wall Street in recent weeks. The 
Dow is down about 4 percent since hitting a record high on May 13, 
while the Nasdaq is down more than 9 percent since reaching its 
all-time high April 26. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest gainers today included Cisco Systems, up 3 1/2 at 112  
5/16, and Yahoo!, up 4 9/16 at 139 15/16, in Nasdaq trading. On the 
New York Stock Exchange, America Online was up 1 3/16 at 106 15/16 
and Disney rose 1 5/8 to 30 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-7 margin on  
the NYSE, where volume came to 549.15 million shares, down from 
566.32 million at the same time Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 16.65 at 1,316.19, and  
the Nasdaq composite index was up 42.73 at 2,446.05. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 6.28 at 630.48, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 5.52 at 781.46. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
