<HEADLINE> AP Corrects Crash-Landings Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a story about the June 1 crash of an  
American Airlines plane in Little Rock, Ark., The Associated Press 
reported that First Officer Michael Origel had less than 200 flight 
hours. In fact, he had only that much time with American, but 
nearly 4,000 flight hours in the Navy and with an air charter 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	The same story said that because he was a chief pilot, Capt.  
Richard Buschmann did not have much recent time in the cockpit. 
While Buschmann did not fly a normal schedule because of his 
management duties, he flew more than the typical chief pilot 
because he was also a check pilot, ensuring the proficiency of 
other pilots, said American Airlines spokesman Tim Smith. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
