<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Portrayed as Clinton Clone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The head of the Republican National Committee  
said Friday that electing Al Gore president in 2000 would be 
tantamount to giving President Clinton a third term and that 
America ``can't afford it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at a weekly public forum here, RNC Chairman Jim  
Nicholson attacked Gore for strongly supporting Clinton during the 
president's impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Democratic vice president was part of an  
administration that accepted campaign contributions tied to the 
Chinese military as China stole nuclear weapons' secrets. He also 
accused Gore of being in the grip of teachers' unions on education 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Describing the GOP as the party of ``lower taxes, less  
government, more freedom, stronger defense and better schools,'' 
Nicholson challenged Gore to set out his positions on tax cuts and 
military spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact of the matter is that electing Al Gore means giving  
Bill Clinton a third term,'' Nicholson said. ``The American 
presidency can't afford it. The integrity and character of that 
office -- and of American leadership -- can't afford it, nor we, as 
taxpayers and citizens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Roger Salazar declined to respond directly to  
Nicholson's remarks but said he wasn't surprised the vice president 
was drawing Republican criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since they see the vice president as a strong candidate, they  
focus their attacks on him,'' Salazar said. ``They have nothing of 
substance to offer on their own. All they can offer are attacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said that it was fair for the Republicans to target  
Gore, the Democratic front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is the vice president,'' he said. ``He flies around the  
country in Air Force Two, campaigning, creating new programs, 
buying constituencies around the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson made only passing mention of Gore's Democratic  
opponent, Bill Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson made his challenge to Gore on taxes and defense  
spending in response to remarks made last week by House Minority 
Leader Richard Gephardt. 
</P>
<P>
	While discussing how to raise money for more education spending,  
Gephardt was quoted as saying, ``You've got to have a combination 
of taking it out of the defense budget and raising revenue. We can 
argue about how to do that, closing loopholes or even raising taxes 
to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt spokeswoman Sue Harvey said Friday that the congressman  
only meant to emphasize the importance of education, and to stress 
that it should be a priority as the federal government figures out 
what to do with budget surpluses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
