<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Gets Confirmation Hearings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Richard Holbrooke's nomination as U.S.  
ambassador to the United Nations got a boost Friday when Sen. Jesse 
Helms scheduled long-delayed confirmation hearings in the Foreign 
Relations Committee for this month. 
</P>
<P>
	But Helms, the committee chairman, said in a statement the  
veteran diplomatic troubleshooter will come before the panel 
burdened with ``much ethical baggage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Holbrooke has some explaining to do, and I and other  
senators will want to hear from him on a number of matters,'' Helms 
said in announcing four hearings starting June 17 -- two on ethical 
matters, one on U.N. reform, one on the conflict in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, a former assistant secretary of state, was architect  
of the 1995 Dayton, Ohio, peace accords that ended the war in 
Bosnia. He currently is vice president of the investment bank 
Credit Suisse First Boston and continues to serve the Clinton 
administration as a special troubleshooter on the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton first announced Holbrooke's nomination in June  
1998 but did not submit it until February because it was bogged 
down in internal administration investigations into allegations 
that Holbrooke violated lobbying and ethics laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Some investigations continued even after the nomination was  
submitted. 
</P>
<P>
	The inquiries dealt largely with Holbrooke's private-sector  
contacts with former State Department colleagues and with speaking 
fees he received. Holbrooke paid $5,000 to settle civil charges 
that he broke lobbying regulations but without an admission of 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke supporters contend the ethics investigations were  
triggered by anonymous Holbrooke detractors within the State 
Department and the committee's delay since February also has been 
deliberate. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's statement, Helms said, ``I must confess that I  
cannot recall another cabinet-level nomination sent to this 
committee with so much ethical baggage attached to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart said ``the time has  
come'' for the Senate to move forward on Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is an exceptionally gifted diplomat. It's time for a  
hearing. It's time to get him in the U.N.,'' Lockhart said. ``You 
know, this country needs his kind of ability at the U.N., and we're 
going to continue pressing to get that done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Helms said he has not decided whether to support the nomination  
but promised ``fair hearings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He promised his committee will ``thoroughly examine all of the  
ethics charges against Mr. Holbrooke, as well as his role and 
responsibility for this administration's misguided policy of 
appeasing Slobodan Milosevic,'' the Yugoslav president. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms scheduled a secret hearing on the ethics allegations for  
June 17, to be followed by an open hearing on the same subject 
later in the day. He set June 22 hearing on U.N. reform and a final 
one on June 24 on U.S. policy in the Balkans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
