<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unions End Strike at Shipbuilder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) -- The remaining unions striking against  
Ingalls Shipbuilding approved a new contract Friday, ending a 
three-week strike at Mississippi's largest private employer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pascagoula Metal Trades Council, an umbrella bargaining  
group for members of various unions, approved the contract Friday, 
but did not release its vote numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Council, which represents 6,500 workers, including pipe  
fitters, welders and other skilled trades, represented the last of 
the 11 unions to approve the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 733,  
which represents about 1,200 of Ingalls' 11,500 workers became the 
first of the striking unions to ratify the contract Thursday on a 
286-175 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The small, independent unit of the International Association of  
Machinists and Aerospace Workers Local 1133, which started the 
strike, also voted for the new contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look forward to resuming normal operations on Monday  
morning and to working with our employees over the life of this 
contract to continue enhancing Ingalls' reputation,'' said Den 
Knecht, Ingalls vice president of public and industrial relations. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike began May 16, idling thousands of workers at the  
shipyard that builds destroyers for the Navy and other large 
vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	Local 733 leaders said the new contract offers improvements to  
pay scales and insurance costs that had doomed a deal last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls, a builder of Navy destroyers, is a division of Litton  
Industries Inc., which controls a number of aerospace, defense and 
electronics businesses. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
