<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Predict NYC Storm Surges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- New York City could suffer huge storm surges as  
often as every several years if the sea rises as expected during 
the coming century, scientists said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven-foot surges, which are now predicted once every 100 years,  
would be expected every 40 years at best and every 4-5 years at 
worst, according to the scientists' preliminary results. 
</P>
<P>
	Such surges could break through barrier islands and flood  
low-lying parts of lower Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens and other 
places around the metropolitan area, according to Cynthia 
Rosenzweig, a NASA researcher who heads a team studying the 
potential impact of climate change on the New York City area. Much 
of Manhattan is within 10 feet of sea level. 
</P>
<P>
	The sea level will rise 1 to 3 feet by the year 2090 under  
different possible scenarios driven by such forces as polar melting 
caused by global warming, according to Vivien Gornitz, a Columbia 
University geologist on the study team. 
</P>
<P>
	The study team is made up of officials and scientists from  
government and the private sector. It is a regional spinoff of a 
government-sponsored study on how vulnerable the country is to 
climate change. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings were released in Boston at a metting of the  
American Geophysical Union, a scientific society. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 7 million people live in New York City, with 19.6  
million in the metropolitan area. 
</P>
<P>
	By the year 2090, the number of 90-degree days in the area is  
predicted to reach 28 to 81 a year, according to the group's early 
findings. There are just 13 such days now. But hundreds of people 
can die of heat-related conditions in a New York City summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The final report on New York is due out in a year.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 21:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Rivers To Get $8M, Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Doc Rivers has reached agreement on a  
four-year, $8 million deal to become coach of the Orlando Magic, 
according to ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	The network said the contract is guaranteed.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're still going through the coaching process,'' Joel Glass,  
the Magic's communications director, told The Associated Press when 
reached at home late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Rivers hasn't been signed and that the team expects to  
have no announcement through the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orlando Sentinel had reported in its Friday editions that  
Rivers met two days with Orlando officials and would be hired as 
coach on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers, who played 13 years in the NBA, is a basketball analyst  
working with Turner Sports, and has spent much of the past month 
working NBA playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers would be the second youngest coach in the league, behind  
New York's Jeff Van Gundy. Both are 37. 
</P>
<P>
	The Magic job opened when Chuck Daly, the coach for the last two  
seasons, retired after a 40-year career in pro and college 
coaching. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
