<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Down on Worries / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices retreated Friday  
on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors took to the sidelines to 
await new weather forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices seesawed throughout the session as market participants  
sought direction from government and private weather forecasters. 
</P>
<P>
	Some were worried that hot, dry weather in parts of the Midwest  
could damage early-planted crops and that rainy weather in other 
parts could delay final plantings for spring wheat and soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	Others say the weather does not appear to be as hot as  
originally believed and that conditions should be nearly ideal for 
continued planting and growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service after trading had ended called for  
continued above-normal temperatures in many Midwest growing regions 
over the next 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures also failed amid ideas weather over the weekend  
would be idea for early winter wheat harvesting. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 4 1/4 cents to $2.56 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn fell 2 1/2 cent to $2.20 3/4 a bushel; July oats fell 2 3/4 cents to 
$1.23 1/2 a bushel; July soybeans fell 1 cent to $4.64 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mostly higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .13 cent to 64.90 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose 1.40 cents to 76.77 cents a pound; June lean 
hogs rose .98 cent to 52 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .38 
cent to 53.45 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
