<DOCNO> APW19990604.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 10:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises in European Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar was up against most other major  
currencies in European trading Friday, as the ailing euro continued 
to slide. Gold prices were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0318, down from $1.0350 Thursday.  
Earlier Friday, the European currency hit a low of $1.0296. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Thursday: 121.84 Japanese  
yen, up from 121.47; 1.5409 Swiss francs, up from 1.5336; 1.4715 
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4784. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6063, up from $1.6038.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar was worth 122.35 yen,  
while the euro was worth $1.0355 and the British pound was worth 
$1.6067. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar was worth: 1.8996 German marks, up from 1.8830; 
6.3710 French francs, up from 6.3152; 2.1404 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.1216; and 1,880.60 Italian lire, up from 1,864.13 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $264.50 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$265.40 on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $264.45, down from $265.45.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $1.90 in Hong Kong to close at $266.45.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $4.88 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$4.96. 
  	   	
</P>
