<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U. of Chicago President Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The president of the University of Chicago,  
accused of dumbing down the curriculum with his plans to reduce the 
number of required courses, is resigning to make way for someone he 
says will be ``less a symbol of change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an open letter to students and faculty, Hugo Sonnenschein  
said ``I have come to feel that it is time for another president, 
one who is less a symbol of change ... to carry the momentum 
forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sonnenschein's resignation, announced Thursday, takes effect in  
June 2000. He will continue to teach economics at the university 
where he arrived at six years ago from Princeton. 
</P>
<P>
	His resignation follows criticism from some that he attempted to  
create a ``U. of C. Lite'' when the faculty voted last year with 
his support to reduce the number of classes in its core curriculum 
from 21 to 18. 
</P>
<P>
	New dormitories, more opportunities for study abroad and a $35  
million athletic center with a pool and fitness center were other 
changes that raised questions. 
</P>
<P>
	With the changes came newspaper stories and testimonials from  
alumni. Many stories were critical of the changes being wrought 
inside the 107-year-old institution. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials say the changes are here to stay.  
</P>
<P>
	``The university is on a course and it's not going to change  
that course,'' Humanities Dean Philip Gossett said of the 
university's changes in its curriculum. 
</P>
<P>
	Some said Sonnenschein wrongly took the brunt of criticism for  
initiating the changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is the faculty -- not the president -- voted in these  
changes,'' Gossett said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a small group within the university who were outvoted by  
their colleagues decided to take their arguments to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who opposed the changes, however, say Sonnenschein's  
supporters -- not them -- are in the minority. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Krane, the outgoing chairman of the university's  
45-member board of trustees, said in a letter to the university 
community that the board continues to support Sonnenschein's 
initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who had lobbied against Sonnenschein were jubilant over  
his resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've really succeeded and now I think we can go home,'' said  
university alumnus Robert Stone, who led efforts to stop the 
changes Sonnenschein helped put in motion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
