<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Is It Over for Term Life Bargains? / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When it comes to life insurance, now may be the  
best time to buy a term policy; that is, if some industry forecasts 
prove accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of actuaries and brokers believe this is the last year  
in which long-term price guarantees will be available at current 
low rates, thanks to regulations earmarked to go into effect after 
Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	After that time, they say, fewer term policies will be offered  
with rates locked in for 10, 20 or 30 years, and those still 
providing such guarantees will cost significantly more than they do 
now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, what we have is a price war going on among  
companies. It's the best time in history to buy; rates are low,'' 
said Byron Udell, president of AccuQuote (www.accuquote.com), a 
life insurance quote service based in Northbrook, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, rates for level-premium term policies have fallen  
dramatically in recent years due to increased competition among 
carriers and the wide availability of insurance-quote services on 
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	A $500,000 guaranteed term policy for a preferred 40-year-old  
nonsmoking man cost around $995 annually in 1994, while today it's 
around $425, according to Udell. 
</P>
<P>
	All that could change when Valuing Life Insurance Model  
Regulation, aka Regulation XXX, is adopted by the states. 
</P>
<P>
	The Triple X rule change, approved by the National Association  
of Insurance Commissioners in Kansas City, Mo., requires insurance 
companies to maintain higher reserves on term policies with premium 
guarantees longer than five years. Industry regulators had been 
concerned that insurers were not setting aside enough money to pay 
future claims, which puts them at risk for failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Triple X still has to be approved by individual states, and the  
earliest it could take effect would be Jan. 1, the date proposed by 
the NAIC. By late May, no state had officially adopted the ruling, 
although several states have conditionally approved it,according to 
the NAIC and industry experts. (New York has had its own version of 
Triple X in place for some time.) 
</P>
<P>
	Udell and some others believe the higher-reserve rule will force  
carriers to raise their rates on level-premium term policies or 
discontinue those types of policies altogether. He says he's 
certain Triple X will be in place by next year. ``All the carriers 
are preparing for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What Triple X is going to provide is a series of defective  
products ... with no guarantees,'' Udell said, adding that rates on 
such products initially may be low but will be steadily raised over 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's an example of what could happen, according to one  
insurer's formula, he said: A $500,000 policy for a 40-year-old 
nonsmoking man would cost around $420 a year and be guaranteed at 
that level for three years, then rise to as much as $2,780 after 
the third year, $4,045 in 10 years and as much as $9,240 in 20 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, many insurance agents have been urging their clients to  
buy now and lock in a cheap rate or risk such a scenario. 
</P>
<P>
	Some industry experts, though, say the salespeople are using  
Triple X merely as a marketing ploy. No one truly knows what will 
happen after Triple X, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just a scare tactic. It's a nice convenient sales  
gimmick to get people to buy insurance,'' said Joseph Belth, editor 
of The Insurance Forum, an industry newsletter published in 
Ellettsville, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know if any states are going to adopt it (Triple X)  
... (and) if it goes into effect, we don't know what effect it will 
have because we don't know for certain how companies will react to 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James Hunt, life insurance actuary for the Consumer Federation  
of America, a Washington-based consumer group, agreed that the 
reaction from some in the industry may be a bit overblown. However, 
he suggested those who might be in the market for term insurance 
buy it now anyway since rates are generally low. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to know how this will affect consumers,'' he said.  
``What we don't know is how pricing actuaries and their management 
will respond in an environment where intense competition will still 
prevail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of households opt for term life insurance because of  
its affordability -- it's about a third to a quarter the cost of 
permanent policies, called whole or universal life. Whole life 
generally offers level premiums for as long as the policy is 
maintained, and a cash value is accumulated over time. Term 
policies pay out when the insured party dies and have no cash 
value. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
