<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Writers Clash on Movie Impacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Leading screenwriters clashed Friday  
over how much responsibility they should take for the possible 
effects that movie violence has on society. 
</P>
<P>
	At a seminar titled ``Guns Don't Kill People ... Writers Do,''  
Brian Helgeland, writer and director of the ultraviolent Mel Gibson 
film ``Payback,'' said writers should answer only to themselves and 
not adhere to a code of conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't know how to respond to a code or a consensus as to  
what's responsible and what isn't acceptable. That is only for me 
to answer in my own work,'' said Helgeland, who also co-wrote 
``L.A. Confidential'' and ``Nightmare on Elm Street 4.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But William Mastrosimone, who wrote the HBO movie ``The Burning  
Season'' and the CBS miniseries ``Sinatra,'' said Helgeland's 
perspective was ``very dangerous'' and ``extremist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to look to ourselves and acknowledge the effect we  
have in the world,'' said Mastrosimone, contending that studies 
clearly show a cause-and-effect relationship between entertainment 
violence and people's real-life behavior. He did not cite any 
particular studies. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-day event is sponsored by the Writers Guild  
Foundation, an education and advocacy group made up of members of 
the Writers Guild of America, the union for TV and movie 
screenwriters. 
</P>
<P>
	The event comes as lawmakers go on the attack against movies,  
television, music and video games following the school massacre in 
Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and Congress have taken Hollywood to task,  
suggesting that the film industry has contributed to a culture of 
violence through the bloody images. 
</P>
<P>
	Callie Khouri, the Academy Award-winning writer of ``Thelma &AMP;  
Louise,'' said the issues are more complicated than simply blaming 
one segment of society. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she was surprised when audiences applauded a scene in  
her movie in which one of the female lead characters shoots a man. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hoped for a stunned reaction from audiences and realization  
that the character just sealed her fate,'' said Khouri. ``I was 
terrified and I realized that I can't control how my work is 
perceived.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Valenti, the Washington lobbyist for the top Hollywood  
studios -- and the man who has taken most of the heat from Congress 
-- assured writers that he would fight for the First Amendment. But 
he said he also will call on Hollywood filmmakers to take personal 
responsibility and cut gratuitous parts from their works. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should look at their creative work and say, `Is this the  
best that I can do?'' Valenti said. ``Is there something here that 
is gratuitous as I define it?''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
