<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Defends Best-Sellers Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Internet bookseller Amazon.com has asked a  
federal court to declare that it can continue to cite The New York 
Times' best-seller list in advertising discount prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon, the No. 1 Internet bookseller, announced May 17 that it  
would offer 50 percent discounts on books on the Times' best-seller 
list. On May 28, the Times demanded in a letter that Amazon stop 
using the list for promotions, saying Amazon was infringing on the 
newspaper's copyright and trademark, Amazon said in a news release 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times did not immediately return calls for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Amazon filed a request late Thursday in U.S. District Court here  
asking for a ruling that would allow it to continue to refer to the 
Times best-seller lists in promoting its discounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The New York Times best-seller list is widely used in the  
book-selling industry as an indicator of the most popular books 
being bought nationwide,'' a company statement said. ``Book buyers, 
therefore, can easily use the list to make price comparisons on the 
best-selling books.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon spokesman Bill Curry said the company's argument is that  
citing the Times' best-seller lists is ``fair use -- that it's data 
that is out there and it is fair use to say that something is a New 
York Times best seller in the same way you would say a movie won an 
Academy Award.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon filed its court action as a last resort after discussions  
with the Times failed to reach an agreement, Curry said. 
</P>
<P>
	After Amazon announced the discounts last month, it was quickly  
matched by the No. 2 Internet bookseller, barnesandnoble.com and 
No. 3 Borders.com. Spokesmen for both companies said they had not 
received any similar letters from the Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes and Noble has a business arrangement with the Times under  
which people who read a book review on the Times' Web site and want 
to buy the book can click a link and order the book from 
barnesandnoble.com. Barnes and Noble spokesman Ben Boyd said the 
deal provides the Times a commission on books sold that way and 
lets barnesandnoble.com use Times content, including the 
best-seller list. 
</P>
<P>
	Borders has no such arrangement with the Times, but Borders  
spokesman Rich Fahle said the company refers to the Times' 
best-seller list online ``just as we've done for years in our 
stores.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No date for a hearing of Amazon's case has been set.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MCI Faces Suit Over Merger Denials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sometimes it's best not to say anything -- not  
only when there's nothing nice to say, but also when you're simply 
not sure what to say. 
</P>
<P>
	That advice holds especially true for public companies that are  
beholden to stock market investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Confronted last week with a news leak that boosted the share  
price of a company it was trying to buy, MCI WorldCom might have 
done best to keep its corporate mouth shut. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the normally savvy long-distance phone company is  
facing a lawsuit and a possible government probe charging that it 
misled investors on May 25 in trying to avoid paying a higher price 
for Skytel Communications, a leading provider of paging services. 
</P>
<P>
	In one legal sense, it doesn't really matter whether MCI  
WorldCom is innocent of intentional wrongdoing, experts said 
Friday: The company bumbled just by responding publicly to the news 
that it had reserved the Internet domain name 
``www.skytelworldcom.com'' to use as a Web address. 
</P>
<P>
	Just like people, public companies have a right to remain  
silent. But the moment they break that silence about their business 
dealings, companies are bound by a 1988 Supreme Court ruling 
requiring truthful and continuous disclosures to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The prevailing wisdom is to say, `We don't comment on rumors  
or potential transactions,''' said Sanford Krieger, a partner at 
the New York law firm Fried Frank Harris Shriver &AMP; Jacobson. ``Once 
a company decides to interject, they have a duty to keep the market 
current in a timely fashion. It's like a conveyor belt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of SkyTel rose as much as 16 percent to $21.87 1/2 on May 25  
after Company Sleuth, an Internet news service, reported the 
registration of the Skytel-related domain name, suggesting a merger 
with MCI WorldCom could be in the works. 
</P>
<P>
	In a series of miscues, MCI WorldCom first issued a statement  
downplaying the significance of the move, then said it had 
withdrawn the registration, and then said it hadn't. Three day's 
later, MCI WorldCom announced that it was buying SkyTel for about 
$1.3 billion in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial statement was particularly vague: ``The action is  
not an indication of any official company intention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to speculators who horde Web addresses in hopes of  
selling them for profit, the statement also said, ``From time to 
time, MCI WorldCom employees, sometimes acting on their own 
initiative, register domain names they believe may be potential 
targets of domain-name squatters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of trading that day, SkyTel had closed with a 6  
percent gain at $20.12 1/2. The merger agreement ultimately announced 
on May 28 valued SkyTel at about $21.25 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	In a lawsuit announced Thursday, investors charged they made  
money-losing trades based on the May 25 statements by MCI WorldCom. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal regulators, meanwhile, are investigating whether MCI  
WorldCom meant to mislead investors, The Wall Street Journal 
reported Friday, citing a person familiar with the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission plans to ask MCI WorldCom  
to supply all documents related to the SkyTel negotiations to 
determine who knew what and when they knew it, the Journal said, 
borrowing the legendary phrase from the Watergate investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps MCI WorldCom has learned its lesson quickly, refusing  
comment Friday on both the investor suit announced Thursday and the 
Journal report. The SEC also declined comment, adding that it never 
confirms or denies the existence of an investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	But regardless of whether MCI WorldCom meant no harm, the  
company's actions did hurt investors who used the announcements to 
steer their trading decisions, said Krieger. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, since MCI WorldCom was already the biggest reseller of  
Skytel paging services before the merger talks began, the domain 
name registration needn't have been related to a merger. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's conceivable that there was no causable connection between  
the registration of that name and the acquisition talks,'' said 
Krieger. ``It's possible that somebody was talking about some kind 
of joint venture. They may have been talking about dozens of forms 
of affiliations. But that doesn't get them off the hook.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
