<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lindros Signs One-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia Flyers star Eric Lindros signed  
a one-year, $8.5 million contract, as he had promised to do in a 
handshake agreement a year ago, a newspaper reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros signed the deal in Toronto on Thursday before starting a  
long drive to Florida this weekend for the Children's Miracle 
Network Telethon, his father told The Philadelphia Inquirer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to proceed on the one-year deal and not pursue a  
long-term contract,'' said Carl Lindros, the player's father and 
agent. ``Eric made a commitment before the season and after the 
season and was very vocal about that commitment, and we're going to 
move ahead on that basis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is the same money as last season, with new incentives,  
Carl Lindros said, refusing to elaborate. In the past, the Flyers 
captain has agreed to incentives tied to team performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Flyers chairman Ed Snider said he was pleased that Lindros would  
return, but said he hadn't seen the signed deal yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``We sent him a contract last week and haven't gotten it back  
yet,'' Snider said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers had until July 1 to sign Lindros, or he would have  
become a restricted free agent, meaning the Flyers would have the 
right to match offers from any other team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros missed the final seven games of the regular season and  
the playoffs while recovering from a collapsed right lung. He still 
has ``muscular pain'' in the area where the incisions were made to 
drain fluid from his chest, but that shouldn't interfere with his 
recovery, Carl Lindros said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have a good summer, Eric is in training, and he  
really looks forward to training camp,'' Carl Lindros said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros had 40 goals and a team-leading 93 points in 71 games  
this season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
