<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Outburst Interrupts Ocalan Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IMRALI ISLAND, Turkey (AP) -- The trial of Kurdish rebel leader  
Abdullah Ocalan was interrupted today when a veteran of Turkey's 
rebel conflict removed his prosthetic leg and held it up in the 
courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	After a brief recess to restore calm, Judge Turgut Okyay  
adjourned the hearing until Tuesday and asked prosecutors to 
prepare for their closing arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where is my human right,'' shouted Naim Karapacik, who lost  
his leg after stepping on a mine during an anti-rebel offensive in 
northern Iraq in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Another veteran, Mahir Akcelik, took the leg and asked: ``Who  
will account for this leg?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The protest came after a lawyer defending Ocalan complained that  
families of rebels killed in the conflict hadn't been invited to 
the trial, while representatives and families of thousands of 
soldiers slain had been. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement caused an angry uproar among the families and  
their lawyers, and the judge ordered four of the lawyers out of the 
courtroom before calling the recess. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is widely expected to end with a death sentence for  
Ocalan, whom Turkey holds responsible for all 37,000 deaths in the 
15-year-old Kurdish conflict. Although Turkish courts continue to 
issue the death sentence, no one has been executed in the country 
since 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan, testifying behind a bulletproof glass enclosure, has  
asked throughout the trial that the court spare his life so he 
could devote himself to ending fighting between Turkey's military 
and his Kurdistan Workers' Party, or PKK. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan has also invited his rebel group to hold a ``peace  
conference'' should the government respond to his call for peace. 
The government has rejected talks with the rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey rules out any concessions to its minority Kurds in their  
drive for autonomy in the southeast, seeing it as a threat that 
would split the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of more than 2,500 victims -- including some  
Kurds -- have attended the proceedings since the trial opened on 
this prison island on Monday. Ocalan's supporters said Thursday the 
trial was turning into a show for the families, who have been 
attending court carrying pictures of their loved ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan's lawyers boycotted Thursday's hearing, complaining that  
Turkey was not doing enough to protect them from a public angered 
by their attempts to save the guerrilla leader. 
</P>
<P>
	They agreed to attend today's hearing when authorities promised  
to find them new accommodations after they were mobbed by hostile 
crowds at the hotel where they are staying. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
