<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets ended the week mixed  
Friday, with many investors staying on the sidelines ahead of the 
release of U.S. economic data that could indicate the direction of 
inflation in that country. 
</P>
<P>
	In Indonesia, shares surged ahead of Monday's parliamentary  
elections amid local speculative buying and suspected government 
support for state-owned companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the buying came from local investors who are  
expecting the election to go smoothly after a generally peaceful 
campaign that ended on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	More skeptical market observers said there were signs of the  
government bolstering the market through buying in state-owned 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index closed up 24.809  
point, or 4.2 percent, to 612.378. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 73.25  
points, or 0.45 percent, closing at 16,300.75 points. On Thursday, 
the index shed 190.49 points, or 1.16 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average gained some ground on selective buying, but  
the market as a whole was mixed at the end of the day's trading. 
The market lacked fresh market-moving news, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders still hope that the government will map out additional  
steps to buoy Japan's economy, in its worst recession since World 
War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 121.62 yen in late  
afternoon trading, up 0.08 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo but 
lower than its late New York level of 121.66 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine shares slumped on heavy foreign selling ahead of the  
release of key economic data in the United States later Friday, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index, or PSE Index,  
fell 27.81 points, or 1.2 percent, to 2,354.60. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Hong Kong closed lower after four days of gains.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of blue chips,  
fell 56.07 points, or 0.5 percent, closing at 12,415.54. On 
Thursday, the index had edged up 12.97 points, a 0.1 percent rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices opened higher in reaction to overnight  
gains on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 
85.80 points, or 0.8 percent, to close at 10,663.69. 
</P>
<P>
	But profit-taking in the afternoon pushed the Hang Seng index  
into negative territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors stayed on the sidelines ahead of the release of  
U.S. economic data. The U.S. Federal Reserve has warned that it 
will raise interest rates if it determines that inflation has crept 
into the booming U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed mixed, with the key index soaring 2.5  
percent as investors snapped up blue-chip stocks in reaction to the 
brightening outlook for the country's economic recovery. The Korea 
Composite Stock Price Index rose 19.29 points to 797.50. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed slightly higher. The benchmark  
Weighted Stock Price Index rose 17.53 points, or 0.23 percent, to 
7,590.44. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed little changed. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index slipped 0.03 point to 2,129.04. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower ahead of the  
release of key U.S. employment data. The All Ordinaries Index 
closed at 2929.3, down 12.3 points, or 0.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Share prices closed lower in moderate trading. The  
benchmark Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, fell 
4.70 points, or 0.6 percent, to 739.80. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower. The benchmark Straits  
Times Index fell 13.73 points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,928.37. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: The key index closed little changed. The Thailand SET  
Index edged up 0.42 points to 476.47. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
