<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO May End Bombing Sunday  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon said today that NATO could end  
its bombing of Yugoslavia as soon as Sunday if Serb military 
authorities cooperate with the alliance's plan for the withdrawal 
of troops from Kosovo. President Clinton said today, ``I am anxious 
to end the bombing'' against Yugoslavia, but not until NATO has 
proof that Slobodan Milosevic is complying with the alliance's 
terms. NATO kept up the bombing campaign today, striking an 
airfield near Belgrade and tanks in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO, Yugoslav Generals Speak  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO generals today initiated talks  
by telephone with their Yugoslav counterparts, a day after Slobodan 
Milosevic's government accepted an international peace plan. 
Generals from the two sides will meet face-to-face tomorrow on the 
border between Macedonia and Kosovo to discuss the technicalities 
for a withdrawal, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said. The West promised 
no letup in the allied bombings until there is a verifiable 
withdrawal of 40,000 Serb force members from Kosovo and more than 
855,000 ethnic Albanian refugees are then allowed to return home. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Arrested for Tiananmen Protests  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Mourners and protesters today commemorated those  
killed 10 years ago in China's crackdown on the Tiananmen Square 
pro-democracy demonstrations. Police, on alert to prevent public 
mourning, arrested at least two people. Most people, however, went 
about their normal activities. Hundreds turned out, as always, to 
watch soldiers lower the red national flag on the square at the end 
of the day. Dozens of uniformed and plainclothes officers kept 
watch. Police briefly detained at least five foreign journalists 
and confiscated their film. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Closer to Senate Run  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON -- ``I'm going to open an exploratory committee in  
July,'' Hillary Rodham Clinton announced today. Forming the 
committee will allow Mrs. Clinton to begin raising money to travel 
to New York, conduct polls and hire staff -- all forming the nucleus 
of a Senate campaign. In political circles, formation of such a 
committee is tantamount to a declaration of candidacy, making Mrs. 
Clinton the nation's first first lady to seek public office. 

</P>
<P>
	Unemployment Falls to 4.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate dipped back  
down to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent in May even though the growth 
of payroll jobs was the smallest in more than three years. 
Unemployment among blacks fell to the lowest level on record while 
the jobless rates of teen-agers and adult women hit 30-year lows, 
the Labor Department said. Even with the drop in unemployment, the 
total number of payroll jobs rose by just 11,000 in May, a sharp 
slowdown from the 343,000 jobs created in April. 

</P>
<P>
	ANC May Achieve Two-Thirds Majority  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- The African National Congress  
is on the verge of a two-thirds majority in Parliament, according 
to nearly complete election returns today. That margin that would 
give the party sweeping powers. The country's largest black 
newspaper, The Sowetan, joined opposition politicians in urging the 
ANC to be judicious with its overwhelming mandate. Final results 
from Wednesday's election are not expected until Sunday. 

</P>
<P>
	Springer Appears at Chicago Hearing  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- TV talk show host Jerry Springer appeared today  
before a Chicago City Council hearing, telling aldermen he knew 
little about the business arrangements behind his show and 
declining to disclose his salary. Alderman Edward Burke, a former 
policeman said that if the fist fights on the show are genuine, 
Chicago police should haul the guests off to jail. The nationally 
syndicated show is taped in Chicago. Security on the show is 
provided by off-duty Chicago police officers. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 102.90, Nasdaq Up 60.72  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the close, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 102.90 points at 10,766.59. Advancers on the New 
York Stock Exchange outnumbered decliners 1,646-1,244. The Nasdaq 
Composite Index was up 60.72 at 2,464.04. 

</P>
<P>
	Agassi's Match Postponed in Paris  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Andre Agassi's semifinal against Dominik Hrbaty was  
postponed until tomorrow because of rain with Agassi leading 6-4, 
7-6 (8-6), 3-6, 1-2. If he gets by the Slovakian, Andrei Medvedev 
will be waiting for him in the title match. Medvedev beat Fernando 
Meligeni today 7-5, 3-6, 6-4, 7-6 (8-6) to reach his first Grand 
Slam final. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
