<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Seeking To Use Book List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Amazon.com wants the same privilege its major  
online competitor barnesandnoble.com has in using the New York 
Times' best-seller list to advertise book discounts, and has gone 
to court to obtain it. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 28, the Times demanded in a letter that Amazon.com stop  
using the list for promotions, saying the online retailer was 
infringing on the newspaper's copyright and trademark, Amazon.com 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com is asking U.S. District Court here for an order that  
would allow it to continue to use the list. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 3 online bookseller, Borders.com, also has received a  
similar letter from the Times but has not decided what to do, a 
spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times released a statement Friday saying it has no objection  
to identifying given books as ``New York Times Bestsellers'' or to 
the discounting of books on the list. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Times said Amazon.com's ``re-publication of The New York  
Times Best Sellers List on its Web site without our permission 
constitutes an unlawful use of our property.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said the Internet book-seller has made some revisions  
to its practices, ``but that is inadequate. Unless Amazon.com 
obtains a license from The Times, they must among other things, 
stop devoting a separate area on its site to the list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com announced May 17 it would offer 50 percent discounts  
on books on the New York Times list. Its offer was quickly matched 
by the No. 2 Internet bookseller, barnesandnoble.com of New York, 
and No. 3 Borders.com of Ann Arbor, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com spokesman Bill Curry said the company's position is  
that using the Times' best-seller list is ``fair use -- that it's 
data that is out there and it is fair use to say that something is 
a New York Times best seller in the same way you would say a movie 
won an academy award.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesmen for barnesandnoble.com said the company has not  
received a similar request from the Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Boyd, a barnesandnoble.com spokesman, said Friday the Times  
is an affiliate of barnesandnoble.com and sells books through its 
Internet site. 
</P>
<P>
	``They earn a commission on all books sold through  
barnesandnoble.com as part of the affiliate relationship,'' Boyd 
said. He said the agreement with the Times allows 
barnesandnoble.com ``to use New York Times' content according to 
their stipulations,'' including the Times' best-seller list. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Fahle, a spokesman for Borders.com, said the company's  
stores have made reference to the best-seller list without 
controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that Borders.com has no business arrangement with the  
Times similar to the affiliation with barnesandnoble.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon claims to be the Internet's largest retailer of videos,  
music and books. It also has bought or is developing interests in a 
variety of online companies offering products and services such as 
pharmaceuticals, beauty aids, greeting cards, pets, groceries and 
auctions. 
</P>
<P>
	No date has been set for a hearing, Curry said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
