<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Like so many drivers on the Winston Cup  
circuit, two-time Daytona 500 champion Sterling Marlin is looking 
to win at Dover Downs International Speedway for the first time in 
his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though he's 0-for-26 on the track known at The Monster  
Mile, Marlin figures there are small victories within repeated 
defeats. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them is to reclaim his body, something the affable  
Tennessean hopes to do again Sunday after the MBNA Platinum 400. 
</P>
<P>
	``The G-forces pull everything to the left, including everything  
in your body,'' said Marlin, who failed to qualify Friday and must 
get in the race in the second round on Saturday. ``If you really 
wanted to have some fun, you'd forget the cars at the end of the 
race and do a leftside-rightside weight on the drivers instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody who drives in the race limps for two days until the  
blood gets back to your right leg.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dover Downs, where narrow straightaways give way to 24 degrees  
of banking in very tight turns, shares with Darlington Raceway and 
Bristol Motor Speedway the distinction of being the most demanding 
tracks on the circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Its a tough place to race,'' Marlin said. ``Shoot, one lap  
around the place can be tough. ``But to do it 400 times ...'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *COOLED OFF:* Over a three-year period, Rusty Wallace and then  
Jeff Gordon were unbeatable at Dover Downs International Speedway. 
But times have changed. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace won the fall race in 1993, then took both Dover events a  
year later. Gordon then became the dominant Dover driver, winning 
in the fall of 1995 and twice the following year. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither has won since at the Monster Mile.  
</P>
<P>
	Gordon starts 14th Sunday in the MBNA Platinum 400. Wallace will  
go from the eighth position on the 43-car grid. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *COMPETITION TIGHTER:* Very little guesswork went into  
predictions prior to races last season. Just take your choice -- 
Jeff Gordon or Mark Martin -- and you had a shot at picking the 
winner. Between them, they prevailed in 20 of 33 races. Gordon won 
a record-tying 13. 
</P>
<P>
	But 1999 is a new dawn of competition on the Winston Cup  
circuit. There have been seven winners -- Terry Labonte, Rusty 
Wallace, John Andretti, Dale Earnhardt, Gordon, Dale Jarrett and 
Jeff Burton -- in the last seven races. 
</P>
<P>
	With Martin winless since the second race of the season and MBNA  
Platinum 400 polesitter Bobby Labonte not yet on the board, and 
both always major players at Dover, the run has a good chance to 
continue. The record for most different winners in succession in a 
season is nine, last achieved in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PIT STOPS:* Ricky Rudd, seeking to set extend his modern NASCAR  
record of winning at least once in 17 consecutive seasons, and Bill 
Elliott top the active drivers with four victories each at Dover. 
... Both Richard Petty and Bobby Allison won seven times at the 
Monster Mile. ... Darrell Waltrip, twice a victor at Dover, hasn't 
visited the winner's circle anywhere in 207 races. ... Kyle Petty 
got the most recent of his eight career victories in this race in 
1995. But last year is one he'd like to forget at Dover. He crashed 
in the spring race and wound up 42nd. In September, an engine went, 
relegating him to 41st. Race winners Dale Jarrett and Mark Martin, 
as well as Jeff Gordon, Bobby Labonte and Jeremy Mayfield finished 
in the top seven in both Dover races last year. ... Pontiac has but 
three victories in 58 races since The Monster Mile became a NASCAR 
stop in 1969. ... Corrie Stott, former crew chief for Sterling 
Marlin, has become team manager for Derrike Cope. ... Casey Atwood 
was moved from 19th to last in the 43-car MBNA 200 field after 
NASCAR said it discovered his team was using fuel that didn't meet 
specs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
