<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, Yugoslav Generals Begin Talking  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Keeping up the pressure, NATO war  
planes struck targets across Serbia today even as alliance generals 
began talks with their Yugoslav counterparts about withdrawing from 
Kosovo. French President Jacques Chirac said today that NATO will 
now refocus its air campaign ``to strictly military objectives.'' 
Russia and the West continue to disagree on the makeup of a 
peacekeeping force for Kosovo, but the differences can likely be 
worked out without imperiling the plan, U.S. Deputy Secretary of 
State Strobe Talbott said today. NATO plans to put 50,000 armed 
troops into Kosovo to keep the peace, including about 7,000 U.S. 
forces. 

</P>
<P>
	Relatives View Ark. Jet Crash Site  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Federal investigators visited a  
hospital today to interview survivors of American Airlines Flight 
1420 while the victims' relatives went to the end of an airport 
runway to see the crumpled plane. The relatives were kept about 100 
yards from the MD-82, which crashed on landing late Tuesday night 
at Little Rock National Airport. Nine people were killed and 83 
were injured. After the initial phase of the investigation focused 
on bad weather at the time of the crash, the NTSB said it learned 
that wind-resisting wing panels used to slow down landing jetliners 
were not opened as Flight 1420 hurtled down a runway and crashed. 

</P>
<P>
	China Arrests 2 Tiananmen Protesters  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- With small acts of defiance, mourners and  
protesters on Friday commemorated those killed 10 years ago in 
China's crackdown on the Tiananmen Square pro-democracy 
demonstrations. Police, on alert to prevent public mourning, 
arrested at least two people. One was whisked away by police after 
he raised a slogan-daubed white umbrella and walked beneath a 
portrait of Mao Tse-tung. White is the color of mourning for 
Chinese. Later, eight police officers tackled a young man in a 
white T-shirt reading ``Down with corruption'' as he threw leaflets 
on the plaza. Tiananmen Square was closed, encircled by a high 
metal wall while workers laid new paving stones. 

</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Bank, Bankers Trust Unite  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The merger between Germany's Deutsche  
Bank and U.S.-based Bankers Trust has been completed, creating the 
world's largest commercial financial institution, officials said 
today. Together, Germany's biggest bank and the eighth largest in 
the United States have assets of about $820 billion, as of March 
31, and a workforce of some 95,000. The final step in the merger 
was taken this week when authorities in Canada and New Jersey 
approved the deal. The acquisition of Bankers Trust constitutes the 
biggest takeover of a U.S. financial institution by a foreign bank. 

</P>
<P>
	Violence Mars Indonesia Campaigning  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Violence marred the final day of  
campaigning for Indonesia's historic election when rock-throwing 
mobs attacked supporters today of the ruling Golkar Party. One day 
after front-running opposition leader Megawati Sukarnoputri filled 
the streets of Jakarta with more than 1 million supporters, only 
about 10,000 Golkar loyalists showed up in the center of the city 
today. 

</P>
<P>
	Summer Camps Increase Security  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After a school year of shootings and copycat  
threats, summer camps are bracing for the arrival of millions of 
children -- and tightening security to make sure tragedy doesn't 
follow them. Some overnight camps are asking parents to pack their 
children's bags to keep out weapons, and camp directors say they 
will be more vigilant in searching campers and sending kids home. 
Still, directors say overnight camps have a number of safety 
advantages over schools. Counselors live round the clock with 
campers and access to weapons is limited since children are not 
allowed to leave. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 25, Nasdaq Up 39  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 25.97 points at 10,689.66. Advancers on the New York 
Stock Exchange outnumbered decliners 1,518-1,304. The Nasdaq 
Composite Index was up 39.22 to 2,442.54. 

</P>
<P>
	Medvedev Reaches French Open Final  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Andrei Medvedev surged into the French Open final  
today, beating Fernando Meligeni 7-5, 3-6, 6-4, 7-6 (8-6), but 
Andre Agassi will have to wait after his semifinal against Dominik 
Hrbaty was postponed because of rain. It will be completed 
tomorrow. Agassi leads 6-4, 7-6 (8-6), 3-6, 1-2. Ranked No. 100, 
Medvedev becomes the lowest-ranked player in the Open era to play 
for the French Open championship. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
