<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Partners Make Cocaine Seizure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. officials said Friday they and  
international authorities had seized more than 11 tons of cocaine 
in six incidents in the Caribbean during the past three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	They estimated that the seizures prevented 103 million  
street-level doses from reaching the United States, the Caribbean 
Islands, Europe and Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	In the two largest and most recent cases, the HMS Marlborough,  
carrying U.S. Coast Guard law enforcement detachments, boarded the 
China Breeze and the Castor. 
</P>
<P>
	The China Breeze, a Panamanian-registered merchant ship, was  
boarded May 27 south of Puerto Rico. Hidden amid the cargo and 
behind concealed panels were 8,800 pounds of cocaine, the 11th 
largest seizure in maritime history, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Castor, also a Panamanian-registered ship, was boarded May  
31 north of Venezuela. It had 8,687 pounds of cocaine aboard, the 
12th largest seizure on record. 
</P>
<P>
	The ships were being escorted to Galveston, Texas, and Miami for  
continued investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, British Defense Secretary George Robertson said:  
``One drug bust of four tons of cocaine is good. Two in one week is 
even better. And we will not give up here. We will continue to 
catch the people who deal in drugs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The interdiction efforts were carried out by Britain's Royal  
Navy, as well as the U.S. Coast Guard, Navy, Drug Enforcement 
Administration, FBI and Customs Service and Puerto Rico's Forces 
United for Rapid Action. 
</P>
<P>
	The organizations were operating as part of the maritime  
component of the president's National Drug Control Strategy, 
supervised by Barry McCaffrey, head of the Office of National Drug 
Control Policy. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, the United Kingdom, the Netherlands and  
France routinely engage in counternarcotics sweeps through the 
Caribbean. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
