<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA To Enforce Crew Rest Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The American Airlines pilots union said Friday  
it had been told by the head of the Federal Aviation Administration 
that the agency will begin strictly enforcing crew rest regulations 
by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The report came three days after an American Airlines jet  
crashed on landing in Little Rock, Ark., at the end of a long day 
for the two-person flight crew, although the FAA said the decision 
was not related to the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Under federal law, airline pilots cannot fly more than eight  
hours in a 24-hour period. They also must be able to rest for eight 
hours in that same span. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of the crew that crashed, the pilots had been on  
duty 13 1/2 hours, near American's 14-hour duty limit and within three 
hours of when they would have had to start their FAA-mandated rest 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots claim airlines routinely violate the tenor of the rest  
rules, especially with backup crews. They can be on standby status 
for days without being told when they should rest. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a reserve pilot might awaken at 7 a.m. and not be  
told until 8 p.m. of a flight assignment beginning at 10 p.m. The 
pilot might then be expected to complete his allotted eight hours 
of flying time over a 10-hour period. 
</P>
<P>
	In such a case, the pilot would be awake for 27 consecutive  
hours. Within 24 hours, he should have received eight hours of 
rest. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lack of compliance has become an industrywide problem and  
a major cause of pilot fatigue that is seriously compromising 
aviation safety,'' said Capt. Richard Rubin, a spokesman for the 
Allied Pilots Association, which represents American's 9,600 
pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration announced in 1995 that it  
intended to resolve the dispute over crew rest. It proposed a rule 
allowing up to 10 hours of flight time, but within a 14-hour duty 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	During ``duty'' time, crews may not be flying, but they may be  
at the airport, checking in for a flight or on a layover. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA proposal would have done three things: given airlines  
two more hours of flight time, given pilots unions a defined duty 
period and given passengers the benefit of having crews who receive 
a 10-hour off-duty period -- two hours more than the current rest 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Various factions balked at the proposal, and in February a  
rule-making body told the FAA there was no consensus within the 
aviation community on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, FAA Administrator Jane Garvey met with  
representatives of the Allied Pilots Association. They came away 
saying she told them the agency would publicize its intent to 
enforce the existing rules next week and begin doing so at the end 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	FAA spokesmen would say only that Garvey had met with the union.  
They referred reporters to a statement on the agency's Web site, 
which stated that the FAA ``will soon place a notice in the Federal 
Register stating its intent to enforce the current regulations 
until a new proposed rule is developed and made part of the Federal 
Aviation Regulations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether the statement was affected by the crash, FAA  
spokesman Eliot Brenner said: ``The meeting had been scheduled for 
at least two weeks.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
