<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Civil War Descendant Sues Appraiser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The great-great-grandson of a general who  
ordered a bloody failed Civil War charge that forced the 
Confederacy from Gettsyburg told a jury Friday a respected antiques 
dealer swindled him out of the general's valuable keepsakes. 
</P>
<P>
	George Pickett V said he was fooled into selling a trunk full of  
items to Russ Pritchard, a frequent guest on PBS' ``The Antiques 
Road Show,'' for one-tenth their value. 
</P>
<P>
	Pritchard paid Pickett $87,500 for the keepsakes, which included  
Confederate Gen. George Pickett's map of Gettysburg, parts of his 
uniform, a lock of his hair and several hundred original Civil War 
documents and letters. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks later, Pritchard sold the items for $870,000 to the  
city of Harrisburg for its planned National Civil War Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was swindled. We'd rather have our things back,'' Pickett  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Pickett's charge across a mile of open field ended with  
half of his 15,000 troops killed, captured, or injured, ending the 
Battle of Gettysburg and driving Confederate troops out of the 
North for the rest of the war. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickett contends Pritchard duped him by posing as a Harrisburg  
representative and purposely underappraising the items so he could 
make a significant profit. 
</P>
<P>
	Pritchard, of American Ordnance Preservation Association in Bryn  
Mawr, denies the allegations. Both he and the city are defendants 
in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Pritchard said Pickett himself set the price, and also received  
a computer, a copier, and a surfing trip to Costa Rica in the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Kapelsohn and the city's attorney, Jeffrey McCarron, said  
Pickett should have been more responsible in finding out what the 
antiques were worth. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Jo Roycroft Pickett, Pickett's wife, acknowledged that  
they should have gotten more information, she said she was swayed 
by a letter from the mayor of Harrisburg that stated Pritchard was 
an official representative of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``I trusted Russ Pritchard,'' she said. ``We thought we had an  
expert from the city.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
