<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charlie Sanders Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Former Detroit Lions tight end and coach  
Charlie Sanders was released on bond after being charged with 
domestic violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Oakland County sheriff's deputies arrested Sanders, 52,  
about 11:45 p.m. Wednesday at his home after his wife Georgianna 
called 911, Lt. Robert Smith said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, who is 6-foot-4 and 220 pounds, punched his wife in the  
forehead, then bit her lip, police and prosecutors told The Oakland 
Press of Pontiac. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders was cooperative with the arresting officers, Smith said.  
</P>
<P>
	District Court Magistrate Marie Soma arraigned Sanders on the  
misdemeanor charge, punishable by up to 93 days in jail, and 
scheduled a June 10 pretrial hearing. A condition of Sanders' 
$1,000 personal bond was that he have no contact with his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders' attorney Steven Cabadas called the matter a family  
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't any domestic violence,'' Cabadas said. ``It's a  
matter the family wants to resolve by themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders played for the Lions from 1968-1977 and remains third on  
the club's all-time list with 336 receptions. He was on the 
coaching staff for eight years and rejoined the Lions as a scout in 
1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
