<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Close Higher; Dow Up 136.15 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices rose smartly on Wall Street today as  
traders were pleasantly surprised by the government's report that 
inflation and the economy weren't running rampant after all. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's employment report helped temper investors'  
concerns that the Federal Reserve might soon raise interest rates 
to slow the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bargain-hunting that followed the recent selloff on Wall Street  
also contributed to today's gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average was up 136.15 to close at  
10,799.84, adding to an 85-point gain on Thursday. For the week, 
the Dow was up 240.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher, including the Nasdaq  
composite index, which has been battered in recent weeks amid a 
sharp decline in technology stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 28.17 to 1,327.71, and the Nasdaq  
composite index was up 60.72 to 2,464.04. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,838 up, 1,118 down and 602 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 689.91 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
716.15 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 10.32 to 634.52, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 5.04 to 780.98 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.35 to 442.33.  
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported today that the nation's  
unemployment rate dipped back down to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent 
in May. But investors were particularly impressed by the fact that 
only 11,000 jobs were created last month, far below the 225,000 
expected by economists, a sign that the economy is growing 
moderately. 
</P>
<P>
	Another indicator closely watched for signs of inflation,  
average hourly earnings, was up 3.6 percent in May compared to a 
year ago, only a slight acceleration from a 3.2 percent increase 
the month before. 
</P>
<P>
	Both factors eased concerns among investors that the Fed will  
soon raise rates to slow an economy that is threatening to 
overheat. The central bank warned May 18 that it would raise rates 
if it determined that inflation was gaining momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors may feel like the worst news on that front has  
already occurred,'' said Bob Dickey, managing director of technical 
analysis at Dain Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed's warning has created volatility on Wall Street in  
recent weeks, with investors fearing a rate hike would cut into the 
profits of major U.S. companies. But analysts suggested that the 
weeks between the Fed's initial hint and the June 29 meeting of its 
Open Market Committee are giving investors time to get used to the 
idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts also attributed today's gains to the cheap prices that  
have resulted from the downturn on Wall Street in recent weeks. The 
Dow is down about 4 percent since hitting a record high on May 13, 
while the Nasdaq is down more than 9 percent since reaching its 
all-time high April 26. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq posted its strongest gain since April 21, led by  
Cisco Systems and Yahoo! On the New York Stock Exchange, America 
Online and Disney were among the biggest gainers. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of these stocks have been hit really hard and there's  
some renewed interest in buying,'' Dickey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, analysts suggested that today's gains may be difficult to  
sustain as long as questions about interest rates hang over the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is still tepid and cautious about what the Fed will  
do,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential 
Securities. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
