<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Clang' Is Sound Blazers Make </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- For the first time this season, boos  
rained down on the Portland Trail Blazers instead of the red and 
black confetti that has followed so many victories at the Rose 
Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers were so awful in an 85-63 Game 3 loss to the San  
Antonio Spurs on Friday night that they didn't even bother to argue 
with the catcalls. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess if I was a fan and I paid my good money, and I watched  
basketball like that, I would have booed too,'' said Blazers point 
guard Damon Stoudamire, who scored two points on 1-of-12 shooting. 
``I didn't play worth a damn tonight, and they have every right to 
boo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers led 26-22 after the first quarter, and for the first  
half looked in good shape to win the game and pull within 2-1 for 
the series. But an eight-point third quarter turned a mediocre 
night into a historically bad one. 
</P>
<P>
	Portland made an NBA playoff record-low 19 baskets and shot only  
25 percent. The 63 points were second-worst in league postseason 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's a matter of quitting,'' backup point guard  
Greg Anthony said. ``I think maybe the spirit was killed at times. 
A lot of that has to go to the San Antonio Spurs. But it's just 
unfortunate that this game was played the way it was from our 
perspective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stoudamire heard a few boos before the game even started, from  
fans angry over his complaints this week over what he sees as a 
lack of playing time in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, Stoudamire said he would never forget the  
times he's sat out crucial minutes in favor of Anthony. He also 
said at times he's regretted his decision to sign a seven-year, $81 
million contract extension to stay in his hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Considering) the timing of what I said this week, I'd  
probably take it back,'' Stoudamire said Friday night. ``That 
looked as if it was one of the reasons why the team was not as 
focused tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite shooting under 30 percent in the first half, Portland  
trailed just 40-38 to start the third quarter. But just when the 
Blazers needed a surge, they got a slump instead. 
</P>
<P>
	A hook shot by Sabonis pulled the Blazers within 48-46 with 6:56  
to go in the quarter. From there, Portland missed its last nine 
shots of the quarter, and the Spurs went on a 16-0 run for a 64-46 
lead entering the fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers had shown a tendency to flatline on offense. In Game  
1 of the conference semifinals against Utah, Portland scored just 
five points in the fourth quarter of an 83-73 loss, the fewest 
points ever in a postseason quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The only thing the Blazers had working was Rasheed Wallace, but  
his productivity was limited by foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace appeared to be off to a charmed night on the first  
possession. With the shot clock running down, Wallace tracked down 
a loose ball and, in the same motion, swished a 23-footer at the 
horn. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace scored 14 points of his 22 points in the first half on  
5-of-7 shooting, but he played only 14 minutes because he picked up 
his second foul with 6:35 left in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	When Wallace wasn't shooting his high jumpers or dunking, the  
Blazers were inept. The rest of the team shot just 6-of-30 in the 
first half. 
</P>
<P>
	Power forward Brian Grant was held to five points on 0-for-5  
shooting, and guard Isaiah Rider had 10 points, missing eight of 11 
attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace's fourth foul came on the offensive end with 9:53 left  
in the third. At the time, Portland trailed only 44-42. When he 
came back, with 3:02 left, the Blazers were down 56-46. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, Sheed is the only one playing well,'' Rider said.  
``The rest of us are not matching his intensity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony didn't mince words about the Blazers' chances.  
</P>
<P>
	``Let's not kid ourselves,'' he said. ``We have a lot of wounds  
that we have to lick, and a lot of pride that we have to rebuild.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 06:50:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Stays Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Ailing Philippine Airlines avoided  
possible closure Friday by meeting a deadline imposed by creditors 
for obtaining a capital infusion of $200 million, government 
regulators said. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority owner Lucio Tan deposited the money in an airline bank  
account, the Securities and Exchange Commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines' creditors had insisted that the new equity be  
raised by Friday as a condition for approval of the company's 
rehabilitation plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have fulfilled the final condition,'' PAL president Avelino  
Zapanta said. ``We have raised $200 million.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The airline has been unable to repay its debt of more than $2.2  
billion because of crippling labor disputes and an ill-timed fleet 
purchase program, launched shortly before Asia's financial crisis 
hit. 
</P>
<P>
	With the new investment, Tan's stake in the Philippine flag  
carrier dropped to 53.6 percent from 70 percent and the 
government's fell to 4.26 percent from 15 percent, the SEC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Half of the new money came from Tan, one of the Philippines'  
richest businessmen. A Hong Kong investment company with close 
links to Tan, Top Wealth Enterprises Ltd., provided $70 million. 
Two Philippine companies -- Maxell Holdings Corp. and Richmark 
Holdings Corp. -- provided the balance, the SEC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maxwell and Richmark are owned by close business associates of  
Tan, according to Jaime Bautista, Tan's financial adviser and a 
former senior PAL executive. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL's rehabilitation plan calls for deep cuts in the airline's  
work force and fleet. Without the new capital, PAL could have been 
forced to liquidate its assets to settle its debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan's relations with PAL's unions have been rocky. Top Wealth  
Enterprises agreed to invest only if PAL workers promised not to 
strike for 10 years, Tan said. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL said Thursday that more than 60 percent of its 8,000 workers  
have accepted the no-strike demand in exchange for stock. Some 
union leaders, however, oppose the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 union members picketed briefly Friday at the SEC  
against layoffs and the strike ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Zapanta said the size of job cuts will largely depend on the  
divestment of non-core holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be no ``widespread retrenchments,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	From a payroll of 15,000 at the time of the pilots' strike, the  
carrier's workforce has fallen to just over 8,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Zapanta said talks with Deutsche Lufthansa AG on the German  
airline taking a consulting role in helping manage PAL are 
continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's still very much up in the air,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	PAL is Asia's oldest airline. On March 15, 1941, it carried five  
passengers from Manila to Baguio in the northern Philippines on its 
maiden flight. It became the first Asian airline to cross the 
Pacific on July 31, 1946. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
