<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 02:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alabama Tax Assessor Sued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- A county tax assessor is being sued by  
residents who say he refused to give them property tax reductions 
solely on the grounds that they couldn't speak English well enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Julio and Carmen Telleria, a Dominican Republic-born husband and  
wife, and Byong-Rye Ahn, a native of South Korea, sued Madison 
County Tax Assessor Wayland Cooley, claiming he refused to give 
them tax breaks because they could not conduct the transaction in 
English. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit contends Cooley is rude and prejudiced toward  
foreigners, and it quotes him as saying they should not have the 
same rights as ``us here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trial of the case was set for next week, but it was delayed so  
the judge could consider a request to dismiss the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooley, 83, has said the property law manual doesn't say  
anything about requiring him to have an interpreter on hand. He 
denies being rude, but thinks immigrants should learn to speak 
English. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I can't understand is why people don't learn the language  
of the country in which they live,'' he has said. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit contends that the Tellerias are paying about $450 too  
much each year in taxes, and Mrs. Ahn is paying about $400 too much 
because of Cooley's refusal to grant reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama law requires applicants to take an oath swearing to the  
accuracy of information about their property. The plaintiffs 
contend Cooley won't vouch for the accuracy of the oath if it isn't 
taken in English, even if an interpreter is present. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers, lawyers for Cooley said that his English-only  
policy was designed ``to prevent potential fraud.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
