<DOCNO> APW19990604.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the euro Friday in an  
unusual turn as traders helped the new European currency rebound 
from yet another record low. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose against the yen as fresh U.S. government data  
underscored the strength of the country's economy. Unemployment 
figures returned to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent in May although 
payroll jobs increased but a fraction of what was expected. In late 
New York trading, the dollar rose to 122.22 yen from 121.66 yen 
late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in late New York trading Friday, the euro rose to $1.0362  
from $1.0343 Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, during Asian trading, the euro fell to its lowest point  
yet, $1.0270, as overseas funds sold the currency aggressively with 
the thought that European economic fundamentals would remain 
distressed. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, data released later Friday showed that industrial  
production fell as did business confidence in the economies of the 
11 countries the euro represents. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, European Union leaders created confusion as they  
ended a meeting in Cologne, Germany Friday with a communique that 
dropped specific draft language supporting the euro. The euro 
continued hovering above its lows. 
</P>
<P>
	But later traders engaged in short covering, where they bought  
back euros they had dumped earlier in a bet the euro would fall 
further. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just started coming up,'' said Grant Wilson, a foreign  
exchange vice president at Mellon Bank in Pittsburgh, as he 
explained that traders were afraid to go home for the weekend 
without having euros in their portfolios. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a curious reaction after what we saw this morning,''  
Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other late New York trading, the dollar fell to 1.5310 Swiss  
francs from 1.5402 and to 1.4702 Canadian dollars from 1.4759. The 
British pound rose to $1.6103 from $1.6064. 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro no longer are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8875 German marks, down from 1.8911; 6.3291 French francs, down 
from 6.3412; and 1,869.16 Italian lire, down from 1,876.17. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
