<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 12:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hispanics Upset With Astros Owner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Two television executives say they were told by  
Houston Astros owner Drayton McLane that the team doesn't market to 
Hispanics because they don't understand baseball, buy cheap seats 
and don't eat stadium food. 
</P>
<P>
	McLane denied making derogatory remarks about Hispanics before a  
dinner Thursday night honoring him with the Houston Advertising 
Federation's Trailblazer Award for community service. He described 
himself as ``angry and outraged'' about the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Marco Camacho, vice president and general manager of KTMD-TV,  
and Rod Rodriguez, the station's sales manager, said they were 
offended by McLane's comments. 
</P>
<P>
	``We asked him why he doesn't market toward Hispanics,'' Camacho  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said it was hard to reach Hispanics because the game of  
baseball is strategy and skill and it's complicated and that's why 
more Hispanics don't go to Astros games. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said if you gave them a basketball and told them to put the  
ball through the hoop, they can do that. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said that baseball is a game of statistics and numbers and  
people like to follow baseball in the newspapers and Hispanics 
don't read newspapers and when Hispanics do go, they buy the cheap 
$2 seats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLane said he talked to six to eight people at a reception  
before the dinner but denied saying anything racially insensitive 
toward Hispanics, who represent 22 percent of the eight-county 
Houston area. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot of Hispanics who do come and are great  
supporters but not in the percentage that the population represents 
in Harris County,'' McLane said. ``There was never a disparaging 
remark pertaining to the cheap seats. That was never said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The food was never discussed. That just wasn't a part of the  
conversation that we had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez, one of those who nominated McLane for the award, said  
he heard the same comments as Camacho. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said Hispanics don't understand the game of baseball, that  
it's a difficult game to follow with a lot of stats,'' Rodriguez 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said Hispanics don't read the newspapers. I looked at my  
general manager (Camacho) to see if he's really saying that. I told 
him I read newspapers. We grew up on baseball. It was our 
livelihood. Hispanics love the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLane said statistics were discussed.  
</P>
<P>
	``The statistics came up and I did comment that baseball is a  
very complex game,'' he said. ``But as far as comments that they 
didn't understand the stats or didn't read the stats is certainly 
something that was never discussed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros owner pointed out his team hires Hispanics and that  
the Astros broadcast their games in Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am angry and outraged by the accusation that KTMD Channel 48  
Telemundo made last night,'' McLane said. ``The report was 
absolutely not true. I did not do an interview with the television 
station nor did I make any such statements to anyone in the room. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me say it again: I did not make the remarks and I would  
not make the remarks reported by that television station. I will 
seek an apology from Telemundo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	KTMD is an affiliate of Telemundo. Camacho said McLane declined  
an on-camera interview because he doesn't speak Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a slap in the face for me,'' Rodriguez said. ``I had a  
lot of respect for the man, but not after last night to learn that 
his is so narrow-minded. It's sad, especially as much as I enjoy 
the game. I won't lose faith in the club but I feel sorry for all 
the Hispanic players on the team.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:31:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Security Tight in Tiananmen Square </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- With small acts of defiance, mourners and  
protesters on Friday commemorated those killed 10 years ago in 
China's crackdown on the Tiananmen Square pro-democracy 
demonstrations. Police, on alert to prevent public mourning, 
arrested at least two people. 
</P>
<P>
	One, a middle-aged man, was whisked away by police after he  
raised a slogan-daubed white umbrella and walked beneath a portrait 
of communist revolutionary Mao Tse-tung that hangs on Tiananmen 
Gate. White is the color of mourning for Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	``Remember the 10th anniversary of the student movement,'' read  
one slogan. Above it were the Chinese characters for ``Democracy 
Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An officer grabbed the umbrella and, with the help of a  
plainclothes officer, took the protester away. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, eight police officers tackled a young man in a white  
T-shirt reading ``Down with corruption'' as he ran onto the Avenue 
of Eternal Peace after throwing leaflets on the plaza. They pushed 
him into a car and drove away. Only his shoe was left behind. 
</P>
<P>
	Police tried to prevent bystanders from picking up the leaflets,  
which criticized pervasive official corruption -- a key complaint of 
the 1989 protests. It was signed ``Beijing university student.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most people, however, went about their normal activities.  
Hundreds turned out, as always, to watch soldiers lower the red 
national flag on the square at the end of the day. Dozens of 
uniformed and plainclothes officers, some carrying walkie-talkies 
hidden in newspapers, kept watch. Police briefly detained at least 
five foreign journalists and confiscated their film. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin  
said the United States has asked China to make a full accounting to 
relatives of those killed and release people serving sentences for 
participating peacefully in the demonstrations. 
</P>
<P>
	``U.S.-China relations will not reach their full potential until  
China brings its human rights practices into compliance with its 
obligations under international human rights instruments,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiananmen Square was closed, encircled by a high metal wall  
while workers laid new paving stones. State-run television opened 
the noon newscast with a report on the seven-month-long 
reconstruction project. Footage showed workers and normal traffic 
flow around the square. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese army began attacking crowds in central Beijing late  
on June 3, 1989. Troops and tanks reached the square before dawn on 
June 4, forcing the last demonstrators to leave -- and ending seven 
weeks of protests that had drawn as many as 1 million people to 
Tiananmen Square and inspired demonstrations in other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of people killed is unknown. The government has never  
given a credible account, but many hundreds are believed to have 
died. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese leaders ordered extra vigilance this year to prevent  
anyone from using the anniversary to stir up anger over rising 
unemployment and widespread corruption. At least 130 dissidents 
were questioned in recent weeks and 42 were in police custody over 
the anniversary, according to the Hong Kong-based Information 
Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those taken in the latest roundup was Liu Feng, a  
Protestant detained Friday on his way to meet friends to pray for 
those who died in the assault, the group said. 
</P>
<P>
	At Wan An Cemetery, near Fragrant Hills on the western outskirts  
of the capital, more than 20 relatives of five victims of the 
assault held a commemorative gathering. Police guarded the entrance 
and a sign in English and Chinese said, ``No correspondents 
accepted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Afterwards, mourners said they took the boxed ashes of three of  
the victims from vaults and put them on the grave of another, Yuan 
Li, a 28-year-old doctoral student shot in the throat. They laid 
flowers on the tomb, sprinkled wine on the ground, stood in silence 
and said a few words of remembrance. A strip of paper placed atop 
the tomb said: ``Mourn the victims of June 4th.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It has already been 10 years since June 4, but the government  
ignores this incident. As the living, we feel we have to stand 
up,'' said You Weijie, whose husband died after being shot in the 
pelvis. 
</P>
<P>
	She and Huang Jinping, who also lost her husband, rode bicycles  
past the spots near Tiananmen Square where their spouses were shot. 
On the front of one bike basket, they hung the ``mourn the victim'' 
paper strip that had been on the tomb, a defiant act given the 
thick police presence. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the only strip of China where commemoration of the  
Tiananmen protests was allowed, thousands of people gathered Friday 
for a candlelight vigil to mourn those killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Songs glorifying the students blared from speakers. A banner  
reading ``June 4: 10th year'' hung from the stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to let the children know about June 4. It is a very big  
event in Chinese history. I hope they can learn about it and 
remember,'' said Anthony Chow, a pastor, who attended the memorial 
with his wife and three young children, aged 4 to 11. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:31:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
