which criticized pervasive official corruption -- a key complaint of 
the 1989 protests. It was signed ``Beijing university student.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most people, however, went about their normal activities.  
Hundreds turned out, as always, to watch soldiers lower the red 
national flag on the square at the end of the day. Dozens of 
uniformed and plainclothes officers, some carrying walkie-talkies 
hidden in newspapers, kept watch. Police briefly detained at least 
five foreign journalists and confiscated their film. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin  
said the United States has asked China to make a full accounting to 
relatives of those killed and release people serving sentences for 
participating peacefully in the demonstrations. 
</P>
<P>
	``U.S.-China relations will not reach their full potential until  
China brings its human rights practices into compliance with its 
obligations under international human rights instruments,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiananmen Square was closed, encircled by a high metal wall  
while workers laid new paving stones. State-run television opened 
the noon newscast with a report on the seven-month-long 
reconstruction project. Footage showed workers and normal traffic 
flow around the square. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese army began attacking crowds in central Beijing late  
on June 3, 1989. Troops and tanks reached the square before dawn on 
June 4, forcing the last demonstrators to leave -- and ending seven 
weeks of protests that had drawn as many as 1 million people to 
Tiananmen Square and inspired demonstrations in other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of people killed is unknown. The government has never  
given a credible account, but many hundreds are believed to have 
died. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese leaders ordered extra vigilance this year to prevent  
anyone from using the anniversary to stir up anger over rising 
unemployment and widespread corruption. At least 130 dissidents 
were questioned in recent weeks and 42 were in police custody over 
the anniversary, according to the Hong Kong-based Information 
Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those taken in the latest roundup was Liu Feng, a  
Protestant detained Friday on his way to meet friends to pray for 
those who died in the assault, the group said. 
</P>
<P>
	At Wan An Cemetery, near Fragrant Hills on the western outskirts  
of the capital, more than 20 relatives of five victims of the 
assault held a commemorative gathering. Police guarded the entrance 
and a sign in English and Chinese said, ``No correspondents 
accepted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Afterwards, mourners said they took the boxed ashes of three of  
the victims from vaults and put them on the grave of another, Yuan 
Li, a 28-year-old doctoral student shot in the throat. They laid 
flowers on the tomb, sprinkled wine on the ground, stood in silence 
and said a few words of remembrance. A strip of paper placed atop 
the tomb said: ``Mourn the victims of June 4th.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It has already been 10 years since June 4, but the government  
ignores this incident. As the living, we feel we have to stand 
up,'' said You Weijie, whose husband died after being shot in the 
pelvis. 
</P>
<P>
	She and Huang Jinping, who also lost her husband, rode bicycles  
past the spots near Tiananmen Square where their spouses were shot. 
On the front of one bike basket, they hung the ``mourn the victim'' 
paper strip that had been on the tomb, a defiant act given the 
thick police presence. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the only strip of China where commemoration of the  
Tiananmen protests was allowed, thousands of people gathered Friday 
for a candlelight vigil to mourn those killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Songs glorifying the students blared from speakers. A banner  
reading ``June 4: 10th year'' hung from the stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to let the children know about June 4. It is a very big  
event in Chinese history. I hope they can learn about it and 
remember,'' said Anthony Chow, a pastor, who attended the memorial 
with his wife and three young children, aged 4 to 11. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
