<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                     *George Washington Bentley    	
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- George Washington Bentley, the last surviving  
founder of The American Legion, died Friday. He was 101. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, Bentley was awarded the Legion of Honor, the highest  
medal of the French government, for his service in France during 
World War I. 
</P>
<P>
	Bentley was assigned to the U.S. Army Engineers Purchasing  
Office in France from June 1918 to October 1919 and saw an ad about 
a meeting to discuss forming an organization of wartime veterans. 
Bentley attended the three-day Paris meeting with more than 1,000 
others in March 1919 at which The American Legion was formed. 
</P>
<P>
	All the attendees are considered founders because they took part  
in forming the organization. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Peter Brough    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Peter Brough, a radio star who attracted a British  
audience of millions in the 1950s as the ventriloquist who brought 
puppet Archie Andrews to life, died Thursday. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	The radio show ``Educating Archie'' served as a launching pad  
for many comics and actors, most notably Julie Andrews, a regular 
on the British Broadcasting Corp. show as a child. 
</P>
<P>
	Brough was a favorite of the royal family, playing at Royal  
Variety Performances and organizing the Windsor Castle staff ball 
for many years. 
</P>
<P>
	After performing for King George VI and the princesses Elizabeth  
and Margaret, the trio asked for the dummy's head to be taken off 
while they had a good look at the controls. 
</P>
<P>
	Brough retired from show business in the 1960s and went on to  
run a textile business. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Zachary Fisher    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Zachary Fisher, a developer and Russian  
immigrant whose lifelong interest in the U.S. military led him to 
convert an abandoned aircraft carrier into an acclaimed naval 
museum, died Friday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher was honored by presidents Bill Clinton and Ronald Reagan  
for his philanthropic efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher's avocation was the U.S. military, and his interest  
peaked after hearing of plans to consign the historic USS Intrepid 
to the scrapyard. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher started a foundation to save the Intrepid in 1978. Four  
years later, the battle-scarred carrier was home to the Intrepid 
Air Sea Space Museum, which is now the world's largest navel 
museum. It remains docked in the Hudson River. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, President Clinton awarded Fisher the Medal of Freedom  
for his efforts on behalf of the military. He also donated millions 
of dollars to the children of military personnel killed in the line 
of duty, starting with the survivors of the Marines killed in 
1983's Beirut barracks bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher also founded the Fisher Houses -- 28 mansions built on the  
grounds of military hospitals across the country as inexpensive 
housing for relatives of patients. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Wil Quick    	
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Wil Quick, a journalist known for his  
anti-smoking advocacy, died Wednesday after suffering a heart 
attack on May 25. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Quick, also known for his passion for civil rights, genealogy,  
the military and the Republican Party, was a reporter and editor at 
the Milwaukee Sentinel from 1960 to 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoking irritated his eyes and gave him a headache. By the 1970s  
-- long before the nation was in its anti-smoking mode -- he was in 
full pursuit of cigarette, pipe and cigar users. 
</P>
<P>
	He filed city ordinance complaints against a Sentinel  
sportswriter and a Milwaukee Journal associate editor for smoking 
in company elevators. 
</P>
<P>
	Quick joined the Wisconsin Initiative on Smoking and Health  
shortly after its founding a decade ago and had a major role in 
expanding the number of smoke-free Wisconsin restaurants listed in 
a dining guide from 65 to the current 1,460. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked at newspapers in Dayton, Ohio, Huntington, W.Va., and  
Three Rivers, Mich., before joining the Sentinel. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, two sons and two daughters.  

</P>
<P>
                          *John McKeithen    	
</P>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Former Gov. John McKeithen, a memorable  
stump speaker who worked to ease race relations and gave New 
Orleans the Superdome, died Friday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only was McKeithen known for his oratory skills, he was able  
to adapt them for the media age. He was the first to use television 
successfully in a Louisiana governor's campaign, becoming famous 
for his ``won't you he'p me'' ads looking directly into the camera. 
</P>
<P>
	Big John, as he was called, served as governor from 1964 to  
1972. A hard-core Democrat, he appointed blacks to state government 
during the civil rights era and was remembered for his efforts to 
soothe racial tensions. 
</P>
<P>
	His administration drew praise and criticism over the Superdome,  
which he helped start but was completed in 1975 after he had been 
out of office for three years. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Keeter Skelton    	
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Keeter Skelton, the wife of former Associated  
Press Houston correspondent Max Skelton, died Wednesday. She was 
78. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Skelton was a former manager of the Press Club of Houston.  
</P>
<P>
	She was a graduate of the nursing program at Houston's Methodist  
Hospital in 1941 and was a second lieutenant in the Army Nurse 
Corps during World War II. She also conducted the Houston 
Chronicle's Goodfellows program for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband established the AP Houston bureau in 1947. He  
retired in 1982 after 35 years with AP and died in 1992. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Hilda Mae Snoops    	
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, Md. (AP) -- Hilda Mae Snoops, the longtime friend of  
former Gov. William Donald Schaefer who served as his official 
state hostess and unofficial first lady, died Friday. She was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Charles Snoops who introduced his wife to Schaefer, a  
childhood friend. After the Snoops divorced in 1962, Mrs. Snoops 
became Schaefer's companion. The two never married. 
</P>
<P>
	But when Schaefer was elected governor in 1986, the divorced  
mother of three took on a much more visible role. Mrs. Snoops, who 
called herself the ``first friend,'' was often at Schaefer's side 
at public and social events. 
</P>
<P>
	Her main task was to oversee the governor's mansion, and she was  
widely criticized for changes she made even though they were mostly 
privately funded. 
</P>
<P>
	One of her first acts was to renovate the mansion's public  
rooms, ripping out expensive restoration undertaken by Patricia 
Hughes, the wife of Schaefer's predecessor, Harry Hughes. Mrs. 
Hughes' use of styles representing different periods of Maryland 
history drew national acclaim, but Mrs. Snoops rejected them as too 
cold and museum-like. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Robert Sobel    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Robert Sobel, a prolific historian of American  
business life who wrote or edited more than 50 books and hundreds 
of articles, died Wednesday from brain cancer. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Sobel began teaching history at Hofstra University in 1956 after  
serving in the Korean War. He joined Hofstra's faculty in 1957, and 
stayed there until his retirement in May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Sobel wrote on topics ranging from the economic philosophy of  
President Calvin Coolidge to the influence of junk-bond financier 
Michael Milken. 
</P>
<P>
	His last book, ``When Giants Stumble,'' was recently released.  
Sobel completed the book as he underwent cancer treatments. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Ruth Whitney    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ruth Whitney, who for more than 30 years was  
editor-in-chief of Glamour magazine and influenced generations of 
women during the growth of American feminism, died Friday of Lou 
Gehrig's disease. She was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Whitney increased Glamour's circulation by 1 million after  
taking over in 1967. Under her leadership, it became the only 
women's magazine to twice win general excellence honors at the 
National Magazine Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	She had been executive editor of Seventeen and editor-in-chief  
of Better Living. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Whitney introduced more than 50 regular columns and features  
to keep pace with women's rapidly changing lifestyles. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a past president the American Society of Magazine  
Editors and was inducted into the 1996 ASME Editor's Hall of Fame 
for enhancing the traditional women's magazine format with a sense 
of social urgency and public service. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a son and a brother.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
