<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hearing Held on Notre Dame Booster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Notre Dame expects it will be at least four  
weeks before the NCAA decides whether to penalize the school 
because a former booster gave financial help to at least a dozen 
football players. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA's Committee on Infractions held a closed hearing  
Friday. A decision is expected in July or August. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA is investigating whether Kimberly Dunbar's relationship  
with players broke a rule stipulating that schools and their 
representatives cannot provide an athlete or a relative or friend 
of an athlete a benefit not authorized by the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	Court records show Dunbar, who is serving a four-year prison  
sentence after pleading guilty to embezzling more that $1.4 million 
from her former employer in South Bend, provided players, their 
families and friends with more than $35,000 in gifts and trips. 
</P>
<P>
	Notre Dame spokesman Dennis Moore said the school responded to  
the NCAA in a ``forthright and complete'' manner. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore said Notre Dame has disbanded the Quarterback Club, a  
group of boosters whose members included Dunbar. The school has 
held assistant coaches accountable for athletes' academic and 
personal development, Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA has already established that Dunbar became a  
representative of the university in June 1995 when she joined the 
Quarterback Club. Court records show she purchased gifts and trips 
for several players after that date, including presents for players 
with whom she had personal relationships. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them were Jarvis Edison, with whom she has a child. She  
took him, fellow player Allen Rossum and Rossum's girlfriend on a 
$10,000 trip to Las Vegas in 1997 to see the Evander Holyfield-Mike 
Tyson fight. She also took then-boyfriend Derrick Mayes to Las 
Vegas in 1995, paying for his $1,836 ticket and a $756 stay at the 
Luxor, according to court documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Jonas, a lawyer representing the company Dunbar embezzled  
the money from, said they have collected 5,000 to 10,000 pages of 
documents concerning Dunbar's relationship with Irish players, and 
the NCAA has not requested any information from them. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials have argued that the possible infractions  
were secondary. NCAA enforcement officials agreed, recommending in 
April the committee shouldn't view the case as major. But the 
infractions committee decided to review the case as a possible 
major violation. 
</P>
<P>
	To bolster their defense, the school has hired the law firm of  
Bond, Schoeneck &AMP; King. The firm, with an office near the NCAA in 
Overland Park, Kan., specializes in assisting colleges under 
investigation by the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	Notre Dame has claimed Dunbar provided the benefits to players  
``in the context of personal relationships'' and not as a booster. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Smrt, the NCAA's enforcement director and one of the  
officials that recommended Notre Dame's infractions be ruled 
secondary, said it's rare for enforcement officials to change their 
minds after making a recommendation to the committee, even if it's 
overruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he wouldn't comment on Notre Dame's case directly, he  
said enforcement officials usually argue for their original 
conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
	Smrt said the committee could rule Notre Dame committed a major  
infraction, but withhold serious punishment. If the committee rules 
the infractions as major, it could put the Irish on probation for 
five years. 
</P>
<P>
	That means any other violation would make Notre Dame eligible  
for harsh penalties -- a ban from national television or bowl games, 
loss of scholarships or recruiting restrictions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 11:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's ENI Gets New Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Renato Ruggiero, former head of the World Trade  
Organization, was named chairman of Italy's state-controlled energy 
holding company, ENI, today, succeeding incumbent Guglielmo 
Moscato, whose term is expiring. 
</P>
<P>
	The company shareholders' assembly also named Vittorio Mincato  
as its chief executive for another term. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian treasury, which owns 36.3 percent of ENI, must  
confirm the selections, but it is largely expected to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	A career diplomat in the Italian foreign service, Ruggiero also  
served as foreign trade minister between 1987 and 1991. His 
two-year stint as director general of the WTO ended April 30. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 09:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche Bank, Bankers Trust United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The merger between Germany's Deutsche  
Bank and U.S.-based Bankers Trust has been completed, creating the 
world's largest commercial financial institution, officials said 
today. Together, Germany's biggest bank and the eighth largest in 
the United States have assets of about 1.55 trillion German marks 
($820 billion), as of March 31, and a workforce of some 95,000. The 
final step in completing the merger was taken this week when 
finance authorities in Canada and New Jersey approved the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, approval was obtained from New York banking  
authorities, European Union cartel officials in Brussels and 
Washington, D.C., and Bankers Trust stockholders, a bank statement 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of Bankers Trust constitutes the biggest  
takeover of a U.S. financial institution by a foreign bank. The 
institution is be larger than UBS AG of Switzerland, currently the 
largest bank, and the recently formed Citigroup Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition to the merger came initially from Jewish  
organizations because of questions regarding Deutsche Bank 
restitution payments to victims of the Holocaust. After signs of a 
compromise on these questions, New York authorities gave their 
blessing, Deutsche Bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are leading in all important areas of financial services  
worldwide,'' Breuer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger, agreed to last November, is the largest takeover of  
a U.S. institution thus far by a foreign financial concern. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Bank is paying $10.1 billion for the deal, which will  
be financed partly through a capital increase of $3.16 billion, the 
bank said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
