<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Blocks Sale of Payroll Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Citing privacy concerns, the governor  
on Friday blocked a law from taking effect that would have allowed 
the state to sell confidential payroll data to private lenders. 
</P>
<P>
	The law allows a state agency to sell personal financial  
information to banks, car dealers and other lenders to help them 
verify an applicant's income, with the applicant's written 
permission. It was intended to expedite loan applications. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, signed by the former Republican governor, was  
expected to take effect later this year after a review period. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, agreed with privacy rights  
groups that said the law would allow systematic privacy violations 
and could result in the unauthorized distribution of sensitive 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	The state ``has a responsibility to protect the privacy of its  
citizens. The wholesale distribution of such information on the 
open market, in my view, would violate that trust and the privacy 
of those individuals,'' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis ordered the director of the Employment Development  
Department not to sell personal information, saying the law gives 
the director such discretion. The leeway also allows the governor 
to block the sale if he chooses, Davis' office said. 
</P>
<P>
	Programs allowing the sale of financial information are  
operating in Iowa, Minnesota, North Carolina and Texas and one is 
being implemented in Pennsylvania. Legislatures in Florida, Indiana 
and Oregon authorized such systems in recent weeks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
