<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Embarassing Microsoft E-Mail Detailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After months of watching its executives  
confronted in court with hard-to-explain e-mails, Microsoft spent 
Friday listening to more recent embarrassing electronic messages. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its trial strategy in fighting antitrust allegations,  
Microsoft wants to show the judge that one of its Internet software 
rivals, Netscape Communications Corp., wasn't illegally crippled 
during its battle with Microsoft's Windows computer operating 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	But Justice Department lawyer David Boies cited an e-mail  
exchange within Microsoft earlier this year -- months after its 
antitrust trial began -- that suggested even some Microsoft 
employees don't believe that Netscape remains a robust competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	``What data can we find right away that shows Netscape browser  
share is still healthy?'' spokesman Greg Shaw wrote to two other 
Microsoft employees earlier this year. ``It would help if you could 
send me some reports showing their market share healthy and 
holding. This is for press purposes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw got this response from Robert Bennett, a Windows product  
manager: 
</P>
<P>
	``All of the analysts have pretty much come to the same  
conclusion, which is that (Netscape) share is declining and 
(Microsoft's) is gaining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be proactively telling people that (Netscape)  
share is doing well -- we are winning because we have better 
technology -- if we show them maintaining/gaining share then we 
contradict that point,'' Bennett wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson laughed as Boies  
read the e-mails in court Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Economist Franklin Fisher volunteered from the witness stand  
that, ``This document speaks for itself rather louder than most.'' 
Fisher testified all week for the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft had other problems with e-mail in the courtroom  
Thursday, when a company lawyer, Michael Lacovara, sought to 
portray the popular upstart Linux operating system as a potential 
threat to the dominance of Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Lacovara introduced e-mail that Microsoft executive David Cole  
wrote last week, titled ``Linux is beating Windows.'' He included 
sales figures showing that at two West Coast electronics chains, 
Linux is outselling Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Boies indicated he was dubious because the e-mail was written so  
recently, and the judge seemed to agree. Jackson called the 
document a ``self-serving, out-of-court declaration'' but allowed 
Lacovara to enter it as evidence in the case. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
