<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Futures Rise; Cocoa Soars  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Energy futures rose sharply Friday on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange amid reports key world oil producers were doing a better 
job of keeping crude off the market. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, cocoa soared a second day, while coffee fell  
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude jumped amid estimates that the Organization of the  
Petroleum Exporting Countries in May improved compliance with an 
agreement to slash production of more than 2 percent of the world's 
oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts estimate that the 10 OPEC countries working to cut  
production met 72 percent of their goal from an April 1 baseline, 
up from 65 percent a month earlier. Compliance stood at 89 percent 
when compared to a February 1998 baseline. 
</P>
<P>
	The estimates helped support ideas the oil producers are serious  
about trying to prop crude prices, which rose sharply after they 
announced an agreement in March but have since drifted lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting crude and unleaded gasoline prices was news that  
Conoco Inc. had shut a 50,000 barrel-a-day gas-making unit at a 
Louisiana refinery. 
</P>
<P>
	The shutdown is the latest in a spate of gasoline production  
cutbacks. Producers in Europe and the United States in recent weeks 
have curtailed production as the cost of buying more expensive 
crude made it less profitable to refine it. 
</P>
<P>
	The shutdown comes with U.S. gasoline inventories up 2 percent  
from a year ago and about 8 percent above the five-year average, 
according to the American Petroleum Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude for July delivery rose 58 cents to $17.32 a barrel; July  
unleaded gasoline rose 1.51 cents to 50.11 cents a gallon; July 
heating oil rose 1.56 cents to 41.29 cents a gallon; July natural 
gas rose 4.3 cents to $2.440 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures jumped a second day on the Board of Trade of the  
City of New York as cocoa shipments slowed to a trickle, suggesting 
a glut may begin to fade in coming weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures on Thursday posted their biggest gains in nearly  
nine years, recovering from recent six-year lows, as cocoa traders 
and exporters reported fewer arrivals of beans at ports in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivory Coast, the world's largest cocoa grower, in the week ended  
May 30 shipped an estimated 7,540 metric tons, down by nearly half 
the week's previous 14,280 metric tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghana, another large grower, also is expected to run out of  
shipments soon, providing supply-side relief to a market that has 
been pressured by a bumper world crop and weaker world demand. 
</P>
<P>
	July cocoa rose $35 to $1,058 a ton.  
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures fell sharply on the New York Board of Trade after  
meteorologists predicted the chance for frost in Brazil, the 
world's largest grower, is slim in coming days. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices have seesawed in recent days as speculators bet  
Brazil cannot make it through a third winter without a damaging 
frost. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil produces mainly robusta beans, which are not certified  
for delivery against New York futures contracts. But many roasters 
mix those beans with high-quality arabica beans for gourmet blends, 
and record production last year left the world flush with supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	July arabica coffee fell 3.05 cents to $1.20 a pound.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
