<HEADLINE> NFL Suspends Leon Lett Indefinitely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Dallas Cowboys Pro Bowl defensive tackle  
Leon Lett was suspended indefinitely by the NFL on Friday for 
violating the league's substance-abuse policy for the third time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can confirm that he has been suspended indefinitely,'' NFL  
spokesman Joe Browne said. 
</P>
<P>
	Browne refused to discuss the details of Lett's case other than  
to say the lineman can reapply for admission to the league in the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	The length of the suspension will be determined by NFL  
commissioner Paul Tagliabue based on evaluations of Lett's progress 
by officials in the league's substance-abuse program. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys were notified of the suspension on Friday. Spokesman  
Rich Dalrymple released a statement declining comment on behalf of 
the team ``because of the confidential nature of the NFL's 
substance testing policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reports that Lett might be facing another league suspension have  
been circulating for months. 
</P>
<P>
	Lett, 30, has been enrolled in the NFL's substance-abuse program  
since 1995. He was suspended four games in 1995, for the last three 
games of 1996 and the first 13 of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 season was his first complete one since 1994 and, as in  
that season, he made the Pro Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Lett's agent, Jim Steiner, could not be reached Friday night.  
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-6, 300-pound Lett went from seventh-round draft pick  
from Emporia State in 1991 to Pro Bowl starter by 1994. Nicknamed 
``The Big Cat,'' Lett used size, speed and strength to become a 
standout in the middle of a solid defensive line, both as a 
run-stopper and pass rusher. 
</P>
<P>
	He had 51 tackles, four sacks, 20 quarterback pressures and a  
team-high seven tackles for losses last season. His presence was 
considered a big reason the Cowboys' run defense improved from 24th 
in 1997 to 12th in 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
