</P>
<P>
	Stock Markets To Close Early Dec. 31  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Major U.S. stock markets will close early on New  
Year's Eve as a precaution against any Year 2000 computer glitches, 
officials said. Trading on the New York Stock Exchange, the Nasdaq 
Stock Market and the American Stock Exchange will end at 1 p.m. on 
Dec. 31. Traditionally, the markets only close early on two days of 
the year: the day after Thanksgiving and Christmas Eve. Richard 
Grasso, chairman of the NYSE, said yesterday he expects its systems 
and those of users of the markets to be in perfect shape for the 
change, but think the early close is a prudent step. 

</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Bank, Bankers Trust Join  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The merger between Germany's Deutsche  
Bank and U.S.-based Bankers Trust has been completed, creating the 
world's largest commercial financial institution, officials said 
today. Together, Germany's biggest bank and the eighth largest in 
the United States have assets of about 1.55 trillion German marks 
($820 billion), as of March 31, and a workforce of some 95,000. The 
final step in completing the merger was taken this week when 
finance authorities in Canada and New Jersey approved the deal. The 
acquisition of Bankers Trust constitutes the biggest takeover of a 
U.S. financial institution by a foreign bank. The new institution 
is be larger than UBS AG of Switzerland, currently the largest 
bank, and the recently formed Citigroup Inc. 

</P>
<P>
	Duty-Free Shopping Ending in Europe  
</P>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- Duty-free shopping within the European  
Union will almost certainly end June 30, after EU leaders failed to 
agree today on a reprieve for the popular travelers' perk. A 
last-ditch appeal from British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his 
French counterpart, Lionel Jospin, failed to muster the required 
unanimity within the 15-nation bloc when Denmark and the 
Netherlands refused to agree. EU nations all agreed nine years ago 
to end tax-free sales of liquor, cigarettes, perfume and other 
luxury goods for travelers on ferries and planes between EU 
nations. Duty-free sales will still be allowed for travel outside 
the EU. 

</P>
<P>
	Shareholders Back Laura Ashley's Plan  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The floral prints and bright summer clothes on the  
racks at Laura Ashley stores offer little hint of the company's 
grim struggle to stave off insolvency. The British retailer, which 
made its name selling English country fashions and furnishings, 
recently won a crucial reprieve when bankers agreed to let it 
continue borrowing so long as it sold off its unprofitable chain of 
U.S. stores. But while shareholders approved the sale yesterday, 
enabling Laura Ashley to write off $34.4 million in debt, the 
retail chain must still try to recover from years of losses and 
chaotic management, including seven chief executives in 10 years. 

</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom Sued Over Skytel  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom is being sued by investors and may  
be facing a federal probe over whether it improperly concealed its 
plans to buy paging company Skytel Communications. A class-action 
suit was announced late yesterday by a group of investors charging 
they made money-losing trades after MCI WorldCom made misleading 
statements. Regulators, meanwhile, are reportedly investigating 
whether MCI WorldCom intentionally mislead investors with its 
statements regarding the Web address on May 25, three days before 
announcing the $1.3 billion purchase of Skytel. 

</P>
<P>
	Cabletron Gets New CEO  
</P>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Cabletron Systems, a computer networking  
company, named a new chairman and chief executive today. Piyush 
Patel, 43, former chief executive of a technology company acquired 
by Cabletron last year, will succeed co-founder Craig Benson as 
chairman, chief executive and president, the company said. Patel 
said he wants to make Cabletron a leader in growing markets for 
delivering voice, video and data. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com Defends Best-Sellers Ads  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Internet bookseller Amazon.com has asked a  
federal court to declare that it can continue to cite The New York 
Times' best-seller list in advertising discount prices, the company 
said. Amazon.com announced May 17 that it would offer 50 percent 
discounts on books on the Times' best-seller list. In a statement 
today, Amazon.com said the Times demanded May 28 in a letter that 
Amazon.com stop using the list for promotions, saying Amazon was 
infringing on the newspaper's copyright and trademark. Amazon.com 
shares were at 108 7/16, up 3 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Cathay Cancels More Flights  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- A weeklong sickout by pilots forced Cathay  
Pacific Airways to ground half its scheduled flights today, but 
airline officials said the situation appears to be improving and 
resumed taking flight bookings for selected routes. The airlines 
and the main pilots' union plan to meet tomorrow to discuss their 
differences. Cathay canceled 59 of the 117 flights scheduled today, 
but began accepting bookings for various destinations ahead of 
tomorrow's meeting. 

</P>
