<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets' Bonilla Upset by Waiver Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Saying the New York Mets could ``ship me to  
Alaska'' if they wanted to get rid of him, Bobby Bonilla reacted 
angrily Friday to a report the team had put him and fellow 
outfielder Brian McRae on waivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do I want to stay here? Ask me if I care,'' Bonilla said  
before the opener of a three-game interleague series against the 
New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can ship me to Alaska if they want. They can send me home  
tomorrow if they like,'' he said. ``I'll watch the boys play from 
my house. I might even buy a season ticket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times reported Friday that both players had been  
placed on waivers by the Mets earlier this week. If any team 
claimed them, the Mets would have automatically lost them. 
</P>
<P>
	Mets general manager Steve Phillips declined to say whether  
Bonilla and McRae had been put on waivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to comment on the report,'' Phillips said.  
``There's nothing to tell them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said he had not been told of such a move.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just don't know,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bonilla, 36, began the night batting only .160 with four home  
runs and 14 RBIs. Put on the disabled list in May because of a 
bruised knee, Bonilla is making $5.9 million this season. 
</P>
<P>
	McRae, 31, began the day batting .262 with five homers and 17  
RBIs. In his first at-bat of the night at Yankee Stadium, he hit a 
solo home run off David Cone in the second inning. 
</P>
<P>
	McRae, who recently criticized Valentine's lineups, did not  
appear as bothered as Bonilla by the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in the big leagues long enough that nothing  
surprises me anymore,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets' outfield situation this season has been complicated by  
the impressive play of young Roger Cedeno and Benny Agbayani. Along 
with Rickey Henderson in left field, the Mets have five players 
vying for three starting spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Major leaguers are routinely placed on waivers, often to make it  
possible to trade them. The first time a player is put on waivers 
during each waiver period, a team retains the right to pull him off 
waivers if another club claims him. Teams do not have that 
opportunity the second time. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips and Valentine both said they did not plan to address  
the situation with Bonilla and McRae. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said his biggest problem was finding enough playing  
time for his outfielders. Bonilla served as the designated hitter 
Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tough spot,'' Valentine said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
