<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Violence Mars Indonesia Campaigning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's election campaign came to  
a chaotic end Friday when troops fired warning shots at 
rock-throwing mobs attacking supporters of the ruling party. 
</P>
<P>
	All sides must now observe a two-day cooling-off period before  
Monday's crucial balloting for a new Parliament -- Indonesia's 
freest election in 44 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golkar Party, which dominated the political landscape for  
decades under former authoritarian President Suharto, made a 
last-ditch attempt Friday to reverse poor poll showings and 
overcome a series of fizzled rallies. 
</P>
<P>
	About 10,000 people showed up for the rally in the city center,  
but that was a fraction of the throngs that have turned out for 
opposition leader Megawati Sukarnoputri's party. Before long, 
simmering anti-Golkar resentment boiled over in at least three 
parts of the capital, Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Mobs, including many Megawati supporters, threw rocks and set  
motorcycles and a bus on fire. They chased Golkar supporters and 
stripped off their yellow T-shirts, burning them along with Golkar 
flags. 
</P>
<P>
	``Long live Mega! We hate Golkar!'' cried one activist, Budi  
Rachmad. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge rallies organized by Megawati have showed widespread  
support for the daughter of Indonesia's charismatic founder, 
President Sukarno, who died in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Her Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle, once banned by  
Suharto, has formed a coalition with two other opposition groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of riot police armed with batons and shields were sent  
to trouble spots and soldiers fired warning shots over the heads of 
about 2,000 people in eastern Jakarta. Some soldiers fired directly 
into the crowd, but officers at the scene said they were using 
blanks. 
</P>
<P>
	State radio reported five injuries, including two children.  
</P>
<P>
	Calm returned to the areas about an hour later after a heavy  
thunderstorm swept through the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting also broke out in central Java between supporters of  
the Muslim-based United Development Party and the National 
Awakening Party, who have clashed in several towns. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Friday's clashes, the campaign turned out to be more  
peaceful than expected. Some ethnic Chinese, who have been targeted 
in past unrest, and foreigners have fled the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in their party colors, singing songs and chanting  
slogans, many of the supporters of the 48 parties appeared 
overjoyed by the prospect of an open election. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Suharto, who resigned last year amid riots and student  
protests, only three parties were allowed to participate in 
elections that many critics claimed were rigged. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar chairman Akbar Tanjung said Thursday that the party has  
abandoned its role as an instrument of authoritarian rule and was 
dedicated to democratic reform and human rights. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited the record of President B.J. Habibie, who has legalized  
political parties and freed many political prisoners since 
Suharto's downfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar has named Habibie, Suharto's hand-picked successor, as  
its presidential candidate when the new Parliament helps choose a 
new leader later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanjung predicted that Golkar would win 30 percent to 40 percent  
of the vote Monday. But opinion polls have shown Golkar with far 
less support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
