<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Admits Embezzling $1.4M Book Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A debt collector for Penguin Books USA Inc.  
admitted in court Friday that he and the company's former 
collections manager embezzled $1.4 million from the publishing 
house. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerome F. Bedell, the collection agent, has been cooperating  
with federal investigators and the company since it uncovered the 
scheme 2 1/2 years ago, and has paid back the more than $900,000 he 
received, said his lawyer, Donald R. Belsole. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his cooperation, Bedell, 57, of Morristown, could still  
face several months in prison on the single conspiracy charge, as 
well as a fine of up to $250,000 or twice the gain or loss from the 
scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	Penguin has maintained the manager, Christina Galatro, hid  
stolen payments from bookstores by extending unauthorized discounts 
to book retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	To cover losses from the embezzlement, discounts and potential  
legal settlements, Penguin parent Pearson P.L.C., the British media 
conglomerate, two years ago took a $163 million pretax charge 
against 1996 earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal prompted the American Booksellers Association to  
examine whether Penguin's discount practices constituted favoritism 
with bookselling chains. Penguin settled the case with a $25 
million payment to the group, which represents independent 
booksellers. 
</P>
<P>
	A Penguin spokesman, Michael Gross, said the company would have  
no comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Messages left for representatives of the booksellers' group were  
not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Galatro was also scheduled to plead guilty Friday but  
canceled. ``She's just not available today,'' said her lawyer, 
Chris S.M. Franzblau, who said she still intends to plead guilty to 
federal criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Penguin employee also helped steal the money, according  
to court papers, but was not named by Bedell. Lawyers declined to 
identify the person. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Galatro is still contesting a Penguin lawsuit charging that  
she and her husband, Stanley, used her cut of the embezzlement -- 
more than $400,000 -- to finance cruises to Alaska, Europe and the 
Caribbean as well as other trips and purchases of antiques and 
jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
	Franzblau said Mrs. Galatro, of Freehold, was released from  
civil liability in her termination agreement and that Penguin still 
owes her $300,000 in severance pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Penguin in June 1997 disclosed the embezzlement when it  
announced its suit against Mrs. Galatro. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell operated Associated Collection Bureau Inc. in Morristown  
beginning in 1976; it changed its name to Associated Companies Inc. 
in 1994 and moved to nearby Parsippany. He has since sold the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Galatro, a Penguin employee since 1980, became manager of  
its collections department in Bergenfield in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	She and Bedell embezzled by two methods, according to Bedell:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Starting in spring 1992, Mrs. Galatro assigned delinquent  
accounts to Bedell for collection, for which he would get up to 25 
percent as his fee. Instead of returning the money he garnered to 
Penguin, Bedell kept it. Mrs. Galatro made false entries at Penguin 
to make it appear the accounts were uncollectable. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Mrs. Galatro stole more than 45 checks from Penguin customers,  
totaling more than $1 million, from November 1995 to January 1997. 
She gave them to Bedell, who cashed them. 
</P>
<P>
	She received her share through an American Express credit card  
Bedell gave her and paid for her purchases, he admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell is to be sentenced Aug. 30 by U.S. District Judge John C.  
Lifland, but that could be delayed, depending on when Mrs. 
Galatro's plea is taken. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
