<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 09:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Mulls Case Against Ill. Lawmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHEATON, Ill. (AP) -- A jury deliberated charges today in the  
conspiracy trial of five lawmen accused of railroading a man for 
the slaying of a 10-year-old girl, after defense attorneys said the 
man's testimony was riddled with lies. 
</P>
<P>
	In closing arguments Thursday, several jurors chuckled as  
attorney Brian Telander ridiculed Rolando Cruz for contradictions 
in his story and admitted lies. 
</P>
<P>
	``This guy lied so much that his name should be Pinocchio, not  
Rolando,'' Telander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cruz claimed he never made an incriminating statement to  
detectives in the 1983 rape and bludgeoning death of 10-year-old 
Jeanine Nicarico of Naperville, who was abducted from her home. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Terry Ekl suggested to jurors that Cruz may  
well have been involved in the crime, or at least talked to someone 
who was. He cited a litany of statements in which Cruz told 
authorities details of the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Special prosecutor William Kunkle argued that Cruz, who spent  
nearly a decade on death row before he was freed, had been 
railroaded. A history of questionable actions, nonexistent reports 
and evolving statements prove the four DuPage County sheriff's 
deputies and an ex-county prosecutor lied and concocted evidence 
against Cruz, Kunkle said. 
</P>
<P>
	The authorities ignored evidence that another man may have  
committed the crime alone because it conflicted with their 
overzealous pursuit of Cruz, Kunkle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors began deliberations in the cases of four defendants late  
Thursday and resumed work today. Judge William A. Kelly will decide 
the fate of the other defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	Cruz was acquitted in 1995 at his third trial, when a dramatic  
change in testimony by one of the deputies. The new testimony cast 
doubt on the contention that Cruz gave two sheriff's detectives 
incriminating details in a statement describing a ``dream'' or 
``vision'' about the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	No police report was ever made on Cruz's alleged statement, and  
Kunkle contends the detectives made it up. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants are charged with conspiracy to obstruct justice  
and conspiracy to commit official misconduct. The deputies face 
additional charges, including perjury. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
