<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kentucky Election Charges Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- A judge threw out charges Friday against  
two top aides to Gov. Paul Patton and two union leaders, ruling 
that the campaign finance laws they allegedly violated were 
unconstitutionally vague. 
</P>
<P>
	The four had been accused of taking part in a scheme to  
circumvent spending limits during Patton's 1995 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Patton, traveling in Japan, said the dismissal of the charges  
was ``welcome news.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charges were thrown out against Andrew ``Skipper'' Martin,  
Patton's chief of staff; Danny Ross, the governor's liaison for 
labor; Lon Fields, former president of a Teamsters local in 
Louisville; and Robert Winstead, the local's current president. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors alleged that the Teamsters carried Ross on the union  
payroll so that the campaign would not have to pay his salary, and 
that the campaign, the union and other labor groups illegally 
coordinated their spending for a get-out-the-vote effort that 
proved decisive in the Democrat's narrow victory over Republican 
Larry Forgy. 
</P>
<P>
	But state Circuit Judge William W. Trude Jr. ruled that the  
campaign finance law's definitions of three terms -- contribution, 
independent expenditure and ``knowingly'' -- were too broad and 
vague. The General Assembly has already amended the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Ben Chandler, whose office brought the  
indictment, said he has not decided whether to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor had refused to suspend Martin or Ross. He said he  
is now ``even more convinced'' that none of the four violated 
``either the letter or the spirit of Kentucky's campaign finance 
laws as I understand them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ross' lawyer,Phillip Shepherd, said the old definitions ``made  
it impossible for anyone who was independently supporting a 
candidate to communicate with a campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``That just runs squarely afoul of the First  
Amendment.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 06:20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYSE Delays Extending Trading Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Balancing investors' desire for late-night stock  
trading with the need to maintain its integrity, the New York Stock 
Exchange has agreed to extend trading hours -- but not until next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Grasso, chairman of the NYSE, said that before the  
world's biggest stock market expands its hours it wants first to 
ensure there are no glitches with the year-2000 computer bug and 
the switch to reporting stock prices in decimals instead of 
fractions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were unanimous this morning in our view that nothing should  
happen, at the Big Board at least, until the millennium change and 
decimalization have been accomplished,'' Grasso said Thursday 
afternoon. That would put off extending the trading day until the 
middle of 2000, at the earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	The go-slow decision came a week after the Nasdaq Stock Market  
voted to begin extending its hours into the evening as soon as this 
fall. 
</P>
<P>
	By adding to its hours, the New York Stock Exchange will be  
taking a big step away from its roots on Wall Street, where traders 
in 1792 first gathered along a curb to buy and sell government 
bonds and bank stocks. In today's fast-paced markets, many 
companies and employees in the financial world will have to 
scramble to keep up. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, financial markets around the world are moving toward  
'round-the-clock trading and electronic trading businesses are 
offering added competition online to the U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	With U.S. markets' current hours of 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. Eastern  
time, investors on the West Coast get shut out after lunch. Between 
20 percent to 25 percent of online trades by individual investors 
are placed after hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies they trade are also becoming more global. As AT&AMP;T,  
IBM and others expand their operations overseas, they gain 
investors in different markets. And vice versa: two weeks ago, the 
NYSE said it would list shares of Japan's Toyota Motor Corp., which 
controls about 10 percent of the U.S. car market. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the NYSE's plans, an evening session would come first,  
followed shortly by the addition of an early morning session. 
Investors will only be able to trade 500 of the exchange's 3,088 
stocks during the extra hours. 
</P>
<P>
	For Wall Street firms and employees, the longer hours will be  
nothing short of a revolution. And some workers worry they won't 
have much time for family dinners or tucking the kids into bed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love what I do, but there's a limit to everything,'' said  
Marty Prinz, president of EDI Financial Inc., a brokerage in 
Dallas. ``Where do you draw the line for sacrificing? ... Most of 
the brokers don't get to spend much time with family while their 
kids are growing up, and I think this will help estrange family 
situations even more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prinz said he worried that the extra hours he'll put in  
supervising night trades could force him to give up time with his 
grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	``You miss out on some of the things that they do in school,''  
he said. ``I think there will be frustrations created by that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prinz and his colleagues may get their first taste of it this  
fall if Nasdaq adds a second, evening session. The extended session 
would start at 5:30 p.m. and end at 9 p.m. or 10 p.m. Eastern time. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq would not comment Thursday on the NYSE's decision to take  
the go-slow approach. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Frank Zarb, who heads Nasdaq, said last week, ``We are  
calling on the industry to do the right thing, to coordinate and be 
responsible and move in unison so the investor can be properly 
protected in the new world of extended hours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the Securities and Exchange  
Commission, which regulates U.S. markets, has voiced concerns about 
extending hours before the end of the year and the transition to 
decimal-quoted stock prices. The SEC declined to comment Thursday 
on the NYSE's decision but called attention to Levitt's earlier 
statements that the industry needs to place investor protection 
first. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia Stock Exchange also plans to expand its hours.  
But like the NYSE, it intends to wait until next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Frucher, chairman of the Philadelphia Stock Exchange, said  
waiting until next year makes sense: ``This will provide the 
industry the time to look at the ramifications of extended hours. 
We want people to deal with their finances as investments and not 
look at the stock market as a gambling casino.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press Writer Beth Gardiner in New York  
contributed to this story. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
