<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nucor CEO Resigns Amid Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE (AP) -- Nucor's chief executive abruptly resigned after  
being passed over for the company chairmanship and clashing with 
top management over whether the nation's No. 2 steel-maker should 
invest in non-steel ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	John Correnti resigned Thursday after days of company meetings,  
including one Wednesday with the Charlotte-based steelmaker's board 
of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman David Aycock, 68, who received the job as Nucor's  
chairman on Jan. 1 following the retirement of company founder Ken 
Iverson, will serve as CEO until Correnti's successor is chosen. 
Aycock retired as Nucor president in 1991, but remained as a 
director until his elevation to chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Correnti) and the board had a little different ideas on the  
direction of the company for the future,'' Aycock said. ``The board 
wants to at least evaluate opportunities in industries or 
businesses that are not steel or steel products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Correnti, 52, acknowledged there were philosophical differences.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have different ideas about corporate strategy and  
how to move the company forward,'' he said. ``This (resignation) is 
a personal decision concerning the future direction of the 
company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson-Humphrey analyst Doug Moffat said he was dismayed by  
the moves, and cut his rating on the stock. 
</P>
<P>
	``Aycock had been out of the company for a long time. I was  
concerned when he came back in as chairman. Obviously, they 
clashed, and Correnti is out,'' Moffat said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aycock, 68, became Nucor's chairman on Jan. 1, following the  
retirement of company founder Ken Iverson. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Aycock said he asked Iverson to leave because the  
company needed to ``start thinking about succession. All up and 
down the line, I didn't feel the company made enough effort with 
succession.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For years prior to his 1996 appointment as chief executive,  
Correnti had been Iverson's heir apparent. Correnti was with 
Nucor's bigger rival U.S. Steel for 11 years before joining Nucor 
in 1980. He succeeded Aycock as president in 1991, and became chief 
executive in 1996. During that time, Nucor's sales nearly tripled, 
from $1.5 billion in 1991 to $4.15 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Nucor, after dropping more than 8 percent Thursday,  
fell 56 1/4 cents to $46.43 3/4 in trading on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 06:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Internet Connections Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Europeans are getting wired, with the number of  
household and business Internet connections nearly doubling last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Dataquest Inc. reports 10 percent of Western European households  
were connected last year, up from five percent in 1997, according 
to today's edition of The Wall Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	About 36 percent of U.S. households were online at the end of  
1998, Dataquest says. 
</P>
<P>
	Business connections in Europe increased to 9.5 percent, up from  
five percent the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany led the way online both at home and work with 24  
percent, and the United Kingdom was second with 17 percent, the 
Journal reported. The fastest growth was in Russia, France and 
Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Online connections in Europe were boosted in part by increased  
activity among Internet service providers, Dataquest said. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Jose, Calif.-based market research company predicts  
cheap broadband services will continue to fuel growth in Europe, 
likely increasing Internet penetration in Western European 
households to 17 percent and in businesses to 16 percent by the end 
of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The critical point to attract mainstream advertisers and  
businesses to the Internet is about 20 percent, Dataquest senior 
analyst Petra Gartzen told the Journal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 17:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Today In History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Today is Saturday, June 5, the 156th day of 1999. There are 209  
days left in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Highlight in History:  
</P>
<P>
	On June 5, 1968, Sen. Robert F. Kennedy was shot and mortally  
wounded just after claiming victory in California's Democratic 
presidential primary. Gunman Sirhan Bishara Sirhan was immediately 
arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	On this date:  
</P>
<P>
	In 1723, economist Adam Smith was born in Kirkcaldy, Scotland.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1783, Joseph and Jacques Montgolfier publicly demonstrated  
their hot-air balloon in a 10-minute flight over Annonay, France. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1794, Congress passed the Neutrality Act, which prohibited  
Americans from enlisting in the service of a foreign power. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1883, economist John Maynard Keynes was born in Cambridge,  
England. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1917, about 10 million American men began registering for the  
draft in World War I. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1933, the United States went off the gold standard.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1940, the Battle of France began during World War II.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1947, Secretary of State George C. Marshall gave a speech at  
Harvard University in which he outlined an aid program for Europe 
that came to be known as ``The Marshall Plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1967, war erupted in the Mideast as Israel raided Egyptian  
military targets. Syria, Jordan and Iraq entered the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1975, Egypt reopened the Suez Canal to international  
shipping, eight years after it was closed because of the 1967 war 
with Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years ago: In one of the most remembered images of China's  
crushed pro-democracy movement, a lone man stood defiantly in front 
of a line of tanks in Beijing until friends pulled him out of the 
way. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: President Clinton headed across the English  
Channel aboard the USS George Washington, en route to the 50th 
anniversary commemoration of D-Day in Normandy. At least 264 
Indonesian villagers in East Java were killed by an earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: A strike at a General Motors parts factory near  
Detroit closed five assembly plants and idled workers nationwide; 
the walkout lasted seven weeks. Volkswagen AG won approval to buy 
Rolls-Royce Motor Cars for $700 million. However, BMW later 
purchased the Rolls-Royce brand name and logo. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Birthdays: Broadcast journalist Bill Moyers is 65. Actor  
Spalding Gray is 58. Rhythm-and-blues singer Floyd Butler (Friends 
of Distinction) is 58. Country singer Don Reid (The Statler 
Brothers) is 54. Rock musician Fred Stone (Sly and the Family 
Stone) is 53. Rock singer Laurie Anderson is 52. Country singer 
Gail Davies is 51. Rock musician Nicko McBrain (Iron Maiden) is 45. 
Jazz musician Kenny G is 43. Rock singer Richard Butler 
(Psychedelic Furs) is 43. Actress Karen Sillas is 34. Singer Brian 
McKnight is 30. Actor Mark Wahlberg is 28. Actor Chad Allen is 25. 
Rock musician P-nut (311) is 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Thought for Today: ``Dare to be naive.''-- R. Buckminster Fuller,  
American inventor and philosopher (1895-1983). 

  	   	
