<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sick Tarantula Gets Top-Notch Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CATONSVILLE, Md. (AP) -- A CAT scan is set for Friday on a  
patient with a habit of showing her fangs and shooting barbed hairs 
from her rump. The patient, Goliath tarantula No. 79011, is 
suffering from an infection. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has a robust, loose personality,'' said Sandy Barnett,  
senior herpetologist at The National Aquarium in Baltimore. ``I 
really hope we can help her out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Giving a CAT scan to a spider is not a regular event, but this  
spider is special and worthy of saving say those who know her. 
</P>
<P>
	Although not rare, her value is in what she can teach doctors  
about the medical care of tarantulas in captivity. 
</P>
<P>
	A member of the largest spider species in the world, No. 79011  
underwent a CAT scan Friday to check on a nasty infection oozing 
from her side. The prognosis wasn't good. Doctors are planning to 
perform a lifesaving operation next week to try to save the 
eight-legged creature. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 79011, weighing in at a hefty 2 1/2 ounces, is the size of a  
salad plate, has dark brown hair, and a turret of eyes atop a flat 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	She also has an abscess the size of a quarter that is causing  
her loose fluid. Instead of walking on the tips of her toes like a 
ballerina, she's down at the heel -- a sure sign of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``They use water pressure to keep their legs up,'' Ms. Barnett  
said. ``This one is walking a little flat-footed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An antibiotic ointment had no effect and another technique,  
punching a hole in her side to drain the infection, could kill her, 
said Dr. Brent Whitaker, the aquarium's director of animal health 
who is to perform the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. David Herring, a veterinary radiologist who donated his  
expertise, said the images Friday looked worse than when first 
taken last month. The abscess looks to be contained within the 
spider's body cavity, making it possible to perform surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	During the procedure, the same artificial skin used in human  
surgery will be used to create a covering over the abscess. The 
abscess can then be drained and more artificial skin can be used to 
seal the drain hole, Whitaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Ian Walker, a veterinary intern at the aquarium who hopes to  
assist Whitaker, said his biggest fear is that he could break into 
the body cavity by mistake, causing her powder blue blood to leak 
out uncontrollably. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will probably lose the animal anyway if we don't try,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tarantula, which comes from South American rain forest, is  
worth all the effort, Whitaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't discriminate,'' he said. ``All of our animals get  
topnotch care.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Embarassing Microsoft E-Mail Detailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After months of watching its executives  
confronted in court with hard-to-explain e-mails, Microsoft spent 
Friday listening to more recent embarrassing electronic messages. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its trial strategy in fighting antitrust allegations,  
Microsoft wants to show the judge that one of its Internet software 
rivals, Netscape Communications Corp., wasn't illegally crippled 
during its battle with Microsoft's Windows computer operating 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	But Justice Department lawyer David Boies cited an e-mail  
exchange within Microsoft earlier this year -- months after its 
antitrust trial began -- that suggested even some Microsoft 
employees don't believe that Netscape remains a robust competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	``What data can we find right away that shows Netscape browser  
share is still healthy?'' spokesman Greg Shaw wrote to two other 
Microsoft employees earlier this year. ``It would help if you could 
send me some reports showing their market share healthy and 
holding. This is for press purposes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw got this response from Robert Bennett, a Windows product  
manager: 
</P>
<P>
	``All of the analysts have pretty much come to the same  
conclusion, which is that (Netscape) share is declining and 
(Microsoft's) is gaining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be proactively telling people that (Netscape)  
share is doing well -- we are winning because we have better 
technology -- if we show them maintaining/gaining share then we 
contradict that point,'' Bennett wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson laughed as Boies  
read the e-mails in court Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Economist Franklin Fisher volunteered from the witness stand  
that, ``This document speaks for itself rather louder than most.'' 
Fisher testified all week for the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft had other problems with e-mail in the courtroom  
Thursday, when a company lawyer, Michael Lacovara, sought to 
portray the popular upstart Linux operating system as a potential 
threat to the dominance of Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Lacovara introduced e-mail that Microsoft executive David Cole  
wrote last week, titled ``Linux is beating Windows.'' He included 
sales figures showing that at two West Coast electronics chains, 
Linux is outselling Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Boies indicated he was dubious because the e-mail was written so  
recently, and the judge seemed to agree. Jackson called the 
document a ``self-serving, out-of-court declaration'' but allowed 
Lacovara to enter it as evidence in the case. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990604.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 09:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Falls to 4.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate dipped back  
down to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent in May even though the growth 
of payroll jobs was the smallest in more than three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Unemployment among blacks fell to the lowest level on record  
while the jobless rates of teen-agers and adult women hit 30-year 
lows as the strong U.S. economy continued to boost all economic 
groups, the Labor Department said in today's report. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the drop in unemployment, the total number of payroll  
jobs rose by just 11,000 in May, a sharp slowdown from the 343,000 
jobs created in April and the weakest showing since an outright 
decline in January 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration, which is hoping a healthy economy will  
convince voters to keep a Democrat in the White House next year, 
insisted that the slowdown in job creation merely depicted an 
economy shifting from red-hot growth to a more sustainable pace. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are in a phase now ... from sizzle to simmer, but it's  
still hot. It's still a good economy,'' Labor Secretary Alexis 
Herman told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets, which had grown increasingly jittery over  
worries that too-rapid growth would prompt the Federal Reserve to 
boost interest rates, took heart from today's report. The Dow Jones 
industrial average was up 60 points at midday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts said the small gain in payroll jobs may reflect  
that employers are having trouble finding qualified people in the 
current tight labor market. Others noted that while May's increase 
in jobs was tiny, the April figure had been revised up sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Private economists remained split on whether recent reports make  
it more or less likely that the central bank will start raising 
interest rates to slow the economy and keep inflation under 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Kasriel, chief economist at Northern Trust Co. in Chicago,  
said he was still looking for a rate increase at the Fed's next 
meeting on June 29-30 because the drop in the unemployment rate, 
along with other reports showing strong consumer demand, are making 
Fed policy-makers uneasy about rising inflationary pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that unemployment fell is the important message here  
along with the bump up in average hourly earnings,'' Kasriel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's report showed that average hourly earnings, a closely  
watched indicator for inflation, rose by 3.6 percent in May, 
compared to a year ago, a slight uptick from the previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4.2 percent jobless rate in May matched the March level, a  
29-year low. Unemployment last touched 4.2 percent in February 
1970. 
</P>
<P>
	The current economic expansion, the longest in peacetime  
history, has given the country a low overall unemployment rate and 
has also aided minority groups, who traditionally lag behind in 
economic gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said today that the unemployment rate for blacks  
fell to a record low of 7.5 percent in May, down from 7.7 percent 
the previous month. This was the lowest unemployment level for 
blacks since the government began tracking this statistic in 1972 
although the rate was still above the 3.7 percent unemployment rate 
for whites. The jobless rate for teen-agers dipped to 12.6 percent 
while the rate for adult women fell to 3.6 percent, both 30-year 
lows. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall gain of 11,000 payroll jobs reflected the fact that  
job growth in service industries moderated substantially last 
month, increasing by only 71,000, well below the average monthly 
gain of 125,000 over the past 12 months. 
</P>
<P>
	While business services added 42,000 jobs last month, reflecting  
strong gains in computer services, growth in engineering and 
management services moderated significantly. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of 45,000 jobs in manufacturing reflected widespread  
cuts in a number of industries including industrial machinery, 
apparel and aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	The mining sector, which includes oil and gas drilling, fell by  
7,000 in May. Construction, which had been enjoying huge large 
gains through the mild winter, suffered a setback of 40,000 lost 
jobs in May. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
