<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> P&AMP;G Said Planning Reorganization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.'s stock price jumped more  
than 3 percent Friday after a report that the consumer products 
maker plans to cut thousands of jobs and close plants at a cost of 
up to $3 billion to become more competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said they weren't surprised by what would be the  
company's second major reorganization in six years. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've been making changes over the last year with their new  
strategy,'' said Douglas Christopher, of Crowell, Weedon &AMP; Co. 
``The company's never been one to just sit around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have praised P&AMP;G for its recent introductions of  
revised or new products, such as last year's rollout of Febreze -- a 
product designed to remove odors from clothing and household 
fabrics -- and the company's continued effort to sell brands for 
which it doesn't anticipate business growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times reported Friday that P&AMP;G will announce the  
changes when its executives meet with investors and analysts 
Wednesday in New York to detail what P&AMP;G calls Organization 2005. 
The Times attributed its report to analysts and institutional 
investors who have already met with management. 
</P>
<P>
	P&AMP;G spokesman Simon Denegri declined to comment on the story.  
</P>
<P>
	In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Procter &AMP; Gamble was  
up $3.12 1/2 a share to $96.62 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	The expected announcement would be the first major overhaul  
since Durk Jager took over as chief executive Jan. 1 after 29 years 
with the company, which makes Crest toothpaste, Tide detergent and 
Pampers diapers among other products. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the new round of cuts are expected to take place outside  
the United States, the Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati-based consumer products company told shareholders  
in September that it planned corporate structural changes including 
forming business units based on products instead of regions, 
improving marketing and streamlining its staff. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said then that it believes the changes are necessary  
to bring new products to the market more quickly, and if the 
company is to meet its stated goal of improving profits and 
doubling its worldwide sales within 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	P&AMP;G said in September that the reorganization creates seven  
global business units based on product lines instead of four units 
based on geographical regions. It also centralizes business 
services such as accounting and payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	The global business units are to be responsible for their  
profits, design, research and development and personnel. Eight 
market development organizations will develop local marketing 
strategies, new distribution channels and improved retail-customer 
relationships. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest reorganization and the prior one implemented in 1993  
are intended to overhaul cumbersome layers of management that 
critics said made P&AMP;G bureaucratic and unable to quickly respond to 
market changes and new products from competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1993 reorganization, designed to reduce expenses to 12  
percent of sales, closed 30 plants and eliminated 13,000 positions 
throughout the world. Most of the job cuts came from early 
retirements, attrition and voluntary separation packages. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
