<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Shaken Baby Dies in Neb. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- A 3-year-old girl with severe brain injuries,  
allegedly caused by child abuse, died this week after her parents 
gave up a long legal battle with the state and agreed to let her be 
taken off life support. 
</P>
<P>
	Tabatha Renshaw, who became known as Baby Tabatha, suffered her  
injuries in January 1996, when she was 25 days old. 
</P>
<P>
	Her parents, Ronda Renshaw and Ronald Davis, say she slipped  
into a coma because of a viral infection, but authorities said the 
child had been violently shaken. 
</P>
<P>
	The parents fought for three years to maintain custody and keep  
the girl on life support. Finally, last week, they agreed to let 
her die. Physicians said that Tabatha had no chance of recovering 
and that life support would only prolong her dying. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Renshaw told authorities she had taken a nap with the child  
and found Tabatha had stopped breathing when she woke up. The 
father said he was in a different room at the time. Both told 
police they did not know how the baby had been harmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have not filed criminal charges against the parents.  
Douglas County Attorney Jim Jansen said prosecutors were waiting to 
examine autopsy results and other evidence in hopes of pinpointing 
which parent shook the child. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for agreeing last week to let Tabatha be taken off  
life support, the parents were allowed to be present for her final 
moments Wednesday night, said Regina Makaitis, the court-appointed 
special prosecutor for the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Bianchi, the attorney representing Ms. Renshaw, said his  
client is grieving for her daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that it's all hit her,'' Bianchi said. ``It's  
difficult for everyone involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a similar case in Pennsylvania, the parents of a severely  
brain-damaged 17-month-old boy are trying to keep that child alive. 
The child's brain injuries were the result of being shaken. 
</P>
<P>
	In that case, the child's father has been charged with attempted  
murder. Prosecutors have said that if the boy dies, they are likely 
to upgrade the charge to murder. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
