<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capital Planners OK WWII Monument </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A controversial World War II monument to be  
built on the green Mall between the Lincoln Memorial and the 
Washington Monument won 9-2 approval Thursday from the National 
Capital Planning Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote came after a series of witnesses denounced the plan as  
ugly and an obstacle to one of Washington's best known views. The 
witness list showed 26 against the plan and six supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the most beautiful city in the world and this is the  
ugliest damn thing I've ever seen,'' Rundy Hamblen, who served as a 
nurse during the invasion of France, told the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hamblen, 77, is a trauma nurse at D.C. General Hospital. In  
an interview after the vote, she said Washington doesn't need any 
more columns and slabs of marble -- she favors a single jet of 
water, half the height of the Washington Monument. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the plan said it would enhance the Mall.  
</P>
<P>
	The Rainbow Pool at the opposite end of the Reflecting Pool from  
the Lincoln Memorial would be rebuilt, with a memorial plaza around 
it. Ceremonial steps 170 feet wide, big enough to serve as an 
amphitheater for ceremonies, would lead into the plaza from 17th 
Street. Two memorial arches, commemorating the victories in the 
Atlantic and the Pacific, would be placed at the north and south 
entrances. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the vote Thursday was technically a preliminary  
approval of the site and design, no major changes seemed likely. 
The commission asked for more details on the landscaping and 
plaques, sculpture and inscriptions that will appear on the 
monument. 
</P>
<P>
	Final approval is needed from Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt,  
the city's Fine Arts Commission and from the planning commission 
itself. No timetable has been set. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
