<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ballet Theater Dances `Anastasia' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Arts and Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Anastasia,'' a three-act ballet about the  
murdered Russian royal family and the woman who claimed to be the 
daughter who survived the communist firing squad, is impressively 
danced for the first time by American Ballet Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Vivana Durante, the petite British Royal Ballet ballerina who is  
a guest with ABT at the Metropolitan Opera House this season, 
danced a delicate, affecting Anastasia, simultaneously dreamy in 
demeanor and precise in steps. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike 19th century full-evening ballets like ``The Sleeping  
Beauty,'' in which much of the dance roles are for villagers and 
court entertainers, the dancing in ``Anastasia,'' while not 
flamboyant, is done by the never-resting principals. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth MacMillan choreographed ``Anastasia'' for the Royal  
Ballet in 1971 and dedicated it to the company's founder, Ninette 
de Valois. The performance Monday was staged, from ballet notation, 
by Monica Parker, who works mainly on MacMillan ballets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anastasia'' was last danced here in 1972 by the British Royal  
Ballet. 
</P>
<P>
	Act 1 shows the royal family enjoying a day on the royal yacht  
in 1914. Victor Barbee and Christine Dunham danced the tall, 
elegant czar and czarina, tenderly loving to each other and their 
children. Ilone McHugh, Gillian Murphy and Oksana Konobeyeva 
portrayed the three older daughters, youthful and lovely in 
lace-edged white dresses, as they danced together and with sailors. 
Durante, smaller than the three, often danced alone. Chase Finlay 
danced their small brother and Ethan Brown danced Rasputin, the 
czarina's sinister confidant. 
</P>
<P>
	The happy atmosphere of Act 1 takes on a poignancy because of  
the audience's foreknowledge of the blood bath to come. Act 2 
depicts Anastasia's 1917 coming-out ball, with women wearing 
fan-shape headdresses and some traditionally Russian group dance 
patterns. 
</P>
<P>
	The last act is the most dramatic. The Anastasia ballerina must  
also be an actress. Wearing a gray dress and found on a hospital 
bed, she dances in many brief scenes of memory or hallucination -- 
with nurses, with distant relatives of the czar who reject her. 
There are quickly cut scenes of five people saving her on a cart, 
of a husband and baby who both die, of soldiers marching in, guns 
drawn. 
</P>
<P>
	With Ermanno Florio conducting, acts 1 and 2 are danced to  
Tchaikovsky, while the final act is set to music by Bohuslav 
Martinu. It ends with the main people in Anastasia's life entering 
while her bed moves around the stage in a circle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
